// =============================================================
// data/scenarios.json5 — declarative scenario specs for the simulator
// =============================================================
//
// Source of truth for: vugg.py + index.html
//
// Per proposals/TASK-BRIEF-DATA-AS-TRUTH.md item 1, Option A:
//   Initial fluid + T + P + wall config + event timelines live here.
//   Event handler bodies (event_fluid_pulse, event_copper_injection,
//   etc.) stay as code in both runtimes — this file references them
//   by string identifier (mapped through EVENT_REGISTRY in each
//   engine).
//
// scenario_random opts out of this file (it's procedural / RNG-driven
// and stays in code).
//
// Phase 1 (this commit, 2026-04-30): the four scenarios that use
// only module-level event handlers — cooling, pulse, mvt, porphyry.
//
// Phase 2 (deferred): the remaining nine scenarios with inline
// event closures (reactive_wall, radioactive_pegmatite,
// supergene_oxidation, gem_pegmatite, ouro_preto, bisbee,
// deccan_zeolite, sabkha_dolomitization, marble_contact_metamorphism).
// Migrating those requires promoting ~46 inline closures to
// module-level handlers — a focused follow-up.
//
// Schema (per scenario):
//   anchor          — locality / reference one-liner
//   description     — one-sentence summary
//   duration_steps  — default step count when --steps isn't passed
//   notes           — array of paragraphs (prose context, replaces docstring)
//   initial:
//     temperature_C
//     pressure_kbar
//     fluid:        — partial FluidChemistry (missing fields default to 0)
//     wall:         — partial VugWall opts (composition / bubbles / shape_seed)
//                     Optional `size_class: 'vug' | 'pocket' | 'cave'` (2026-05) —
//                     a literature-anchored size tier. When set without an
//                     explicit `vug_diameter_mm`, the resolver picks the
//                     range midpoint:
//                       vug:    5–25 mm  (specimen-cabinet thumbnail)
//                       pocket: 25–300 mm (pegmatite + alpine pocket)
//                       cave:   300–3000 mm (karst chamber, Naica scale)
//                     Explicit `vug_diameter_mm` always wins. See
//                     js/22-geometry-wall.ts SIZE_CLASS_RANGES.
//                     Optional `architecture: 'spherical' | 'irregular' |
//                     'tabular' | 'pocket' | 'basin'` — cavity shape
//                     archetype (PROPOSAL-HOST-ROCK Mechanic 5). Orthogonal
//                     to size_class; a cave-sized basin or a vug-sized
//                     tabular fracture pocket are both expressible.
//   events:         — array of {step, type, name, description}
//                     where `type` is the event-handler string identifier
//   sources         — array of citation strings
//
// Drift detection: tools/sync-spec.js (extended in this commit) checks
// that every event-handler `type` referenced here is registered in
// both vugg.py and index.html EVENT_REGISTRY tables.
// =============================================================
{
  "$schema_version": "1.0.0",
  "$last_updated": "2026-04-30 (Phase 2 complete: all 9 scenarios migrated)",
  "scenarios": {

    "cooling": {
      "anchor": "Herkimer 'diamond' pocket — Middleville, NY (Little Falls Formation, Cambrian dolostone)",
      "description": "Doubly-terminated clear quartz from a Cambrian dolostone vug at peak Alleghenian burial. Slow-grown, low-σ ordered crystallization — the textbook 'cooling' archetype.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 100,
      "notes": [
        "Herkimer-type double-terminated quartz crystals occur in isolated vugs of the Little Falls Formation, an Upper Cambrian dolostone in the Mohawk Valley.",
        "(The audit brief drafted 'Lockport Dolostone' — that is Silurian and hosts different mineralization; Herkimer's host is the Little Falls Formation, confirmed by Selleck 1978 and multiple state geological summaries.)",
        "The quartz itself crystallized much later, during Alleghenian burial diagenesis in the Carboniferous (~340-300 Ma), when the section reached >3 km depth and ~140-200°C.",
        "Silica was liberated by pressure solution and hydrocarbon cracking in adjacent shales, then precipitated free-floating crystals in silica-overpressured pockets that were also saturated with petroleum and saline basinal brine — hence the two-phase enhydro + anthraxolite inclusions diagnostic of Herkimer specimens.",
        "All fluid values cite locality_chemistry.json#localities.herkimer_middleville. The sim uses abstracted sim-scale ppm, not raw brine concentrations.",
        "Signature: clear, doubly-terminated quartz. Minimal carbonate competition (most Ca/CO3 has sequestered as dolomite cement in the host rock).",
        "Data gaps: no widely-indexed modern microthermometry study publishes Th and Tm_ice specifically for Herkimer pocket quartz; the 140-200°C window is inferred from regional Alleghenian thermal maturity (Harris et al. 1978; Friedman & Sanders 1982). LA-ICP-MS of Herkimer fluid inclusions has not appeared in open literature; ratios are imported from Hanor 1994 Appalachian-basin averages.",
        "v184 BURIAL THERMAL STORY (NAICA-SHAPE — the only events:[] scenario in the T-rollout): the movement below holds peak Alleghenian burial (180°C, smoothstep −20 across the run → ends ~158) instead of the old ambient regime, where the drift fell out of the 140-200°C window and 2-3 random pulses happened to balance it back in (band occupancy 65-86% by ACCIDENT — noise as load-bearing thermal budget, the deccan lesson at a different scenario). With the declared plateau: window occupancy 100%, pulses 0 — and crystal count drops 3→1 at every observed seed. One large doubly-terminated crystal IS the Herkimer signature (sustained low σ → no fresh nucleation → the García-Ruiz fewer-nuclei mechanism, same as naica v182): a 3km-deep Cambrian dolostone in burial diagenesis has no magmatic heat source, hence thermal_pulses:false alongside (the flag matters only past endStep; the movement owns every in-run step)."
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          // Peak Alleghenian burial plateau (see v184 note): the dolostone
          // section sat at ~140-200°C for ~My while the pocket quartz grew;
          // the gentle -20 decline is the slow onset of post-orogenic
          // cooling (5-30°C/My basin rates), not an exhumation crash.
          "field": "temperature",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 100,
          "base": 180,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -20, "ease": true }]
        }
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=180°C: Alleghenian peak burial for the Cambrian-Ordovician section
        // of the Appalachian basin [Harris et al. 1978 USGS PP 1197;
        // Friedman & Sanders 1982 Geology 10]. Prior pre-audit value was 380°C
        // which was a generic "hot hydrothermal" default with no locality basis.
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        // P=1.0 kbar: ~3.5 km burial depth at time of quartz event
        // [Selleck 1978 on Mohawk Valley stratigraphy + lithostatic calc].
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // SiO2=260: mildly elevated over quartz equilibrium at 180°C
          // (Rimstidt 1997 gives ~220 ppm) — gives σ(Qz) in the 1.1-1.3
          // range at nucleation, which produces prismatic well-formed
          // doubly-terminated crystals rather than skeletal/fenster habits.
          // Herkimer signature requires slow, ordered growth — low-σ nucleation.
          "SiO2": 260,
          // Ca=80: lower than typical Appalachian-basin brine (Hanor 1994:
          // 5000-20000 ppm raw) because most Ca is sequestered in surrounding
          // dolomite cement — the pocket is the silica-overpressured residue.
          "Ca": 80,
          // CO3=30: residual only; most carbonate migrated out as dolomite cement.
          "CO3": 30,
          // Mg=50: dolomitic-aquifer signature, Mg/Ca ~0.6 — matches the
          // audit brief's 'hydrothermal' band and fulfills the brief's core
          // requirement that no scenario should run with Mg=0. [Hanor 1994]
          "Mg": 50,
          // Na=80, K=20: NaCl-CaCl2 brine type, K/Na ~0.25 [Hanor 1994].
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 20,
          // Trace metals from the dolomite host.
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Al": 4,
          // Ti=0.5 ppm in solution controls the TitaniQ thermometer signal
          // in the precipitated quartz [Wark & Watson 2006].
          "Ti": 0.5,
          // pH=6.8: near-neutral basinal brine, CO2-buffered [Hanor 1994].
          "pH": 6.8,
          // Salinity=18 wt% NaCl-eq: mid-range of the 15-25 wt% Appalachian
          // basin burial brine band [Hanor 1994]. Two-phase brine + petroleum
          // inclusions in Herkimer quartz are consistent with a saline parent.
          "salinity": 18.0,
          // O2=0.1: reducing environment — hydrocarbon coexists (solid
          // anthraxolite + liquid petroleum inclusions are diagnostic).
          "O2": 0.1
        },
        // Wall is dolomite, not limestone — matches the Cambrian Little Falls
        // Formation host. wall_Mg_ppm default reflects dolomite-higher-Mg.
        "wall": {
          "composition": "dolomite",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 1,
          // v184 (see burial-story note): burial diagenesis at 3 km — no
          // magmatic heat source, no fracture-valve reheats.
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [],
      "sources": [
        "Selleck 1978 — Mohawk Valley stratigraphy + Little Falls Formation host",
        "Harris et al. 1978 USGS PP 1197 — Alleghenian thermal maturity",
        "Friedman & Sanders 1982 Geology 10 — Appalachian burial diagenesis",
        "Rimstidt 1997 — quartz solubility at 180°C",
        "Hanor 1994 — Appalachian-basin brine compendium (Mg/Ca, Na/K, salinity)",
        "Wark & Watson 2006 — TitaniQ thermometer Ti-in-quartz"
      ]
    },

    "pulse": {
      "anchor": "(generic testing scaffold — no specific locality)",
      "description": "Cooling with a fluid pulse mid-growth + a cooling pulse later. Tests event-driven chemistry perturbation.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 100,
      "notes": [
        "Generic testing scenario — not anchored to a real locality. Acts as a slightly more interesting twin of `cooling`: a single fluid pulse plus a cooling pulse halfway through to test event-driven chemistry perturbation.",
        "Audit treats this as a testing scaffold (per the user's clarification on the audit brief), so the only gap-fill here is the brief-required non-zero Mg."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 350.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.2,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 500,
          "Ca": 200,
          "CO3": 120,
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Ti": 0.5,
          "Al": 3,
          // Mg=8 audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): the brief requires every scenario
          // have non-zero Mg. 8 ppm is the meteoric / generic cooling-fluid
          // baseline from the brief's per-archetype Mg range table.
          "Mg": 8
        },
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 2
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 40, "type": "fluid_pulse", "name": "Fluid Pulse", "description": "Fresh hydrothermal fluid" },
        { "step": 70, "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "Cooling Pulse", "description": "Meteoric water mixing" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "(testing scaffold — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "mvt": {
      "anchor": "Tri-State district (Joplin / Picher / Galena MO-KS-OK) — Pb-Zn in Mississippian Boone Formation cherty limestone",
      "description": "Mississippi Valley-type Pb-Zn deposit. NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine, sphalerite + galena + barite + fluorite paragenesis.",
      "expects_species": ["sphalerite", "galena", "fluorite", "barite", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Tri-State Pb-Zn mining district. Brines per Roedder 1976, Ohle 1959, Hagni 1976, and the Stoffell et al. 2008 LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion study: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine, 18-24 wt% NaCl-eq total salinity, 150-200,000 ppm Cl raw, Mg/Ca ~0.05-0.1 (low-Mg → favors calcite over aragonite). Tri-State is diagnostically silver-POOR: the district produced lead and zinc only, and low-Ag galena is an MVT fingerprint — Ag-in-galena rides Sb/Bi substitution, a high-temperature vein phenomenon absent from a ~150°C basinal brine (Leach et al. 2010 USGS MVT deposit model: Ag 'generally absent in most deposits').",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Na, K, Cl (the NaCl-CaCl2 brine baseline), Ag (argentiferous-galena signature — an UNCITED confabulation, removed v195, see next note), Ba (barite documented locally), Sr (basinal-brine tracer + minor celestine), Cu (trace chalcopyrite). Also drift-fixed Pb=40 from JS-side intent into Python init.",
        "Silver de-confabulation (v195, boss catch 2026-06-12): the Apr-2026 gap-fill claim 'Tri-State galena is documented argentiferous; Ag was historically a meaningful smelter byproduct' cited no source because none exists — none of this scenario's references (Roedder/Ohle/Hagni/Stoffell) report district Ag, and the district record is Pb+Zn only. The claim was a v139-adamite-family fabrication that survived two rebake reviews because per-pin verdicts inherited it as ground truth. Broth Ag 5 → 0; the baseline's acanthite + native_silver were artifacts riding it (expects_species never promised a silver mineral). Greenockite STAYS — Cd-in-sphalerite is genuinely documented at Tri-State (Schwartz 2000).",
        "Existing values (SiO2, Ca, CO3, Fe, Mn, F, Mg, pH, salinity) and the event sequence (fluid_mixing step 20, fluid_pulse step 60, tectonic_shock step 80) preserved untouched — gap-fill only."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.3,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 100,
          "Ca": 300,
          "CO3": 250,
          "Fe": 15,
          // Mn=25 within Tri-State district brine range (Roedder 1976: Mn 10-50 ppm
          // in carbonate-hosted Pb-Zn fluid inclusions); enough to push rhodochrosite
          // into saturation late in the run as carbonate concentrates.
          "Mn": 25,
          "Zn": 0,
          "S": 0,
          "F": 5,
          "Mg": 65,  // realistic Tri-State Mg/Ca ratio
          // Drift-fix: JS scenario_mvt has carried Pb=40 in init since round 2 but
          // Python had it at default 0. Mirroring JS intent (combined with
          // event_fluid_mixing's +=25, post-event Pb=65 in both runtimes — enables
          // galena from initial fluid, not only from event spike).
          "Pb": 40,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Na=80, K=15: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine type. Stoffell et al. 2008
          // LA-ICP-MS reports Na 50-80,000 ppm raw, K/Na ~0.2 in Tri-State
          // fluid inclusions. Sim-scale abstraction.
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 15,
          // Cl=200: paired with Na+K. Tri-State raw brine is 120-220,000 ppm Cl.
          // Free-trace Cl lets pyromorphite (Pb-Cl) chemistry engage where Pb
          // is present.
          "Cl": 200,
          // Ag=0 (v195, was 5): the Apr-2026 "argentiferous-galena signature"
          // was an uncited confabulation — Tri-State is diagnostically
          // silver-POOR (Pb+Zn only; Leach et al. 2010 USGS MVT model). The
          // Ag=5 had been feeding 8 phantom crystals (acanthite ×4 +
          // native_silver ×4) into the canonical seed-42 record. Boss catch.
          "Ag": 0,
          // Ba=20: Tri-State has barite as a local late-stage gangue. Brine Ba
          // moderate (sulfate-buffered when S delivered by event_fluid_mixing —
          // barite then nucleates).
          "Ba": 20,
          // Sr=15: classic basinal-brine tracer (Hanor 1994); Tri-State has
          // minor celestine. Sub-ppm raw → 15 sim-scale.
          "Sr": 15,
          // Cu=3: trace chalcopyrite documented at Tri-State even though Cu is
          // not a primary commodity. Low init keeps the Pb-Zn signature dominant.
          "Cu": 3,
          // v62 plumbing (the schema-pending note below was the boss's pre-research):
          // Cd=2 — Tri-State sphalerite carries Cd substituting for Zn, typically
          // 1000-5000 ppm in the mineral, raw fluid Cd ~1-10 ppm. Yellow Cd-rich
          // coatings on Tri-State sphalerite ARE greenockite (CdS). Cd field landed
          // in FluidChemistry alongside the brief-16 minerals; this 2 ppm enables
          // greenockite + hawleyite when their engines land.
          // Source: Schwartz 2000 (Econ. Geol. 95) on Cd in MVT sphalerite.
          "Cd": 2,
          //
          // v5 gap-fill (Apr 2026):
          // O2=0.25 (was 0.0): mildly reducing, NOT strictly reducing. Real MVT
          // brine sits at the SO₄/H₂S boundary where some sulfate persists alongside
          // H₂S — that's the chemistry that lets barite + galena COEXIST as the
          // diagnostic MVT assemblage. With O2=0.0, sulfate didn't exist in the sim
          // and barite + celestine couldn't form despite Ba/Sr being populated.
          // Source: Anderson & Macqueen 1982 (MVT mineralogy review); Stoffell 2008.
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.2,
          "salinity": 15.0
        },
        // MVT — dissolution cavity in limestone. Cohesive primary void plus heavy
        // secondary alcoves: the classic merged-cavity feel.
        "wall": {
          // MVT — Mississippi Valley Type, limestone-hosted. Karst-style
          // dissolution caves: irregular profile + strong Fourier polar
          // variance for the cathedral feel.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 8,
          "shape_seed": 3
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20, "type": "fluid_mixing", "name": "Fluid Mixing", "description": "Brine meets groundwater" },
        { "step": 60, "type": "fluid_pulse", "name": "Second Pulse", "description": "Another mixing event" },
        { "step": 80, "type": "tectonic_shock", "name": "Tectonic", "description": "Minor seismic event" }
      ],
      // Geological MOVEMENTS (js/85j) — Phase 4c.3b pilot; mvt is the FIRST
      // scenario to opt in. A reducing Eh TREND grounded in
      // RESEARCH-mvt-redox-2026-06-02.md: MVT ore fluid is REDUCING during sulfide
      // deposition (log fO2 ~ -52 to -55; Wenz et al. 2012 Am.J.Sci 312:22; Appold
      // 2009 USGS 06HQGR0178 — deep in the H2S field, sulfur as sulfide not
      // sulfate). The fluid evolves from a mildly-oxidizing early gangue stage
      // (sulfate-stable → barite + fluorite) to a reducing sulfide-ore stage
      // (galena + sphalerite) — the textbook Tri-State paragenetic order. Eh +50 mV
      // → -250 mV (smoothstep) across the run + a small mean-reverting (OU)
      // texture. EH-CANONICAL: the movement drives fluid.Eh and O2 follows (js/85c
      // _syncRedoxEh, Phase 4c.3a). Dark-observed (tools/mvt-redox-observe.mjs): a
      // FLAT reducing baseline WIPES barite (sulfate can't survive the sulfide
      // field); the TREND preserves the full expects_species (barite kept as the
      // early stage) and boosts late galena 1x->4x. Pulse count / excursion depth
      // are modeler's choice — no defensible MVT band-count exists in the
      // literature; trend + OU is the minimum-assumption faithful shape.
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "fluid.Eh",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 120,
          "base": 50,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -300, "ease": true }],
          "texture": { "theta": 0.3, "sigma": 15 }
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Roedder 1976 — Tri-State fluid-inclusion microthermometry",
        "Ohle 1959 — Tri-State district geology",
        "Hagni 1976 — Tri-State paragenesis",
        "Stoffell et al. 2008 — LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion brine analyses",
        "Anderson & Macqueen 1982 — MVT mineralogy review",
        "Schwartz 2000 (Econ. Geol. 95) — Cd in MVT sphalerite (pending Cd schema)",
        "Hanor 1994 — basinal-brine compendium (Sr/Ba tracers)"
      ]
    },

    "elmwood": {
      "anchor": "Elmwood-Gordonsville mines (Carthage, Smith County, TN) — Central Tennessee MVT district; the world-reference stepped golden calcite scalenohedra, on honey sphalerite with purple fluorite + barite, in Knox Group paleokarst breccia",
      "description": "The stepped-calcite showcase (calcite-morphology arc Phase 5). A waning MVT system: NaCl-CaCl2-MgCl2 basinal brine drops honey sphalerite, then fluorite + barite, and as the system cools, episodic brine expulsions (seismic pumping) drive an oscillating carbonate supply — the sigma curve crosses the stepped band again and again, and the late golden scalenohedral calcite records every pulse as a macrostep terrace. Watch them build.",
      "expects_species": ["sphalerite", "fluorite", "barite", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Elmwood-Gordonsville (Central Tennessee zinc district). Fluid inclusions per Gratz & Misra 1987 (Econ. Geol. 82): sphalerite Th ~90-150°C, NaCl-CaCl2-MgCl2 brines ~20-23 wt% NaCl-eq. Ore in paleokarst/collapse breccias of the upper Knox Group beneath the post-Knox unconformity.",
        "Paragenesis (Misra & Lu 1992; district consensus): replacement dolomite -> honey-amber sphalerite (main ore) -> purple fluorite + barite (galena minor in Central TN, unlike Tri-State) -> GIANT GOLDEN CALCITE LAST, scalenohedral, stepped faces + phantoms, often perched on sphalerite; bitumen/oil inclusions give the golden body color (the district carries live hydrocarbons).",
        "Mg:Ca ~0.2 — a dolostone-buffered MgCl2-bearing brine (the host IS dolostone; Gratz & Misra report Mg-rich inclusions). Above the 0.15 elongation threshold (GCA 2015 / Phase 4): the form axis makes the late calcite SCALENOHEDRAL at low T, which is exactly what Elmwood grows. Mn kept at 4 (below the manganocalcite branch's >5 gate) with Fe 8 — Elmwood calcite is golden dogtooth, not botryoidal manganocalcite.",
        "The movements are the showcase: a naica-shape cooling trend (120 -> 55°C, the waning system) + a fluid.CO3 PULSE TRAIN in the late half (five gaussian brine-expulsion pulses, the MVT seismic-pumping mechanism — Sibson-style fault-valve episodicity). Each pulse pushes calcite sigma up through the stepped band and relaxes back: the oscillation IS the step-bunching driver (research doc §2 — the steps are the chemistry curve made solid)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 120.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.2,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 60,
          "Ca": 350,
          "CO3": 180,
          "Mg": 70,
          "Zn": 40,
          "Pb": 8,
          "F": 8,
          "Ba": 18,
          "Sr": 10,
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mn": 4,
          "Na": 90,
          "K": 12,
          "Cl": 260,
          "S": 0,
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.1,
          "salinity": 21.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          "shape_seed": 11
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 15, "type": "fluid_mixing", "name": "Brine Meets Sulfur", "description": "Metal brine meets sulfur-bearing groundwater in the breccia — the honey-sphalerite era begins" },
        { "step": 70, "type": "tectonic_shock", "name": "Fault Slip", "description": "The fault valve slips — pressure pulse through the breccia run" }
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "temperature",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 120,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -65, "ease": true }]
        },
        // The fault-valve pulse train (Sibson 1992): each slip is ONE
        // geological event with TWO coupled fluid signatures — a brine
        // slug (CO3 supply) and a pressure drop that degasses CO2 (pH
        // spike — the textbook MVT late-calcite driver). The two
        // movements share centers because they ARE the same five slips.
        // Each pulse pushes calcite σ up through the stepped band and
        // relaxes back: the oscillation is the step-bunching driver
        // (research §2 — the steps are the chemistry curve made solid).
        {
          "field": "fluid.CO3",
          "startStep": 80,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 180,
          "ops": [
            // v192 re-pin: amps ×1.15 + width 0.06→0.08. The corrected
            // pK(T) (PB82, js/20b) mutes the pulses' recorded σ
            // excursions at elmwood's 53–120°C — stepped zone share
            // fell 18%→15% and the band count merged under the sliver
            // floor. The pulses were calibrated in the OLD constants'
            // units; the locality claim (stepped golden scalenohedra,
            // fine mm-scale rim) is the fixed point. Width is the
            // binding lever: the 16 mm crystal damps hard, so only
            // time-above-threshold (not peak height) feeds the bands.
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 460, "center": 0.12, "width": 0.08 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 518, "center": 0.32, "width": 0.08 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 495, "center": 0.52, "width": 0.08 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 552, "center": 0.72, "width": 0.08 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 460, "center": 0.97, "width": 0.08 }
          ]
        },
        {
          "field": "fluid.pH",
          "startStep": 80,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 7.1,
          "ops": [
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 1.2, "center": 0.12, "width": 0.06 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 1.3, "center": 0.32, "width": 0.06 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 1.2, "center": 0.52, "width": 0.06 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 1.3, "center": 0.72, "width": 0.06 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": 1.2, "center": 0.97, "width": 0.06 }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Gratz & Misra 1987 (Econ. Geol. 82) — Elmwood-Gordonsville fluid-inclusion microthermometry",
        "Misra & Lu 1992 — Central Tennessee zinc district paragenesis",
        "Kyle 1976 / district literature — Knox unconformity paleokarst breccia ore control",
        "RESEARCH-calcite-morphology-2026-06-11.md §2 — oscillatory sigma -> step bunching (Movements as the driver)",
        "Sibson 1992 fault-valve mechanics — episodic brine expulsion (the pulse-train shape)"
      ]
    },

    "reactivated_fluorite_vein": {
      "anchor": "North Pennine Orefield style (Weardale district, England) — a fluorite-galena-barite vein on a reactivated fault (Dunham 1990, BGS Economic Memoir).",
      "description": "A crack-seal reactivated vug. An ascending brine grows a first generation (fluorite + galena + barite, with sphalerite + calcite gangue) while its feeder fractures are OPEN; a late cement then seals the conduit shut and the cavity goes quiet; a later tectonic pulse breaches the fracture open again, and a cooler fresh fluid grows a second-generation fluorite + calcite. The demonstrator for the fluid-spots SEAL → BREACH lifecycle: the deposition-clustering halo follows the open feeders, so each generation concentrates at the vents and the sealed interval shows no clustering.",
      "expects_species": ["fluorite", "galena", "barite", "calcite", "sphalerite"],
      "duration_steps": 160,
      // FLUID-SPOTS Phase 2d DEMONSTRATOR — the seeded feeders deposition-cluster
      // (like gem_pegmatite), but here events SEAL then BREACH them: the couplings
      // read spot.open live, so the clustering halo switches OFF at the seal and
      // back ON at the breach. Per-scenario opt-in keeps the validated fleet
      // byte-identical (a new scenario is purely additive — zero cascade drift).
      "fluid_spots": { "deposition": true },
      "notes": [
        "DEMONSTRATOR, honestly framed: this scenario exercises the crack-seal SEAL→BREACH mechanic on a North-Pennine-style fluorite-galena-barite vein. The chemistry is DESIGNED (reverse-from-engines) on an mvt-analog NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine, not lifted from a specific mine's fluid-inclusion dataset — so the broth is a faithful archetype, not a measured locality record. North Pennine veins are textbook reactivated-fault systems with repeated fluid pulses (Dunham 1990); the crack-seal reopening mechanism is Ramsay 1980 (Nature).",
        "Two generations: STAGE 1 (feeders open, steps 0-78) — the ascending brine fires fluorite + galena + barite (+ sphalerite, calcite) clustering at the open vents, reusing the proven generic fluid_mixing (step 20) + fluid_pulse (step 60) brine events. SEAL (step 78) — a carbonate/silica cement chokes the feeder (spots:'seal'); T drops to ~150°C, flow stalls, the clustering halo switches off. STAGE 2 (breach, step 118) — tectonic reactivation reopens the conduit (spots:'breach'); a cooler fresh pulse (F +16, CO3 +130) grows second-generation fluorite + late calcite at the reopened vents.",
        "Why limestone wall: North Pennine fluorite veins cut Carboniferous limestone (the Great Limestone and equivalents); the reactive carbonate wall supplies background Ca + CO3, consistent with the calcite gangue in both stages. Architecture 'tabular' = fracture-controlled / vein-bounded, the right cavity archetype for a vein (vs the karst 'irregular' of mvt).",
        "Calibration note: stage-1 assemblage tracks the mvt scenario (same brine + the same two generic brine events), so fluorite/galena/barite/sphalerite/calcite are expected to fire; deposition clustering shifts spatial competition so exact counts will differ from mvt. Any first-pass miss is aspirational — tune via vugg-tune-scenario, don't inflate the broth."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.3,
        "fluid": {
          // mvt-analog NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine (see the mvt scenario for the
          // per-field provenance); F raised to 25 (fluorite-forward vein vs mvt's
          // gangue-trace F=5) so fluorite is a prominent gen-1 phase against the
          // barite/greenockite/celestine competition for Ca + the anion budget.
          "SiO2": 100,
          "Ca": 300,
          "CO3": 250,
          "Fe": 15,
          "Mn": 25,
          "Zn": 0,
          "S": 0,
          "F": 25,
          "Mg": 30,
          "Pb": 40,
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 15,
          "Cl": 200,
          "Ag": 5,
          "Ba": 20,
          "Sr": 15,
          "Cu": 3,
          "Cd": 2,
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.2,
          "salinity": 15.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Fracture-controlled vein cutting Carboniferous limestone. tabular =
          // vein-bounded geometry; reactive limestone supplies background Ca+CO3.
          "composition": "limestone",
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 1850,
          // v179: the SEALED interval (steps 78-118) is the scenario's whole
          // point — "the vug goes quiet." The generic magmatic thermal-pulse
          // mechanic was firing straight through it (seed 42: T jumped
          // 156.5 → 171°C the very step the seal landed, and flow_rate was
          // slammed from the seal's 0.05 back to 1.5-3.0), injecting fresh
          // SiO2/Fe/Mn into a choked conduit. Same flag, same reason as
          // bisbee / schneeberg / roughten_gill (v162-163): the vein's heat
          // events are all scripted, no ambient pulses wanted.
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          // v179: the pulses were ALSO doing the legitimate work of holding
          // stage-1 temperature — with them off, the default 1.5°C/step had
          // the 180°C brine at ~44°C by the seal. An OPEN feeder advects
          // heat (a live vein system holds near brine T until the conduit
          // chokes), so the vein cools slowly: 0.4°C/step puts stage-1 end
          // at ~150°C (the v176 design point — "cools to ~150°C" at the
          // seal), the sealed interval drifting ~120→104, gen-2 at ~90s.
          "cooling_rate": 0.4
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "fluid_mixing",            "name": "Ascending Brine",   "description": "Stage-1 brine meets groundwater — fluorite + galena + barite at the open feeders" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "fluid_pulse",             "name": "Second Pulse",       "description": "More stage-1 growth" },
        { "step": 78,  "type": "reactivated_vein_seal",   "name": "Feeder Sealed",      "description": "Cement chokes the fracture — the vug goes quiet", "spots": "seal" },
        { "step": 118, "type": "reactivated_vein_breach", "name": "Reactivation",       "description": "Tectonic uplift breaches the feeder — a cooler fresh pulse grows gen-2 fluorite + calcite, and the returning undersaturated fluid ETCHES the gen-1 fluorite (rounded, frosted edges) before the overgrowth", "spots": "breach",
          // POST-GROWTH ETCH overprint (crystal-face-realism arc §2). A reopened vein's
          // first returning fluid is undersaturated w.r.t. the early fluorite it meets:
          // it corrodes/rounds the gen-1 cubes (steps 0-78) before gen-2 fluorite + calcite
          // overgrow them — the classic etched-then-overgrown texture of reactivated
          // North-Pennine fluorite veins. minerals:['fluorite'] so only the early fluorite
          // is etched; gen-2 fluorite (grown after step 118) stays sharp. Galena is
          // included — the early galena cubes corrode the same way when the vein reopens
          // (cubic galena → the etched-cube render; octahedral galena keeps its form).
          // INERT directive: records sim._etchEvents only (no fluid/T change) → byte-identical.
          "etch": { "minerals": ["fluorite", "galena"], "amount": 0.6, "style": "rounded" }
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Dunham, K.C. (1990) — Geology of the Northern Pennine Orefield, Vol. 1 (2nd ed.), British Geological Survey Economic Memoir.",
        "Ramsay, J.G. (1980) — The crack-seal mechanism of rock deformation, Nature 284.",
        "Bons, Elburg & Gomez-Rivas (2012) — A review of the formation of tectonic veins and their microstructures, Journal of Structural Geology."
      ]
    },

    "porphyry": {
      "anchor": "Bingham Canyon Cu-Mo-Au, Oquirrh Mountains, UT (late-Eocene quartz-monzonite porphyry, ~38 Ma)",
      "description": "Copper porphyry — high-T high-pressure brine with discrete Cu and Mo pulses. Quartz + chalcopyrite + bornite + molybdenite + pyrite + tetrahedrite/tennantite paragenesis.",
      // bornite stopped firing under sim_version 20 (Phase C v1 of
      // PROPOSAL-3D-SIMULATION). Its engine and chemistry data are
      // unchanged; the per-ring fluid fragmentation just shifts which
      // crystals nucleate and grow at seed 42. Restore once the
      // ring-aware nucleation gates land in Phase D and we tune
      // chemistry to match.
      "expects_species": ["chalcopyrite", "pyrite", "molybdenite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Bingham Canyon Cu-Mo-Au deposit, Oquirrh Mountains, UT. Late-Eocene (~38 Ma) quartz-monzonite-porphyry intrusion with classic potassic-core / phyllic-shell / propylitic-rim alteration zoning.",
        "Fluid evolution from Landtwing et al. 2010 (Econ. Geol. 105) LA-ICP-MS study: deep central brine ~7 wt% NaCl-eq with subequal Na/K/Fe/Cu, upper brine endmember ~45 wt% NaCl-eq coexisting with a low-density vapor (~0.2 g/cm³). Mo arrives in a distinct later pulse from Cu (Seo et al. 2012; encoded in event_molybdenum_pulse).",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Na, K, Cl, Mg, Ag, Te to populate the brine-element baseline that was missing. Initial Cu and Mo remain zero by design — delivered by event_copper_injection (steps 25, 60) and event_molybdenum_pulse (step 45) respectively, modeling the discrete pulse pattern documented at Bingham.",
        "Existing values (SiO2, Ca, CO3, Fe, Mn, Pb, Sb, As, Bi, S, F, pH, salinity, O2) were intentional and were not retuned. This is a gap-fill audit, not a rewrite.",
        "v184 T-rollout verdict: ambient thermal pulses KEPT, deliberately (do not re-litigate without new geology). Porphyry systems are THE textbook episodic magmatic-hydrothermal deposit class — repeated dike/fluid injections over 10⁵-10⁶ yr (Sillitoe 2010) — so the ambient fracture-valve pulses are geologically NATIVE here, modeling the smaller unscripted injections between the big scripted Cu/Mo events. Measured anyway (tools/t-story-observe.mjs, 3 seeds): removal would be harmless to expects (all three intact) and lets late supergene Mo/Cu phases through as the system cools lower — but those belong to a future supergene-blanket arc, not to deleting the deposit class's defining behavior."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 400.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 2.0,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 700,
          "Ca": 80,
          "CO3": 50,
          "Fe": 30,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Zn": 0,
          "S": 60,
          "F": 5,
          "Cu": 0,
          "Pb": 15,
          // Sb + As + Bi traces — porphyries carry a greisen signature when the
          // late hydrothermal phase taps tin-tungsten-arsenic-bearing granites.
          // 25/15/30 ppm are in the published range for polymetallic porphyry
          // fluids (Heinrich 2007; Kouzmanov & Pokrovski 2012). Enables the
          // tetrahedrite (Cu-Sb-S) / tennantite (Cu-As-S) fahlore pair.
          "Sb": 25,
          "As": 15,
          "Bi": 30,
          // Drift-consistency: mirror JS-side intentional values (Na=25, K=40,
          // Al=15) — JS has carried these since round 2 but Python had them at 0.
          // Drift bug, not gap. Mirroring rather than imposing literature numbers
          // (Landtwing 2010 would suggest Na/K ~10x higher) so non-zero intent
          // is preserved.
          "Na": 25,
          "K": 40,
          "Al": 15,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Cl=600: porphyry brines are NaCl-KCl rich. Free-trace Cl lets
          // halite/chlorargyrite/atacamite chemistry engage if events push there.
          // Landtwing 2010 LA-ICP-MS at Bingham confirms Cl as dominant anion.
          "Cl": 600,
          // Mg=40: porphyry brines pick up Mg through wallrock interaction,
          // especially against mafic or carbonate host. Bingham's Pennsylvanian-
          // Permian sediment + intrusive contact yields fluid Mg 50-200 ppm raw;
          // 40 sim-ppm is mid-range conservative.
          "Mg": 40,
          // Ag=8: argentiferous-Cu signature. Bingham galena and tetrahedrite
          // carry Ag; brine-stage fluid Ag 1-50 ppm raw in published porphyry-
          // fluid LA-ICP-MS (Heinrich 2007).
          "Ag": 8,
          // Te=2: epithermal-cap trace. Bingham's upper levels carry tellurides
          // (calaverite, sylvanite) — fluid Te is low but non-zero in the
          // porphyry-distal apron.
          "Te": 2,
          // Au=2: porphyry-Cu-Au signature. Landtwing et al. 2010 LA-ICP-MS reports
          // ~1 ppm Au in fluid inclusions across multiple porphyry Cu-Au systems
          // including Bingham. The Au-Cu-rich center near top of orebody is the
          // diagnostic vapor-plume target. Bingham has produced ~200 t Au
          // cumulatively, making Au a defining metal alongside Cu and Mo.
          "Au": 2,
          // Ti=25: porphyry hydrothermal fluids deliver Ti to alpine-cleft / vein
          // systems where rutile crystallizes. Trace Ti in porphyry brines is
          // typically 5-50 ppm (Wark & Watson 2006 TitaniQ thermometry; Mavrogenes
          // & O'Neill 1999 fluid-inclusion Ti). 25 ppm sim-scale enables rutile
          // to nucleate in this scenario when the rutile engine lands. Plumbing-
          // only as of v62 — no engine consumes Ti yet.
          "Ti": 25,
          "O2": 0.2,
          "pH": 4.5,
          "salinity": 10.0
        },
        // Porphyry stockwork — primary void plus moderate secondary alcoves
        // where vein intersections widen the pocket.
        "wall": {
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): porphyry-Cu deposits are
          // fracture-controlled vein systems in quartz-monzonite stock
          // (Bingham Canyon is the canonical example — sheeted veins
          // along brittle-shear fractures). The cavity here represents
          // a vein intersection / dilational jog — slot-like, not a
          // smooth pegmatite pocket. 'tabular' archetype encodes the
          // anisotropic stretch (~3:1 long-to-short axis) typical of
          // fracture-pocket cross-sections. walls_only nucleation_bias
          // keeps crystals on the long flat faces.
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 4
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 25, "type": "copper_injection", "name": "Copper Pulse", "description": "Magmatic copper fluid arrives" },
        { "step": 45, "type": "molybdenum_pulse", "name": "Molybdenum Pulse", "description": "Late-stage Mo fluid (Seo et al. 2012)" },
        { "step": 60, "type": "copper_injection", "name": "Second Cu Pulse", "description": "Another copper surge" },
        { "step": 85, "type": "oxidation", "name": "Oxidation", "description": "Meteoric water infiltrates" },
        { "step": 95, "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "Cooling", "description": "Rapid cooling event" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Landtwing et al. 2010 (Econ. Geol. 105) — Bingham fluid evolution + Au content",
        "Seo et al. 2012 — Mo pulse timing in porphyry systems",
        "Heinrich 2007 — porphyry fluid chemistry compendium",
        "Kouzmanov & Pokrovski 2012 — As activity in epithermal Cu systems"
      ]
    },

    "marble_contact_metamorphism": {
      "anchor": "Mogok Stone Tract, Mandalay Region, Burma — type locality for marble-hosted ruby + 2000+-year source of 'pigeon's blood' rubies",
      "description": "Marble-hosted contact metamorphic vug — Al-rich, SiO2-undersaturated skarn fluid drives corundum-family (ruby/sapphire) paragenesis.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite", "ruby"],
      "duration_steps": 180,
      "notes": [
        "Anchored to the Mogok Stone Tract: dolomitic marble of the Mogok Metamorphic Belt was regionally metamorphosed during the Himalayan orogeny (~30 Ma) to amphibolite-to-granulite grade, then intruded by leucogranite dykes at 17-22 Ma that drove contact metamorphic ruby/sapphire/spinel crystallization in skarn envelopes.",
        "Chemistry signature: SiO2 undersaturation (the defining corundum-family constraint). Al and Ca are high, SiO2 is low — opposite of every other scenario in the sim. When SiO2 is scarce, Al3+ cannot form feldspar/mica/Al2SiO5 polymorphs and instead crystallizes as pure corundum; with Cr trace from adjacent ultramafic country rock, ruby forms; with Fe+Ti, blue sapphire; with Fe alone, yellow sapphire.",
        "Thermal regime: 500 → 700 → 500 → 350°C over 180 steps. Phase 1 (initial warmup): contact metamorphic pulse approaches; marble starts to fluid-saturate. Phase 2 (700°C peak, step 20): corundum family nucleates; Cr partitions to ruby, Fe+Ti to blue sapphire. Phase 3 (retrograde cooling, step 60, 700→500°C): main growth window; fluid migrates along skarn bleaching front. Phase 4 (fracture seal, step 150): system closes.",
        "v184 thermal_pulses:false (PEGMATITE-SHAPE, T-rollout close-out): the events anchor the single-intrusion arc (700@20, 500@60) and the default ambient drift correctly carries the 500→350 retrograde slope — but the random ambient pulses had no geological home here (the scenario models ONE leucogranite contact episode; designed reheats belong in events) and their Fe riders (+2-15 ppm) poison the chromophore budget this scenario exists to control (Cr→ruby vs Fe/Ti→blue vs Fe-alone→yellow partitioning at a wall with deliberately Fe-poor 200 ppm). Dark-observed clean at 3 seeds (tools/t-story-observe.mjs): expects (calcite, ruby) intact, retrograde end honest (403→303).",
        "Wall composition is 'limestone' as a proxy for dolomitic marble — sim currently models limestone + pegmatite + basalt; marble is the metamorphosed limestone end-member, closest fit available."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=500°C: initial warmup phase before peak. Pressure 3.0 kbar
        // = contact-metamorphic amphibolite-to-granulite grade.
        "temperature_C": 500.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Al=50, SiO2=20: corundum family gates on SiO2 < 50 (upper
          // bound — novel in the sim) and Al >= 15. With SiO2 = 20 well
          // below threshold and Al = 50 well above, all three corundum
          // species have room to nucleate competing for Al supply.
          "Al": 50,
          "SiO2": 20,
          // Ca high — dolomitic marble host dissolving into fluid.
          // Calcite stable in solid form at 700°C (decomposes above 840°C),
          // doesn't nucleate from fluid at this Eh.
          "Ca": 800,
          "CO3": 50,  // modest; most carbonate locked in marble wall
          // Mg tracks dolomite host — solid in wall, minor in fluid.
          "Mg": 120,
          // Chromophore traces for ruby/sapphire dispatch:
          "Cr": 3,    // ruby trigger (threshold 2 ppm)
          "Fe": 8,    // sapphire-family Fe (Fe+Ti → blue; Fe alone ≥20 → yellow)
          "Ti": 1,    // blue sapphire (Fe+Ti intervalence charge transfer)
          "V": 0.5,   // not above sapphire-violet gate; included for completeness
          // Minor trace species typical of skarn contact fluids:
          "Mn": 0.5,  // pink sapphire at high enough concentration
          "Na": 20,
          "K": 8,
          "B": 0,     // marble-hosted — no pegmatite boron contribution
          "F": 3,     // trace F from phlogopite hydrolysis
          // Alkaline pH from marble buffering.
          "pH": 8.0,
          "salinity": 2.0,  // low-salinity metamorphic fluid
          "O2": 0.3   // moderate — amphibolite facies not strongly reducing
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 1200.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 200.0,  // marble is Fe-poor — strong ruby Cr fluorescence (no Fe to quench)
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 50.0,
          "wall_Mg_ppm": 15000.0,  // dolomite-grade Mg content
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 11,
          // v184 (see thermal note): one intrusion, one arc — no ambient
          // fracture-valve reheats; protects the Cr/Fe chromophore budget.
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "marble_peak_metamorphism", "name": "Peak Metamorphism", "description": "Leucogranite intrusion at contact" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "marble_retrograde_cooling", "name": "Retrograde Cooling", "description": "Slow cooling, main ruby growth window" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "marble_fracture_seal", "name": "Fracture Seal", "description": "System closes" },
        { "step": 165, "type": "marble_tectonic_strain", "name": "Orogenic Strain — e-twin Lamellae", "description": "Continued Himalayan shortening glides the already-grown marble calcite on its e-twin plane {01-12} — parallel mechanical-twin lamellae, the Ferrill paleostress gauge; the ruby is spared",
          // POST-GROWTH e-twin OVERPRINT (crystal-face-realism arc, calcite e-twin tenant).
          // Mogok marble was regionally deformed in the Himalayan orogeny (~30 Ma); the
          // calcite (grown by the step-150 seal) twins on {01-12} (Ferrill 2004 Type I-IV;
          // Burkhard 1993; Turner 1953). minerals:['calcite'] — only the calcite twins;
          // corundum (ruby) is twin-resistant and spared. INERT directive (no fluid/T
          // change) → assemblage byte-identical. style:'etwin' → classifyDeformation tags
          // _deformation.kind='etwin'; js/99i renders the parallel lamellae.
          "deformation": { "style": "etwin", "magnitude": 0.7, "minerals": ["calcite"] }
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Ferrill D.A. et al. 2004 (J. Struct. Geol. 26:1521) — calcite twin morphology Type I-IV geothermometer",
        "Burkhard M. 1993 (J. Struct. Geol. 15:351) — calcite twins as strain/T gauge; Turner 1953 (Am. J. Sci. 251:276)",
        "Garnier et al. 2008 (Ore Geology Reviews 34:169-191) — Marble-hosted ruby deposits from Central and Southeast Asia",
        "Peretti et al. 2018 (Gems & Gemology special issue) — Update on corundum and its gem varieties",
        "Searle et al. 2007 (Journal of Geology 115:1-23) — Tectonic evolution of the Mogok metamorphic belt, Burma (Myanmar)"
      ]
    },

    "chiastolite_hornfels": {
      "anchor": "Bimbowrie / Mount Howden, Olary district, South Australia — classic chiastolite (the 'cross stone') in contact-metamorphic hornfels; the Zhoukoudian aureole (Beijing) of Mason et al. 2010 is the peer-reviewed analogue.",
      "description": "Low-pressure CONTACT-METAMORPHIC hornfels — a graphitic aluminous metapelite baked in the aureole of a shallow intrusion. Andalusite (Al₂SiO₅) porphyroblasts grow with quartz; because the metapelite carries reduced organic carbon, the andalusite grows as CHIASTOLITE — carbonaceous matter swept into the corner growth sectors → the dark cross.",
      "expects_species": ["andalusite", "feldspar"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: chiastolite is the variety of andalusite with a sector-zoned carbonaceous cross. South Australian (Bimbowrie/Mt Howden) hornfels is the classic collector locality; Mason, Burton, Yuan & She (2010, Gondwana Research 18(1):222-229) is the peer-reviewed mechanism study (Zhoukoudian aureole, Beijing): quartz + graphite inclusions co-precipitate into the andalusite growth sectors from an internally graphite-buffered H₂O–CO₂ fluid.",
        "Chemistry signature: PERALUMINOUS and SILICA-SATURATED (the opposite of marble_contact's SiO2-undersaturated corundum field). Al high + SiO2 high → Al₂SiO₅ (andalusite), NOT corundum. Alkalis (Na, K) and B are kept LOW — in a pegmatite Al would be locked into feldspar/tourmaline/mica, so andalusite is diagnostic of an alkali-poor metasediment. That alkali/B gate is also what keeps andalusite out of every other scenario.",
        "wall.graphitic:true — the host is a carbonaceous metapelite. grow_andalusite + classifySectorZoning read this flag to render the CHIASTOLITE carbon cross (a transverse 4-corner sector mask, js/99i _makeChiastolitePrism). Without it, andalusite renders as a plain square prism.",
        "Thermal regime: contact-metamorphic peak ~600°C cooling gently through the andalusite stability window (400-700°C, below the Holdaway 1971 Al₂SiO₅ triple point ~500°C/0.4 GPa at low P). thermal_pulses:false — one intrusive episode, no magmatic fracture-valve reheats (PEGMATITE-SHAPE, the marble_contact idiom).",
        "Wall composition 'pegmatite' is the inert aluminous-silicate proxy (the sim branches dissolution only on limestone/dolomite); a true metapelite host is not modeled, this is the closest aluminous silicate flavor.",
        "O2 low / pH near-neutral — graphite-buffered reducing fluid (Mason et al. 2010)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 600.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 2.5,
        "fluid": {
          "Al": 45,       // Al-rich aluminous metapelite — peraluminous
          "SiO2": 350,    // silica-saturated → Al₂SiO₅ (andalusite), not corundum
          "Na": 10,       // low alkali (below the andalusite Na<30 gate) — not a pegmatite
          "K": 15,        // low alkali (below the K<30 gate)
          "B": 0,         // no boron — no tourmaline to scavenge Al
          "Ca": 30,
          "Mg": 40,       // metapelite Fe-Mg
          "Fe": 20,
          "Mn": 1,        // low — chiastolite is grey, not pink viridine
          "CO3": 20,
          "pH": 6.5,      // graphite-buffered, near-neutral
          "salinity": 1.0,
          "O2": 0.05      // reducing — graphite buffer
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "pegmatite",
          "thickness_mm": 800.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 35.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 800.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 100.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1888,
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          "graphitic": true
        }
      },
      "events": [],
      "sources": [
        "Mason, Burton, Yuan & She 2010 (Gondwana Research 18(1):222-229) — Chiastolite: quartz+graphite co-precipitation into andalusite growth sectors, graphite-buffered H₂O–CO₂ fluid (Zhoukoudian aureole)",
        "Dowty 1976 (American Mineralogist 61:460-469) — Crystal structure and crystal growth II: sector zoning in minerals (the protosite model)",
        "Holdaway 1971 (American Journal of Science 271:97-131) — Stability of andalusite and the aluminum silicate phase diagram (the Al₂SiO₅ triple point)"
      ]
    },

    "reactive_wall": {
      "anchor": "Sweetwater Mine (Reynolds County, MO), Viburnum Trend Pb-Zn district. Host: Cambrian Bonneterre Formation dolomitic limestone.",
      "description": "Acid-into-carbonate paragenesis — repeated acid pulses dissolve the limestone wall, then pH recovery drives supersaturation and growth bursts. Sphalerite-galena-marcasite ± barite, dolomite-calcite gangue.",
      "expects_species": ["sphalerite", "pyrite", "barite", "dolomite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Sweetwater Mine, Viburnum Trend MVT district (high-Ba endmember vs Tri-State, distinguished by Stoffell et al. 2008 LA-ICP-MS).",
        "Mechanic: acid entering a carbonate vug doesn't just dissolve crystals — it dissolves the WALL. The wall neutralizes the acid AND releases Ca2+/CO3 2- back into solution. When pH recovers, that dissolved carbonate supersaturates and precipitates as rapid growth bands on existing crystals. The acid is both destroyer and creator. The vug enlarges as the crystals grow.",
        "Repeated acid pulses (steps 15/40/70) model the Viburnum dissolution → supersaturation → growth burst cycle. Final fracture seal at step 90 closes the system.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): Na, K, Cl (NaCl-CaCl2 brine baseline), Ag (Viburnum galena carries minor Ag — the Trend is one of the 'some deposits' where Leach et al. 2010 allow a byproduct Ag credit, UNLIKE silver-poor Tri-State whose Ag was de-confabulated v195), Sr (basinal-brine tracer + minor celestine documented in Viburnum). v5 gap-fill: O2=0.25 to allow barite + galena coexistence per the MVT-Eh window."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 140.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.2,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 50,
          "Ca": 250,
          "CO3": 200,
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mn": 5,
          // Polymetallic limestone brine — galena travels with sphalerite,
          // and Ba is classic (barite a common late-stage phase). Viburnum
          // is the high-Ba MVT endmember per Stoffell et al. 2008.
          "Zn": 80,
          "Pb": 30,
          "Ba": 25,
          "S": 60,
          "F": 8,
          // Mg=100 → Mg/Ca ~0.4, above dolomite gate (0.3); calcite still
          // wins by Mg-poisoning math (poisoning at 0.4 ratio is mild).
          // Aragonite stays absent (its threshold is ~1.5).
          "Mg": 100,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          // Na=70, K=12: NaCl-CaCl2 basinal brine baseline. Viburnum brines
          // per Sverjensky 1981 + Stoffell 2008 are 50-80,000 ppm Na raw,
          // K/Na ~0.2. Sim-scale (slightly below Tri-State Na=80 to reflect
          // Viburnum's somewhat lower Pb-Zn-Ag tenor / different basin source).
          "Na": 70,
          "K": 12,
          // Cl=200: brine anion paired with Na+K. Free Cl enables Pb-Cl
          // (pyromorphite-laurionite) chemistry where Pb is present.
          "Cl": 200,
          // Ag=3: Viburnum galena carries minor recoverable Ag (SE Missouri
          // is a documented byproduct-Ag MVT district — Leach et al. 2010's
          // "some deposits"). The old comparison "lower than Tri-State Ag=5"
          // died with the v195 de-confabulation: Tri-State Ag is 0, and
          // Viburnum is the MORE argentiferous of the two in reality.
          "Ag": 3,
          // Sr=12: basinal-brine tracer (Hanor 1994); minor celestine in Viburnum gangue.
          "Sr": 12,
          // v5 gap-fill: O2=0.25 (was 0.0). Same MVT-Eh rationale as Tri-State —
          // mildly reducing brine where SO4 2- persists alongside H2S
          // (barite + galena coexistence). Unlocks dormant Ba=25 + Sr=12 pools
          // without disturbing the existing sulfide assemblage.
          // Source: Sverjensky 1981; Anderson & Macqueen 1982.
          "O2": 0.25,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 18.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 3000.0,   // iron-bearing limestone
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 800.0,    // Mn in the host rock
          // Aggressive acid dissolution — 3 primary + 10 secondary bubbles
          // give the deeply lobed cavity of a reactive front.
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 10,
          "shape_seed": 5
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 15, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_1", "name": "First Acid Pulse",  "description": "CO2-saturated brine" },
        { "step": 40, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_2", "name": "Second Acid Pulse", "description": "Stronger metal-bearing brine" },
        { "step": 70, "type": "reactive_wall_acid_pulse_3", "name": "Third Acid Pulse",  "description": "Weakening system" },
        { "step": 90, "type": "reactive_wall_seal",         "name": "Fracture Seal",     "description": "Flow stops" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Sverjensky 1981 (Econ. Geol. 76) — Viburnum Trend brine geochemistry",
        "Stoffell et al. 2008 — LA-ICP-MS fluid-inclusion brine analyses (Tri-State vs Viburnum distinction)",
        "Leach et al. 2010 — MVT genesis review",
        "Anderson & Macqueen 1982 — MVT mineralogy review",
        "Hanor 1994 — basinal-brine compendium (Sr/Ba tracers)"
      ]
    },

    "sabkha_dolomitization": {
      "anchor": "Coorong lagoon system (South Australia) and Persian Gulf sabkhas. The classic natural laboratory for direct-from-solution dolomite formation per Kim, Sun et al. 2023 (Science 382:915).",
      "description": "Cycling-brine sabkha producing ORDERED dolomite at ambient T via the Kim 2023 mechanism. Twelve flood/evap pulses over 240 steps drive Ω across the dolomite saturation boundary repeatedly — the cyclic Ω modulation that's needed to produce ordered dolomite at surface T.",
      "expects_species": ["dolomite", "anhydrite", "selenite"],
      "duration_steps": 260,
      "notes": [
        "Surface T (~25°C), high-Mg evaporative brine, seasonal flood-evaporate cycles. Per Kim, Sun et al. (2023, Science 382:915), exactly this kind of cyclic Ω modulation is what's needed to produce ordered dolomite at ambient T.",
        "The acid-pulse-and-relax style of reactive_wall produces only DISORDERED HMC because the dissolution events are too aggressive (full dissolution rather than gentle surface etch). Sabkha tidal pumping is the right kind of cycling — gentle, frequent, repeated.",
        "Twelve flood/evap pairs over 240 steps produce ~12 dissolution-precipitation cycles. With N0=10 in the f_ord formula, this reaches ORDERED (f_ord > 0.7) by mid-scenario. The result: true ordered dolomite, the geological prize the Kim 2023 paper made accessible.",
        "Schema note: the original Python/JS implementations used factory functions `make_flood(idx)` and `make_evap(idx)` to bake the cycle index into each handler's narrator string. Per the Phase 2 migration, we use one flood handler and one evap handler reused across all 12 cycles (the supergene_acidification precedent — same handler, multiple Event entries pointing to it). Cycle number is preserved via the event `name` field ('Tidal Flood #1', 'Evaporation #1', etc.) instead of an in-handler f-string."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Coorong surface T — ambient. The Kim mechanism's whole point is
        // that ordered dolomite at this T is achievable with cycling.
        "temperature_C": 25.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,    // near-surface lagoonal vug
        "fluid": {
          // Marine evaporative brine baseline (~3x seawater concentration):
          // Mg high, Ca moderate, Mg/Ca ~3.5 (above 1, dolomite-favoring),
          // CO3 modest, alkaline pH from photosynthetic mats. Na+Cl carry
          // the salinity but don't drive minerals here.
          "SiO2": 20,
          "Ca": 400,
          "CO3": 300,
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Mg": 1400,
          "Na": 10500,
          "K": 380,
          "S": 2700,
          "F": 2,
          "Cl": 18000,
          // Sr is the bonus tracer — marine brines carry ~8 ppm Sr,
          // gets concentrated by evaporation. Aragonite scavenges it.
          "Sr": 20,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 8.3,
          "salinity": 120.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Sabkha — supratidal evaporite playa. Basin geometry: top
          // hemisphere collapses, crystals nucleate floor-only on the
          // playa surface.
          "architecture": "basin",
          "composition": "limestone",   // Coorong lagoon floor is bioclastic carbonate
          "thickness_mm": 300.0,
          // Phase 1c (v148, 2026-05-26): bumped 30 → 60 mm to address
          // the cavity-fill ceiling identified in
          // HANDOFF-CARBONATE-PHASE-1-COMPLETE.md §1.5. At 30 mm
          // (volume = 14.1 cm³) the early-nucleating selenite + anhydrite
          // saturate the cavity within ~2 steps of step-1 evap, and the
          // currentFill ≥ 1.0 in-loop guard then rejects positive
          // growth zones for ALL slower-growing crystals — Kim
          // dolomite (rate ×0.30-1.0 from f_ord gate), HMC (PWP × Mg
          // poisoning), and aragonite (slow at sabkha cool-warm T).
          // Result at v147: dolomite 2.2 µm, HMC 0.8 µm, aragonite 15
          // µm — all sub-visible despite the Kim mechanism firing at
          // 12/12 cycles and f_ord 0.82.
          //
          // 60 mm gives 8× the cavity volume (113.1 cm³), enough room
          // for the carbonate cascade to grow past nucleation before
          // selenite/anhydrite saturate. Geologically defensible —
          // Persian Gulf sabkha intercrystalline pores range from <1 mm
          // to several cm depending on depth + parent lithology; the
          // 60 mm representative is on the cm-scale end (cavity-collapse
          // pore in carbonate-cemented zone) but matches the cathedral
          // tier the simulator uses for showcase scenarios elsewhere.
          // Selenite still grows visibly (47 mm at v147 fits 60 mm
          // cavity comfortably).
          "vug_diameter_mm": 60.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 200.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 50.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 24             // 24 hours = one tidal cycle
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // Twelve flood/evap pairs (one Kim cycle per pair) over 240 steps,
        // followed by a final seal event at step 245. flood at steps
        // 10/30/50/.../230, evap at 20/40/60/.../240. Single flood +
        // single evap handler reused per cycle.
        { "step":  10, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #1",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  20, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #1",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  30, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #2",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  40, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #2",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  50, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #3",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  60, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #3",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #4",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step":  80, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #4",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step":  90, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #5",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #5",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #6",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 120, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #6",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #7",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #7",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #8",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #8",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 170, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #9",  "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #9",  "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 190, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #10", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 200, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #10", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 210, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #11", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 220, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #11", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 230, "type": "sabkha_flood", "name": "Tidal Flood #12", "description": "Seawater dilution" },
        { "step": 240, "type": "sabkha_evap",  "name": "Evaporation #12", "description": "Brine reconcentration" },
        { "step": 245, "type": "sabkha_final_seal", "name": "Final Seal", "description": "Sabkha matures, fluids stop cycling" }
      ],
      // PROPOSAL-CARBONATE-GEOCHEM Phase 1 Week 4c. Sabkha is the
      // canonical open-system carbonate scenario — the evaporating
      // brine surface IS in contact with the atmosphere, and Kim 2023
      // explicitly identifies cyclic atmospheric pCO2 exchange as part
      // of the dolomitization mechanism. Modern atmospheric pCO2
      // (4.2e-4 bar) is the appropriate default; Holocene + Pleistocene
      // sabkhas saw similar values.
      "open_to_atmosphere": true,
      "atmospheric_pCO2_bar": 4.2e-4,
      "sources": [
        "Kim, Sun et al. 2023 (Science 382:915) — cyclic Ω modulation produces ordered dolomite at ambient T",
        "Coorong lagoon (South Australia) + Persian Gulf sabkhas — natural laboratory anchors"
      ]
    },

    "naica_geothermal": {
      "anchor": "Naica, Chihuahua, Mexico — Cueva de los Cristales, 290 m below surface. Lead-Zinc-Silver mine (Industrias Peñoles); the giant selenite cave was breached in April 2000 when a mine drift broke through into the chamber. Selenite blades up to 12 m × 1 m × 55 tonnes.",
      "description": "Slow geothermal pool that grew the largest crystals on Earth. Anhydrite-saturated water cools by hundredths of a degree per year through the gypsum-anhydrite boundary at ~58°C and holds just below it (~54-57°C), where gypsum reprecipitates from anhydrite dissolving at depth. Stable for ~500,000 years (Garcia-Ruiz et al. 2007). Mining begun 1985 dewatered the cave; pumping stopped 2017 and the cave reflooded.",
      "expects_species": ["selenite"],
      "duration_steps": 320,
      "notes": [
        "Garcia-Ruiz et al. 2007 (Geology 35:327) — the canonical paper on Naica's growth mechanism. Anhydrite at depth (T > 58°C) dissolves slightly; rising water cools to ~54°C; gypsum reprecipitates. The cooling rate is critical: at hundredths of a degree per year, the brine stays close enough to the boundary that crystals grow over geological timescales without significant nucleation of new seeds. Old crystals just keep adding layers.",
        "v182 THERMAL STORY (the first consumer of the v181 T-unlock): the buffered pool is now a DECLARED temperature movement — base 56°C, smoothstep trend −3 over steps 0-260, no OU texture (Naica's signature is thermal stability; fluid-inclusion work shows a remarkably steady bath, so the no-noise choice IS the science, not a simplification). Ambient drift + pulses stand down for the window (pre-v182 they were bulldozing the design: drift crashed 56→25°C in ~21 steps and ~19 random thermal pulses bounced T between the floor and 53°C — the 55-58°C selenite sweet-spot fired ~2 steps per run and the 54-57 Garcia-Ruiz band was occupied 0% of the time; now 31% and 50%). Dark-observed (tools/naica-thermal-observe.mjs, 3 seeds): total crystal count DROPS ~40-60% (27→11, 39→16) while the cavity still seals — fewer nuclei, larger individuals — which is the Garcia-Ruiz mechanism emerging from the engines rather than being scripted. The low-T noise feeders (opal, goethite, lepidocrocite, tigers_eye, pyrolusite) drop out; the cave trends toward its real near-monomineralic character.",
        "The six slow_cooling events keep their CHEMISTRY half under the movement — the anhydrite-at-depth resupply (Ca≥280, S≥380 floors) + O2/pH/flow resets are what they contribute now; their -0.7°C drops are superseded by the movement's trend (the handler's T>51 guard goes inert inside the window). Events are the chemistry beats; the movement is the thermal sentence.",
        "Mining-drainage event at step 260 (1985 in real time) fires fluid_surface_ring → 0 and SETS T=35; recharge at step 290 (2017) refloods at T=30. The movement window deliberately ENDS at 260: the thermal buffer was the WATER, so once the cave drains the pool era is over and the mining events own T. Ambient resumes post-260 with cooling_rate 0.1 (a drained cave at 290 m in warm country rock cools gently — observed end T ~27°C, matching the recharge note's 'cooler bath'), and thermal_pulses:false (no fracture-valve reheats in a conductively buffered system; same flag family as bisbee/roughten_gill/schneeberg/reactivated_vein).",
        "The default vug_diameter_mm of 50 mm grossly understates Naica reality (the chamber is ~30m × 10m × 10m). The simulator's max_size_cm cap on selenite is 2400 cm = 24m, double the real-world record (Garcia-Ruiz). Both are intentional — the sim isn't trying to reproduce Naica scale, it's reproducing Naica chemistry."
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "temperature",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 260,
          "base": 56,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -3, "ease": true }]
        }
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 56.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.08,    // shallow geothermal — 290m depth
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 30,
          // Anhydrite-saturated Ca-SO4 brine. Garcia-Ruiz et al.
          // report ~600 ppm Ca, ~1500 ppm SO4 at the cave's 58°C
          // boundary; we slightly amplify for engine kinetics.
          "Ca": 320,
          "S": 420,
          "CO3": 15,             // low — limestone host but Ca-SO4 dominates
          "F": 1,
          "Fe": 3,
          "Mn": 0.5,
          "Mg": 30,              // low Mg — the system is gypsum, not aragonite
          "Na": 90,              // mod salinity — not a brine, but not fresh
          "K": 8,
          "Cl": 180,
          "Sr": 6,
          "Pb": 5,               // trace — Naica is technically a Pb mine
          "Ag": 1,
          "O2": 1.5,             // oxidized — the brine contacts cave atmosphere
          "pH": 7.2,
          "salinity": 4.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",   // Naica is in Sierra de Naica limestone
          "thickness_mm": 1000.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 600.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 80.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 58,             // 58°C, the Naica equilibrium T
          // v182 thermal story (see notes): the declared movement owns T
          // through step 260; these two govern the post-drainage era only.
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          "cooling_rate": 0.1
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step":  30, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #1", "description": "Geothermal cooling from 56 toward 54°C boundary" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #2", "description": "Anhydrite at depth resupplies Ca + SO₄" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #3", "description": "Selenite cathedral blades grow another notch" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #4", "description": "Crossing toward the 54°C Naica equilibrium" },
        { "step": 190, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #5", "description": "Half a million years compressed to one event" },
        { "step": 230, "type": "naica_slow_cooling",  "name": "Cooling pulse #6", "description": "Cave reaches Naica baseline" },
        { "step": 260, "type": "naica_mining_drainage", "name": "1985: Mining Begins", "description": "Pumps drop the water table; cave drains" },
        { "step": 290, "type": "naica_mining_recharge", "name": "2017: Pumps Stop", "description": "Cave refloods; growth resumes in cooler water" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Garcia-Ruiz, Villasuso, Ayora, Canals, Otálora 2007 (Geology 35:327) — Formation of natural gypsum megacrystals in Naica, Mexico",
        "Otálora & Garcia-Ruiz 2014 (Chem. Soc. Rev. 43:2013) — Nucleation and growth of the Naica giant gypsum crystals",
        "Forti & Sanna 2010 (NSS Bull.) — The Naica caves and their crystals: a unique speleological problem",
        "Van Driessche, Garcia-Ruiz, Tsukamoto, Patiño-Lopez, Satoh 2011 (PNAS 108:15721) — Ultraslow growth rates of giant gypsum crystals (the measured stability the v182 thermal movement models: no-noise pool at marginal saturation)"
      ]
    },

    "searles_lake": {
      "anchor": "Searles Lake, San Bernardino County, California — Pleistocene-Holocene closed-basin alkaline-saline brine, the textbook locality for sodium-borate / sodium-sulfate / sodium-chloride evaporites. ~70 evaporite mineral species documented (Smith 1979 USGS PP 1043). Type locality for hanksite, sulfohalite, borax (commercially), tincalconite.",
      "description": "Mojave desert closed basin with Sierra Nevada snowmelt feed. Wet/dry seasonal cycling drives the full evaporite cascade: halite throughout, borax + mirabilite in cold winter, thenardite + tincalconite paramorphs in summer heat. The 20-mule team era of American borate commerce ran on chemistry like this.",
      "expects_species": ["halite", "borax", "mirabilite", "thenardite", "tincalconite"],
      "duration_steps": 300,
      "notes": [
        "Smith 1979 USGS Professional Paper 1043 — the canonical Searles Lake mineralogy + paragenesis reference. ~70 mineral species; the simulator covers the major Na-sulfate/borate/chloride suite (halite, borax, tincalconite, mirabilite, thenardite). Trona, hanksite, sulfohalite, glauberite, gaylussite, pirssonite, ulexite, colemanite, kernite are all real and worth adding later.",
        "Initial T = 18°C (Mojave October — playa temps span 5°C winter to 50°C summer). Initial chemistry seeds the alkaline-saline brine: Na 1500, B 100, S 400, Cl 1500, alkaline pH 9.5, low Ca (Ca > 50 would steal borate as colemanite). Salinity high (180 g/L) reflects the ~4× seawater concentration of mid-Pleistocene Searles brine.",
        "Five seasonal cycles over 300 steps. Each cycle: winter_freeze (steps 30, 90, 150, 210, 270) drops T to 8°C and bumps soluble species; summer_bake (steps 60, 120, 180, 240) heats to 55°C, firing the dehydration paramorph cascade (mirabilite → thenardite, borax → tincalconite). Inter-cycle fresh_pulse events flood the basin briefly.",
        "fluid_surface_ring isn't set in initial state — the basin starts fully saturated. The summer_bake events drop it through evaporation; fresh_pulse refills. The vadose-transition concentration boost (×3 per drying) is what brings borax + mirabilite into supersaturation.",
        "Death Valley (Furnace Creek) and Boron, CA also belong to this basin family but with slightly different brine-chemistry signatures. Searles is the most chemically diverse — chosen as the sim's anchor because more of its minerals are already plumbed."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 18.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 40,            // playa silt, rhyolitic ash from Sierra
          "Ca": 25,              // intentionally low — Ca > 50 inhibits borax
          "Na": 1500,            // 4x seawater Na
          "K": 250,              // Searles is K-anomalous (commercial K2SO4)
          "Mg": 40,              // low — Searles is a NaSO4-NaB4O7-NaCl basin
          "S": 400,              // sulfate-rich
          "B": 100,              // boron-rich — the commercial borate driver
          "Cl": 1500,            // chloride-rich
          "CO3": 80,             // some, but Searles is sulfate > carbonate
          "F": 3,
          "Fe": 1,
          "Mn": 0.5,
          "Sr": 5,
          "Li": 12,              // Searles has Li (commercial extraction in 1900s)
          "O2": 1.6,             // oxidized — playa surface
          "pH": 9.5,             // alkaline — keeps borate as B(OH)4-
          "salinity": 180.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Evaporite playa — flat closed-basin shape. The basin
          // archetype collapses the top hemisphere (no ceiling — a
          // playa doesn't have one) and biases nucleation to the
          // floor where halite + borax + mirabilite + thenardite
          // crystallize on the dried lake-bed. Matches the sabkha
          // sister scenario's choice. Mojave-anchored geology: dry
          // pan with brine pools, not a closed cavity (Smith 1979
          // USGS PP 1043 documents the actual subsurface stratigraphy
          // and basin geometry).
          "architecture": "basin",
          "composition": "limestone", // playa floor is mixed carbonate + evaporite mud
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 400.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 60.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1862     // first borax claim at Searles, 1862
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step":  30, "type": "searles_winter_freeze", "name": "Winter Freeze #1", "description": "Mojave night drops below 32°C; mirabilite + borax precipitate" },
        { "step":  60, "type": "searles_summer_bake",   "name": "Summer Bake #1",   "description": "Playa heats to 55°C; mirabilite → thenardite, borax → tincalconite" },
        { "step":  75, "type": "searles_fresh_pulse",   "name": "Sierra Snowmelt #1","description": "Brief flash flood; soluble salts redissolve" },
        { "step":  90, "type": "searles_winter_freeze", "name": "Winter Freeze #2", "description": "Cold-evaporite window opens again" },
        { "step": 120, "type": "searles_summer_bake",   "name": "Summer Bake #2",   "description": "Dehydration cascade fires" },
        { "step": 135, "type": "searles_fresh_pulse",   "name": "Sierra Snowmelt #2","description": "Refresh from spring runoff" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "searles_winter_freeze", "name": "Winter Freeze #3", "description": "Mid-Holocene cold pulse" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "searles_summer_bake",   "name": "Summer Bake #3",   "description": "Glauber salt loses 10 H₂O" },
        { "step": 195, "type": "searles_fresh_pulse",   "name": "Sierra Snowmelt #3","description": "Late Holocene refill" },
        { "step": 210, "type": "searles_winter_freeze", "name": "Winter Freeze #4", "description": "Late Pleistocene-style cold" },
        { "step": 240, "type": "searles_summer_bake",   "name": "Summer Bake #4",   "description": "Fourth dehydration cascade" },
        { "step": 255, "type": "searles_fresh_pulse",   "name": "Sierra Snowmelt #4","description": "Modern Holocene flush" },
        { "step": 270, "type": "searles_winter_freeze", "name": "Winter Freeze #5", "description": "Final cold pulse before basin drying" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Smith 1979 USGS Professional Paper 1043 — Subsurface Stratigraphy and Geochemistry of Late Quaternary Evaporites, Searles Lake, California",
        "Smith & Pratt 1957 USGS Bull. 1045-A — Hanksite from Searles Lake",
        "Eugster 1980 Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci. 8:35 — Lake Magadi-Searles brine geochemistry",
        "Boron, CA + Death Valley — adjacent commercially-active borate localities in the same basin family"
      ]
    },

    "great_salt_plains": {
      "anchor": "Salt Plains National Wildlife Refuge, Alfalfa County, Oklahoma — a 65-km² salt flat on the Permian red beds (Flowerpot Shale / Cedar Hills Sandstone). The ONLY place on Earth selenite grows the iron-stained 'hourglass' habit. The hourglass selenite is the Oklahoma state crystal; the refuge is the public crystal-digging locality.",
      "description": "Gypsum-saturated, salt-saturated groundwater wicks up through red-bed sand and evaporates just under a thin salt crust. Wet/dry seasonal cycling grows selenite in fast bursts that trap clay, sand, and Permian iron oxide on the terminal growth sectors — the visible hourglass — and step the blade outward each dry season. The iron-flooded crystals go solid reddish-to-chocolate brown.",
      "expects_species": ["selenite", "halite", "anhydrite", "celestine", "quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 250,
      "notes": [
        "USFWS Salt Plains NWR + Oklahoma Geological Survey: selenite forms just under a wafer-thin salt crust where gypsum-saturated saline groundwater reaches the surface and evaporates. Fine sand + clay are mechanically included on the fast-growing sectors, producing the hourglass shape; iron oxide in the red-bed soil gives the reddish-to-chocolate-brown colour. This hourglass habit is found NOWHERE else in the world.",
        "Showcase for the crystal-face-realism arc's hourglass-selenite render (2026-06-22): low-T (<45°C) sediment-laden fast growth → js/45 _seleniteHourglassParams tags the blade gypsum_hourglass; the repeated wet/dry fast-growth pulses drive the stepped-growth ziggurat (steps≥2); accumulated trace_Fe deepens the amber → chocolate brown and floods the heavily-included blades to solid brown. The render machinery already shipped SIM-neutral; this scenario is where it is the centerpiece.",
        "Initial broth: gypsum-saturated (Ca 120, S 120) salt-saturated (Na 700, Cl 700) oxidized surface brine at 28°C, near-neutral pH 7.6, iron-bearing (Fe 4) with suspended silt (SiO2 30). The DRY events (gsp_dry) spike Ca/S to 150 + concentrate Fe → fast selenite bursts that trap sediment; the WET events (gsp_wet) dilute to Ca/S 35 (σ<1) so growth pauses between pulses. Five wet/dry cycles over 250 steps.",
        "Halite is a co-product (the literal salt crust of the Salt Plains); minor goethite/iron-oxide staining is geologically the same iron that colours the hourglass. The star is selenite."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 28.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 30,            // suspended clay + red-bed silt (the inclusion source)
          "Ca": 120,             // gypsum-saturated groundwater
          "Na": 700,             // salt-saturated sand → the crust
          "Mg": 20,
          "S": 120,              // sulfate — the gypsum half
          "Cl": 700,
          "CO3": 15,             // low — clastic red beds, not carbonate
          "Fe": 8,               // Permian red-bed iron oxide — intense (the red beds ARE red)
          "Mn": 0.5,
          "Sr": 4,
          "O2": 1.6,             // oxidized playa surface
          "pH": 7.6,             // near-neutral
          "salinity": 150.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Salt flat over Permian red-bed sand — flat, floor-biased basin (no
          // ceiling), like the sabkha + searles sisters. 'sandstone' is an inert
          // clastic host (the engine treats any non-limestone/dolomite composition
          // as inert silicate — no Ca/CO3 dissolution; the Ca comes from the
          // gypsum-saturated groundwater, not the wall). High wall_Fe = the red beds.
          "architecture": "basin",
          "composition": "sandstone",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 120.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 3000.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 40.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 1930     // Salt Plains established as a NWR, 1930
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step":  25, "type": "gsp_wet",        "name": "Spring Rain #1",   "description": "Water table rises; brine dilutes below gypsum saturation" },
        { "step":  45, "type": "gsp_dry",         "name": "Dry Season #1",    "description": "Sun bakes the flat; selenite burst traps clay + iron" },
        { "step":  75, "type": "gsp_wet",        "name": "Spring Rain #2",   "description": "Rain floods the flat again" },
        { "step":  95, "type": "gsp_dry",         "name": "Dry Season #2",    "description": "Second fast burst — the blade steps out" },
        { "step": 125, "type": "gsp_wet",        "name": "Spring Rain #3",   "description": "Mid-season flood" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "gsp_dry",         "name": "Dry Season #3",    "description": "Third dry burst" },
        { "step": 175, "type": "gsp_wet",        "name": "Spring Rain #4",   "description": "Late flood" },
        { "step": 195, "type": "gsp_dry",         "name": "Dry Season #4",    "description": "Fourth dry burst" },
        { "step": 215, "type": "gsp_wet",        "name": "Spring Rain #5",   "description": "Final flood" },
        { "step": 235, "type": "gsp_dry",         "name": "Dry Season #5",    "description": "Fifth dry burst — the deepest iron flooding" },
        { "step": 245, "type": "gsp_crust_seal",  "name": "Crust Seal",       "description": "The salt crust hardens; cycling stops" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service — Salt Plains National Wildlife Refuge, selenite crystal digging (formation mechanism: gypsum-saturated groundwater evaporating under a salt crust; clay/sand/iron-oxide inclusions form the hourglass)",
        "Oklahoma Geological Survey / Oklahoma Historical Society — Great Salt Plains; hourglass selenite as the Oklahoma state crystal",
        "Ham W.E. (1961) Oklahoma Geological Survey — geology of the Salt Plains / Permian red-bed evaporites of northwestern Oklahoma"
      ]
    },

    "bisbee": {
      "anchor": "Bisbee, Arizona — Warren Mining District, Cochise County. Laramide quartz-monzonite porphyry intruding Paleozoic Escabrosa Limestone + Abrigo Formation. Major Cu-Ag-Au district (~8 Mt Cu, ~25 Moz Ag, ~3 Moz Au historically).",
      "description": "Classic copper porphyry with world-class oxidation zone. Complete Cu paragenesis from primary sulfides through supergene enrichment to the cyan-blue chrysocolla finale. Centerpiece mechanic: azurite ↔ malachite ↔ chrysocolla cascade tracking pCO2 evolution.",
      "expects_species": ["chalcopyrite", "malachite", "azurite", "chrysocolla", "brochantite"],
      "duration_steps": 340,
      "movements": [
        {
          // v186 EVENT-SUBSUMPTION — the supergene rollercoaster as a
          // declared redox sentence. The second EVENT-CONFOUNDED redox
          // scenario (after schneeberg v185), and the harder one: bisbee's
          // redox is NON-MONOTONIC (the nine event O2 writes trace −150 →
          // +180 → a deep reducing dip → +280), so the movement needs the
          // full primitive alphabet, not a single front. Composition is
          // schneeberg's (events keep Cu/S/CO3/pH/T beats; the movement is
          // the redox sentence). Window 0→305 = the whole phreatic life;
          // it ends AT the step-305 final_drying event (full drain →
          // vadose), where air owns redox (the flat +322 mV after 305 is
          // the vadose O2 floor, not the broth). Same boundary logic as
          // schneeberg — a redox movement lives in groundwater.
          //
          // FOUR OPS, each a measured beat of the Warren-District cascade:
          //   1. step +330 @ u=0.233 (step 71), soften 12/305 — the
          //      meteoric oxidation front, rising FROM the step-65 uplift
          //      event (never before its arrival; schneeberg lesson). A
          //      12-step ramp (not the 22 first tried) — a slower front
          //      starved brochantite's acid-flush window.
          //   2. pulse −60 @ u=0.351 (step 107), width 12/305 — the
          //      enrichment-blanket POISE: the pocket rides the redox
          //      interface (~+131 mV, not the full +180) where descending
          //      Cu²⁺ meets reducing sulfide and chalcocite replaces
          //      chalcopyrite.
          //   3. pulse −400 @ u=0.436 (step 133), width 9/305 — the barren
          //      DEEP REDUCING PULSE (down to ~−185 mV), the brief Eh-below-
          //      cuprite window that grows the Cornish-style native-copper
          //      trees. −400 (not −330) is load-bearing: the shallower dip
          //      dropped native_copper below 5/8 seeds; −400 holds it at 5/5.
          //   4. trend +100 ease — the long late oxidation climb to the
          //      +280 mV azurite-era plateau (the Bisbee Blue monsoon).
          //
          // DETERMINISTIC (no texture): the monsoon punctuation is the
          // EVENTS (azurite_peak/co2_drop/silica_seep), and OU re-rolls the
          // 1-crystal marginals. Gate verified at 8 seeds
          // (tools/eh-subsumption-observe.mjs): every lineage at BASE rate
          // (native_copper 5/5, brochantite 8/8, the malachite/chrysocolla
          // cascade whole). Logged BASE-side debt (NOT this change): azurite
          // 0/8 — the famous Bisbee Blue isn't nucleating; a future tune arc.
          "field": "fluid.Eh",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 305,
          "base": -150,
          "ops": [
            { "kind": "step",  "amp": 330,  "at": 0.23278688524590164,  "soften": 0.03934426229508197 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": -60,  "center": 0.3508196721311475, "width": 0.03934426229508197 },
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": -400, "center": 0.4360655737704918, "width": 0.02950819672131148 },
            { "kind": "trend", "amp": 100,  "ease": true }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Bisbee, Arizona — Warren Mining District, Cochise County. Host: combo Laramide quartz-monzonite porphyry intruded into Paleozoic Escabrosa Limestone + Abrigo Formation. In the sim this is represented as a limestone wall (the pH buffer, the CO3 source for azurite) with scenario events that inject dissolved SiO2 from the surrounding silicate matrix weathering — the supply path for late chrysocolla.",
        "Centerpiece mechanic: the azurite → malachite → chrysocolla cascade. Azurite dominates at high pCO2 (event 6, CO3 >= 120 ppm). A pCO2-drop event (event 7) dissolves azurite and fires malachite. A silica-seep event (event 8) dissolves malachite-without-silica and fires chrysocolla pseudomorphs on the remaining azurite crystals. Three carbonate/silicate phases recording three different groundwater chemistries, each one freezing a different step of the Cochise County monsoon.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): Ag=40 (Bisbee was a major Ag producer ~25 Moz; argentiferous galena + tetrahedrite + argentite + minor native Ag per Graeme et al. 2019). Mg=50 (Escabrosa Limestone host dolomitic in places; brief-required non-zero baseline). P=5 (enables pyromorphite given Pb+Cl already populated). Sb=5 (tetrahedrite trace; completes the Sb-As-Bi greisen triplet). Au=3 (Bisbee ~3 Moz historically — Cu-Au porphyry; native gold + auriferous chalcocite per Graeme 2019).",
        "Round 8c-1 additions (Apr 2026): Co=80, Ni=70 — Bisbee's deep primary sulfide assemblage includes minor Co/Ni-bearing sulfarsenide phases (cobaltite + nickeline + safflorite) per Graeme et al. 2019, citing Bryant 1968. Activates dormant Co/Ni pools for the new sulfarsenide engines and feeds the existing erythrite + annabergite supergene arsenates further down the cascade."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Primary porphyry stage — hot magmatic-hydrothermal brine.
        // Graeme et al. 2019 fluid inclusion data: 320-450C, 0.5-1.5 kbar,
        // hypersaline (35-55 wt% NaCl eq).
        "temperature_C": 400.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Cu 400 ppm — upper end of primary porphyry; the whole
          // district budget. Concentrated in the sim relative to nature
          // because we don't model the open-system leaching that strips
          // Cu from 10 km^3 of rock into a small pocket.
          "SiO2": 500,
          "Ca": 60,
          "CO3": 30,
          "Fe": 200,
          "Mn": 4,
          "Cu": 400,
          "S": 150,
          "F": 6,
          "Cl": 400,
          "Pb": 15,
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 120,
          "Al": 20,
          // Trace — arsenic from arsenopyrite, bismuth greisen signature
          // (Bisbee has documented bismuth enrichment).
          "As": 8,
          "Bi": 2,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "Ag": 40,    // Warren District ~25 Moz Ag [Graeme et al. 2019]
          "Mg": 50,    // dolomitic Escabrosa baseline; brief-required non-zero
          "P": 5,      // enables pyromorphite (Pb+Cl+P now all present)
          "Sb": 5,     // tetrahedrite-tennantite sulfosalt trace
          "Au": 3,     // ~3 Moz Au; supergene-preserved native gold + auriferous chalcocite
          // Round 8c-1: minor Co/Ni-bearing sulfarsenides (cobaltite +
          // nickeline + safflorite) documented at depth — activates
          // cobaltite + nickeline + millerite engines and feeds erythrite +
          // annabergite supergene cascade.
          "Co": 80,
          "Ni": 70,
          // Very reducing primary — chalcopyrite/bornite-stable.
          "O2": 0.05,
          "pH": 5.0,
          "salinity": 30.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Bisbee — limestone-replacement skarn cavities. Karst-style
          // dissolution + supergene overprint = irregular profile.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "composition": "limestone",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 2500.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 400.0,
          // Primary cavity dug by magmatic-hydrothermal replacement of
          // limestone. Secondary alcoves from supergene overprint.
          // 3+7 matches the supergene_oxidation profile.
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          "shape_seed": 13,
          // v162: supergene regime — no magmatic thermal pulses. The whole
          // azurite→malachite→chrysocolla cascade (steps 145-305) is a ~25°C
          // near-surface monsoon process; the ungated ambient_cooling pulse
          // mechanic was spuriously reheating it toward 350°C (strip T chip).
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 25,  "type": "bisbee_primary_cooling",     "name": "Primary Cooling",     "description": "Chalcopyrite + bornite lock in" },
        { "step": 65,  "type": "bisbee_uplift_weathering",   "name": "Uplift + Weathering", "description": "Meteoric acid strips primary ore" },
        { "step": 95,  "type": "bisbee_enrichment_blanket",  "name": "Enrichment Blanket",  "description": "Chalcocite replaces chalcopyrite" },
        { "step": 120, "type": "bisbee_reducing_pulse",      "name": "Reducing Pulse",      "description": "Native copper fracture fillings" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "bisbee_oxidation_zone",      "name": "Oxidation Zone",      "description": "Cuprite mantles native copper" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "bisbee_azurite_peak",        "name": "Azurite Peak",        "description": "High-pCO2 monsoon — Bisbee Blue" },
        { "step": 225, "type": "bisbee_co2_drop",            "name": "pCO2 Drop",           "description": "Azurite -> malachite conversion" },
        { "step": 265, "type": "bisbee_silica_seep",         "name": "Silica Seep",         "description": "Chrysocolla crusts + pseudomorphs" },
        { "step": 305, "type": "bisbee_final_drying",        "name": "Final Drying",        "description": "Fractures seal, system locks" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Graeme, Graeme & Graeme 2019 — modern Bisbee monograph",
        "Bryant 1968 — Warren District geology",
        "Crane 1911 — early Bisbee geology",
        "Vink 1986 — azurite ↔ malachite pCO2 thermodynamics",
        "Mote et al. 2001 — supergene chrysocolla geochemistry"
      ]
    },

    "supergene_oxidation": {
      "anchor": "Tsumeb mine, Otavi Mountain Land, Namibia. 1st-stage gossan (uppermost supergene zone). One of the most mineralogically diverse deposits ever discovered (~280 species), type locality for germanium.",
      "description": "Cold, oxygenated supergene weathering of a Pb-Zn-Cu sulfide pipe. Pb+Mo→wulfenite, Zn+CO3→smithsonite, Zn+As→adamite, Pb+As+Cl→mimetite, Fe→goethite, Ca+SO4→selenite, Cu+CO3→malachite. The 1st-stage gossan brings the high-Pb-As-Cl uppermost zone with mimetite, anglesite, cerussite, willemite, and Ge-bearing oxidation phases.",
      "expects_species": ["wulfenite", "smithsonite", "adamite", "mimetite", "malachite", "vanadinite", "cerussite", "selenite", "conichalcite", "pharmacolite", "haidingerite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Tsumeb mine (Otavi Mountain Land, Namibia). Pipe-shaped Pb-Zn-Cu sulfide body in Neoproterozoic dolomite, with three distinct supergene oxidation zones developed during Mesozoic-Cenozoic uplift. Argentiferous (native Ag, proustite, pyrargyrite, argentiferous galena). References: Pinch & Wilson 1977 (canonical Tsumeb monograph), Lombaard et al. 1986 (geology), Melcher 2003 (Ge geochemistry).",
        "Acid-window mechanic (steps 5-16): the supergene_acidification handler fires FOUR times (steps 5/8/12/16) to hold pH near 4 against the limestone wall's carbonate buffering. Without the repeated pulses, the buffer neutralizes pH back to 6+ within ~5 steps. The 15-step acid window is when scorodite + jarosite + alunite nucleate. ev_meteoric_flush at step 20 ends the acid phase.",
        "Chemistry-audit gap-fill pass (Apr 2026): added Ag (Tsumeb's silver suite), Ge (the type-locality element), Sb (proustite-pyrargyrite + tetrahedrite enabling), Na/K (minor groundwater cation traces), Au=0.3 (sub-threshold trace, no nucleation). v5 gap-fills: Al=25 (alunite enabling per Hemley 1969 + Stoffregen 2000), W=20 (Round 8d-1, Tsumeb deep-zone scheelite + raspite + stolzite per Strunz 1959). Existing 8-event sequence preserved untouched."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 35.0,    // shallow water-table zone
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,    // near-surface
        "fluid": {
          // CO3 80 → 110 so azurite's high-pCO2 gate (CO3 >= 120 after
          // meteoric flush adds 30) can be reached in a limestone-hosted
          // supergene vug. Real azurite localities (Bisbee, Chessy, Tsumeb)
          // all have limestone or dolomite wall rock.
          "SiO2": 30,
          "Ca": 120,
          "CO3": 110,
          "Fe": 40,
          "Mn": 6,
          "Mg": 5,
          "Zn": 90,
          "S": 50,
          "F": 3,
          // Cu 25 → 55: enough to feed chalcocite/bornite at supergene
          // enrichment zones. Pb bumped 35 → 60 for anglesite/cerussite/
          // pyromorphite saturation.
          "Cu": 55,
          "Pb": 60,
          "Mo": 15,
          // As 12 → 25 (stale-mineral retune 2026-05): Tsumeb fluid
          // inclusion data shows As 50-500 ppm in oxidation-zone brines
          // (Pinch & Wilson 1977); 12 ppm was undershooting the Tsumeb
          // anchor. tools/stale_mineral_probe.mjs found adamite σ
          // peaking at 0.68 vs gate of 1.0 — formula's (Zn/80)×(As/30)
          // term needed more As headroom. Bump also benefits the
          // already-live mimetite + erythrite + annabergite engines
          // (small calibration drift expected; geological direction).
          "As": 25,
          "Cl": 20,
          // V trace — roll-front / red-bed signature. Low start; bumped by ev_v_bearing_seep.
          "V": 1.5,
          // P trace — meteoric water typically <1 ppm; pyromorphite waits for ev_phosphate_seep.
          "P": 0.5,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "Ag": 8,    // argentiferous suite [Pinch & Wilson 1977]
          "Ge": 5,    // type-locality element [Melcher 2003]
          "Sb": 5,    // proustite/pyrargyrite/tetrahedrite enabling
          "Na": 30,
          "K": 10,
          "Au": 0.3,  // sub-threshold trace; no native gold nucleation expected
          // v5 gap-fills:
          "Al": 25,   // alunite engine cap [Hemley 1969; Stoffregen 2000]
          "W": 20,    // scheelite + lead-tungstate suite [Strunz 1959]
          // v62 plumbing: Cd from sphalerite oxidation. Tsumeb sphalerite
          // carries 0.1-1% Cd substituting for Zn (Lombaard 1986; Pinch &
          // Wilson 1977 documents greenockite + hawleyite oxidation-zone
          // assemblages on Tsumeb sphalerite). 0.5 ppm sim-scale enables
          // greenockite + hawleyite when their engines land.
          "Cd": 0.5,
          "O2": 1.8,
          "pH": 6.8,
          "salinity": 2.0
        },
        // Supergene oxidation front — 3 primary + 7 secondary bubbles model
        // complex meteoric dissolution cavity formation.
        "wall": {
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): Tsumeb 1st-stage gossan is
          // a deeply weathered + dissolved oxidation pocket — the type
          // locality has highly irregular cavity geometry from
          // century+ of acid pulse erosion through Pre-Cambrian
          // dolomite. 'irregular' archetype encodes that (cathedral-
          // scale variance, polar_amp×1.4). Default 'pocket' (smooth
          // pegmatite ellipsoid) was wrong for a supergene gossan.
          // Bubble counts left at scenario-tuned 3/7.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          "shape_seed": 7
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // Acid phase fires the same handler 4x (steps 5/8/12/16) to maintain
        // the acid window against the limestone wall's pH-buffering.
        { "step": 5,   "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Phase",        "description": "Early sulfide oxidation drops pH" },
        { "step": 8,   "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Continues",    "description": "Sulfide-oxidation acid persists" },
        { "step": 12,  "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Continues",    "description": "Carbonate buffer overrun" },
        { "step": 16,  "type": "supergene_acidification",   "name": "Acid Final Pulse",  "description": "Last sulfide-oxidation pulse" },
        { "step": 20,  "type": "supergene_meteoric_flush",  "name": "Meteoric Flush",    "description": "Oxygenated rainwater recharges" },
        { "step": 40,  "type": "supergene_pb_mo_pulse",     "name": "Pb+Mo Pulse",       "description": "Galena+molybdenite weathering" },
        { "step": 55,  "type": "supergene_cu_enrichment",   "name": "Cu Enrichment",     "description": "Primary chalcopyrite upslope weathers" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "supergene_dry_spell",       "name": "Dry Spell",         "description": "Evaporation concentrates sulfate" },
        { "step": 95,  "type": "supergene_as_rich_seep",    "name": "Arsenic Seep",      "description": "Zn/Pb arsenate saturation" },
        { "step": 115, "type": "supergene_phosphate_seep",  "name": "Phosphate Seep",    "description": "Soil-zone PO4 enables pyromorphite" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "supergene_v_bearing_seep",  "name": "V-bearing Seep",    "description": "Red-bed V leaches in, vanadinite fires" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "supergene_fracture_seal",   "name": "Fracture Seal",     "description": "System closes", "spots": "seal" }
      ],
      // Geological MOVEMENTS (js/85j) — Phase 3, the SECOND scenario to opt in
      // (after mvt's 4c.3b Eh trend). A sustained meteoric ACID FRONT on fluid.pH,
      // grounded in RESEARCH-supergene-acid-front-2026-06-02.md. Supergene sulfide
      // oxidation generates sulfuric acid (4 FeS2 + 15 O2 + 14 H2O -> 4 Fe(OH)3 +
      // 8 H2SO4; Fe2+->Fe3+ is the rate-determining step, Singer & Stumm 1970
      // Science 167:1121), progressively acidifying the O2-rich oxidation-zone
      // fluid; the limestone wall buffers it (CaCO3 + H2SO4 -> Ca + SO4 + CO2),
      // so it stays mildly acidic and Ca/CO3 surge as the front advances.
      // Tsumeb arsenate-mineral stability tracks this oxidation-zone pH/Eh
      // (Bowell 2014, Rev. Mineral. Geochem. 79:589). pH 6.8 -> 4.3 (smoothstep)
      // + a small mean-reverting (OU) texture; clampMin 3.5 = the limestone-
      // buffered floor (a carbonate-hosted gossan doesn't run away to AMD pH 2 —
      // in-run pH stays >= 4.7).
      //
      // startStep 20 is LOAD-BEARING: a same-field (pH) movement OVERWRITES the
      // field each step (run_step applies movements AFTER apply_events, 85-sim:184),
      // so starting at 0 would CLOBBER the early acid-window EVENTS (steps 5/8/12/16,
      // which sawtooth pH to ~4.7 to nucleate jarosite + alunite + scorodite). Begin-
      // ning the movement AT step 20 (just after supergene_meteoric_flush re-wets
      // and re-neutralizes) makes the movement COMPOSE with the events instead of
      // clobbering them: the events own the early sharp acid spike, the movement owns
      // the slow SUSTAINED re-acidification as oxidation deepens. (Verified via the
      // tmp diagnostic: start0 erases the acid window -> 38 sp, loses jarosite+alunite;
      // start20 PRESERVES it -> 40 sp, full acid-sulfate suite kept AND vanadinite
      // recovered. The static baseline FAILS to grow vanadinite, a declared
      // expects_species; this movement recovers it.) DARK-OBSERVED (tools/movement-
      // assemblage-observe.mjs supergene_oxidation pH 6.8 -2.5 0.12 3.5 20).
      // Driving ONE master var (pH) makes the SI engines emit correlated pulses (Mn
      // UNFROZEN CV 0.04->0.33, Ca/CO3 surge from carbonate dissolution, Fe/Zn/S
      // mobilized) — elements never randomized directly. The sustained front means
      // pH does NOT recover to neutral by run-end (~5.1) — the more faithful gossan
      // profile vs the old acid-spike-then-full-recovery (strip contract updated).
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "fluid.pH",
          "startStep": 20,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 6.8,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -2.5, "ease": true }],
          "texture": { "theta": 0.3, "sigma": 0.12 },
          "clampMin": 3.5
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — canonical Tsumeb monograph",
        "Lombaard et al. 1986 — Tsumeb geology",
        "Melcher 2003 — Tsumeb Ge geochemistry",
        "Seo et al. 2012 — Pb+Mo simultaneous weathering for wulfenite formation",
        "Hemley et al. 1969 — alunite stability + Al solubility under acid-sulfate conditions",
        "Stoffregen et al. 2000 — alunite-jarosite paragenesis review",
        "Strunz 1959 — Tsumeb deep oxidation zone scheelite + lead-tungstate suite (raspite + stolzite)",
        "Bowell 2014, Rev. Mineral. Geochem. 79:589 — Tsumeb hydrogeochemistry + arsenate mineral stability (the acid-front movement)",
        "Singer & Stumm 1970, Science 167:1121 — Fe(II)→Fe(III) as the rate-determining step of sulfide-oxidation acid generation",
        "Skarpelis 2009, Resource Geology 59(1) — Lavrion Pb-Ag-Zn supergene oxidation profile (carbonate-hosted analogue)"
      ]
    },

    "gem_pegmatite": {
      "anchor": "Cruzeiro mine, São José da Safira, Doce Valley, Minas Gerais (Variant A — Brasiliano-age miarolitic gem pegmatite, 700-450 Ma).",
      "description": "Miarolitic cavity in a complex zoned pegmatite. The residual pocket where incompatible elements (Be, B, Li, F) accumulate beyond belief, then cross saturation in cascade — schorl → beryl → spodumene + elbaite → late topaz, with kaolinization of the microcline walls at the end.",
      "expects_species": ["tourmaline", "spodumene", "topaz", "feldspar", "albite", "lepidolite", "cassiterite"],
      "duration_steps": 230,
      // FLUID-SPOTS Phase 2c.2b — the per-cell deposition-clustering DEMONSTRATOR
      // (the boss's "best crystals cluster near the feeder"). A miarolitic gem
      // pocket connects to its plumbing at a few feeder channels; the finest
      // crystals concentrate around them. The seeded set here is 3 hotspots
      // (shape_seed 42); with `deposition: true` nucleation gains a decaying halo
      // of boost around each open vent → tourmaline/cassiterite concentrate at the
      // feeders (0→18% of crystals within 2 cells), assemblage preserved. Per-
      // scenario opt-in keeps the validated-chemistry fleet (e.g. reactive_wall)
      // byte-identical. Strength is the global setDepositionClustering(PEAK_K,LAMBDA).
      "fluid_spots": { "deposition": true },
      // FLUID-SPOTS Phase 2c.3 — the UNITED point-source showpiece. An origin:'cell'
      // movement injects a BORON halo at the cavity's dominant (most-equatorial) open
      // feeder: the feeder is the boron delivery point (PROPOSAL §10 / §9c). It resolves
      // to the same equatorial vent the deposition cluster favors, so the chemical halo
      // (strip-visible B chip, 0-120 scale → clampMax 120) sits at the SAME feeder where
      // tourmaline concentrates (2c.2b) and the cavity deepens (2b): one point, three
      // signals — shape + chemistry + crystals. Anchored to the step-30 "Schorl Arrives
      // (B + Fe supersaturation)" event: the feeder delivers the boron that brings schorl.
      // NB the injection is a per-cell CHEMICAL halo (strip + per-vertex visible), DECOUPLED
      // from the legacy ring-fluid nucleation gate, and these growth engines aren't
      // nutrient-rate-limited → the bulk assemblage is unchanged (verified byte-identical);
      // the uniting is the spatial CO-LOCATION of halo + cluster at the feeder.
      "movements": [
        { "field": "fluid.B", "origin": "cell", "startStep": 30, "endStep": 230,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": 100, "ease": true }],
          "texture": { "theta": 0.3, "sigma": 4 }, "clampMax": 120 }
      ],
      "notes": [
        "Cruzeiro is the type-locality for fine schorl-elbaite tourmaline + smoky quartz pockets, with documented beryl, spodumene, lepidolite, and accessory apatite. Brasiliano-age (Neoproterozoic) pegmatite field cutting Macaúbas Group meta-sediments. Morteani et al. 2002 covers fluid chemistry; Cassedanne (1991) and Proctor (1985) cover the Cruzeiro-specific paragenesis.",
        "Thermal regime: 650 → 300°C over ~230 steps in three phases. Phase 1 (650-550°C): wall-zone crystallization (microcline, quartz, early schorl). Phase 2 (550-400°C): main pocket growth — beryl finally nucleates when Be crosses threshold; spodumene when Li crosses; schorl transitions to elbaite as Fe depletes and Li accumulates. Phase 3 (400-300°C): late hydrothermal — topaz if F survives, then kaolinization of microcline walls.",
        "Saturation cascade mechanic: there is no explicit 'nucleate beryl now' command. Each mineral's supersaturation formula reads the current fluid, and the nucleation gates fire in order naturally as chemistry evolves — microcline first (K-feldspar = feldspar here), then the Be/Li/B gates cross as incompatible elements build up.",
        "v183 thermal_pulses:false — the PEGMATITE-SHAPE T story (contrast naica's v182 movement): all eight events SET temperature (620→560→500→450→420→360→320→300), so the three-phase curve is already fully event-anchored and a declared movement would clobber it. The fix is silencing the ambient noise around it: a sealed miarolitic pocket has no fracture-valve hot injections (the pocket IS the isolated residual chamber), the pulses' Fe riders (+2-15 ppm) directly fight the li_phase event's documented Fe depletion (Fe→5 is what turns schorl into elbaite), and a late pulse was re-warming the ended system to ~476°C against the design's 300°C floor (dark-observed, tools/t-story-observe.mjs: end T 476→276 with the flag; assemblage and crystal counts IDENTICAL at 3 seeds — the v181 dedicated thermal stream means a thermal-regime change no longer re-rolls the nucleation cascade). Topaz remains aspirational at seed 42 (absent in BASE too — its tuning is a separate vugg-tune-scenario arc; the honest T floor can only help it).",
        "Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026): P=8 (pegmatite residual P; enables Cruzeiro accessory apatite per Cassedanne 1991). Mg=5 (brief-required non-zero baseline; pegmatite pocket fluids are Mg-poor since Mg partitions strongly into outer-shell biotite/chlorite during pegmatite differentiation)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 650.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatite-level silica saturation — far above quartz equilibrium
          // at any T, so quartz is supersaturated throughout.
          "SiO2": 8000,
          "Ca": 30,
          "CO3": 15,
          "Fe": 50,
          "Mn": 8,
          // Al starts high enough that six competing silicate engines
          // (feldspar, albite, quartz, tourmaline, beryl, spodumene) can all
          // draw on it for the full scenario AND leave residual for topaz
          // to nucleate in phase 3. 150 ppm is on the upper end of realistic
          // pegmatite pocket fluid Al but within published ranges
          // (London 2008, pegmatite fluid chemistry).
          "Al": 150,
          // Alkali feldspar chemistry — microcline first, then ev_albitization
          // flips K -> Na.
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 40,
          // Incompatible elements — these are the point of the scenario.
          // All start above their respective minimum thresholds but below
          // the nucleation σ threshold; they build (unused early) and then
          // the cascade fires.
          "Be": 25,    // beryl nucleation σ 1.8 — waits longest
          "B": 35,     // tourmaline σ 1.3 — fires earliest once hot
          "Li": 35,    // spodumene σ 1.5, also feeds elbaite
          "F": 25,     // topaz σ 1.4 — fires late when T drops into window
          // Color-element traces. Cr from hinted ultramafic contact;
          // Mn for morganite/kunzite/rubellite; Cu for the Paraíba long-shot.
          "Cr": 2.5,
          "Cu": 0.3,
          "V": 2.0,
          // Ti=25: pegmatite residual liquor is enriched in incompatible
          // high-field-strength elements including Ti. Cruzeiro and other
          // miarolitic pegmatites carry trace rutile + accessory ilmenite +
          // Ti in tourmaline/biotite. 25 sim-ppm enables rutile to nucleate
          // when its engine lands — sometimes as inclusion in growing quartz
          // (rutilated quartz / Cupid's darts is a Brazilian classic from
          // similar pegmatite settings). v62 was 0.8.
          "Ti": 25,
          // Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026):
          "P": 8,    // accessory apatite [Cassedanne 1991]
          "Mg": 5,   // brief-required non-zero baseline
          // v62 plumbing: W for the new tungstate engines. 5 ppm enables
          // scheelite + wolframite (Sn-W vein chemistry overlaps with Be-Li
          // pegmatites; Cornish + Panasqueira-adjacent geology). Pb=0 in
          // this broth keeps existing raspite/stolzite (which need Pb≥40)
          // dormant, so this is a clean single-axis bump.
          // Te is intentionally NOT added here — adding Te≥0.5 with Au=0
          // would unblock native_tellurium nucleation and disturb the
          // pegmatite paragenesis. The Au-Ag-Te trio gets its own
          // epithermal_telluride scenario.
          "W": 5,
          // v89 plumbing: Sn for the new cassiterite engine. 80 ppm
          // above the cassiterite engine's Sn>=20 nucleation gate.
          // Sn is a classic LCT-pegmatite incompatible (Cassedanne
          // 1991 documents minor cassiterite in Cruzeiro alongside
          // wolframite; the Sn-W pair is the standard greisen-stage
          // signature). Pre-v89 Sn was implicit at 0 (the field
          // didn't exist); adding the explicit 80 ppm activates
          // cassiterite alongside the existing W=5 wolframite.
          "Sn": 80,
          "O2": 0.1,
          "pH": 6.8,
          "salinity": 6.0
        },
        // Pegmatite country rock — silicate, not acid-reactive on sim
        // timescales, so when pocket fluid turns mildly acidic in phase 3
        // pH stays low (no carbonate buffering). That's what lets
        // grow_feldspar's kaolinization branch fire on the microcline.
        "wall": {
          "composition": "pegmatite",
          "thickness_mm": 500.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 8,
          // v183 (see the thermal note above): the eight T-setting events ARE
          // the thermal story; this kills the fracture-valve noise around it.
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          // Tier 1 C (post-v69): pegmatite miarolitic cavities have
          // crisp euhedral cavity walls — the host is a brittle,
          // unweathered silicate matrix that preserves the original
          // sphere-union dissolution boundary without subsequent
          // rounding. London 2008 photographs of Brazilian + Maine
          // miarolitic cavities show sharp dihedral creases between
          // primary and satellite voids. 'sharp' surfaces those
          // creases on the cavity mesh.
          "cavity_render": "sharp"
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 5,   "type": "gem_pegmatite_outer_shell",        "name": "Outer Shell",        "description": "Wall-zone microcline + quartz" },
        { "step": 30,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_first_schorl",       "name": "Schorl Arrives",     "description": "B + Fe2+ supersaturation — first tourmaline" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_albitization",       "name": "Albitization",       "description": "K-feldspar -> albite replacement cascade" },
        { "step": 90,  "type": "gem_pegmatite_be_saturation",      "name": "Be Saturation",      "description": "Beryl finally nucleates — enormous crystals incoming" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "gem_pegmatite_li_phase",           "name": "Li Phase",           "description": "Spodumene + elbaite territory" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "gem_pegmatite_late_hydrothermal",  "name": "Late Hydrothermal",  "description": "Topaz window opens — F survivors fire" },
        { "step": 190, "type": "gem_pegmatite_clay_softening",     "name": "Clay Softening",     "description": "Kaolinite replaces pocket walls" },
        { "step": 215, "type": "gem_pegmatite_final",              "name": "Final Cooling",      "description": "System approaches 300C floor" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Morteani et al. 2002 — fluid chemistry of Brazilian gem pegmatites",
        "Cassedanne 1991 — Cruzeiro mine paragenesis",
        "Proctor 1985 — Cruzeiro tourmaline + beryl mineralogy",
        "London 2008 — pegmatite fluid Al partition (~150 ppm upper bound)"
      ]
    },

    "ouro_preto": {
      "anchor": "Ouro Preto Imperial Topaz veins, Minas Gerais, Brazil (Variant B per Morteani et al. 2002).",
      "description": "Hydrothermal topaz vein in Precambrian phyllite + quartzite. Single clean cooling curve from 360°C to 50°C — the 'anti-flash-quench' of the gem-pegmatite scenarios. F-pulse gates topaz nucleation; Cr leach commits the imperial color.",
      "expects_species": ["topaz", "quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 260,
      "notes": [
        "Hydrothermal veins cutting Precambrian phyllite and quartzite in the Ouro Preto district. Fluid inclusion data (Morteani et al. 2002) puts crystallization at ~360°C, 3.5 kbar from metamorphic brines derived from devolatilization of phyllite.",
        "Single clean cooling curve — 360°C → 50°C — the anti-flash-quench of the gem-pegmatite scenarios. No thermal events, no pressure spikes. One exhalation from the granite cooling below.",
        "The gate: topaz can't nucleate until fluorine accumulates past a saturation threshold. Early quartz grows alone. A mid-scenario metamorphic dehydration event (step 35) pumps F from the phyllite micas into the fluid, and the vein transitions to imperial topaz territory. The imperial color — golden-orange to pink — depends on Cr3+ dissolved out of nearby ultramafic bodies; without chromium the topaz is colorless or pale blue.",
        "Audit gap-fills (Apr 2026): Na=60, K=40 (phyllite muscovite/albite breakdown per Morteani 2002). Mg=15 (phyllite chlorite/biotite, brief-required non-zero baseline; conservative since host is quartzite + phyllite, not mafic)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 360.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 3.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Quartz-saturated metamorphic brine from devolatilizing phyllite.
          // SiO2 1200 ppm is enough to supersaturate quartz at 360C
          // (silica_equilibrium at 360C ~1050 ppm) — quartz lines the vein
          // walls first, as per real Ouro Preto paragenesis.
          "SiO2": 1200,
          "Ca": 40,
          "CO3": 20,
          "Fe": 6,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Al": 15,
          // Starts below F-threshold (20 ppm) — topaz waits for the pulse.
          "F": 12,
          // Trace Cr from nearby ultramafic contact. Starts sub-threshold;
          // ev_cr_leach bumps it into the imperial-color window (3-8 ppm).
          // Random seeds can push it past 8 (pink imperial) if the Cr leach
          // lands on an already-elevated baseline.
          "Cr": 0.5,
          "Ti": 0.6,
          // Audit gap-fills:
          "Na": 60,
          "K": 40,
          "Mg": 15,
          "O2": 0.3,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 3.0
        },
        // Ouro Preto topaz vein — 2 primary + 4 secondary bubbles;
        // hydrothermal vein in quartzite reads as a small cohesive pocket.
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 9
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 5,   "type": "ouro_preto_vein_opening",      "name": "Vein Opening",       "description": "Fracture propagates, fresh brine" },
        { "step": 35,  "type": "ouro_preto_f_pulse",           "name": "F-Pulse",            "description": "Phyllite dehydration — F crosses saturation" },
        { "step": 55,  "type": "ouro_preto_cr_leach",          "name": "Cr Leach",           "description": "Ultramafic dike contributes chromium" },
        { "step": 90,  "type": "ouro_preto_steady_cooling",    "name": "Steady Cooling",     "description": "Main topaz growth phase" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "ouro_preto_late_hydrothermal", "name": "Late Hydrothermal",  "description": "Kaolinite softening, F depleted" },
        { "step": 200, "type": "ouro_preto_oxidation_stain",   "name": "Oxidation Stain",    "description": "Goethite staining, surface water" },
        { "step": 240, "type": "ouro_preto_final_cooling",     "name": "Final Cooling",      "description": "System approaches ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Morteani et al. 2002 — fluid inclusion microthermometry of Ouro Preto Imperial Topaz veins"
      ]
    },

    "deccan_zeolite": {
      "anchor": "Deccan Traps zeolite vesicle (Stage III, ~21-58 Ma post-eruption). Nashik 'bloody apophyllite' is the type expression. Per Ottens et al. 2019.",
      "description": "Patient zeolite-stage paragenesis in cooled basalt vesicles. Stage I silica veneer + Stage II zeolite blades + Stage III alkaline K-Ca-Si-F pulse builds pseudo-cubic apophyllite around hematite-needle phantoms.",
      // magnetite stopped firing under sim_version 20 (Phase C v1).
      // Same drift cause as bornite/porphyry — see that note. Restore
      // when chemistry tunes for the new sim version.
      "expects_species": ["hematite", "quartz", "apophyllite", "stilbite", "heulandite", "scolecite", "mesolite", "thomsonite", "chabazite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Per Ottens et al. 2019, the Deccan basalt vesicles fill in stages over tens of millions of years. Stage I (early): silica veneers, chalcedony coating. Stage II: zeolite blades (stilbite, scolecite, heulandite) and early calcite. Stage III: the apophyllite stage — alkaline K-Ca-Si-F fluid percolates through cooled basalt vesicles and crystallizes pseudo-cubic apophyllite blocks, sometimes carrying hematite-needle phantoms (the 'bloody apophyllite' of Nashik).",
        "Compared to the metamorphic / hydrothermal scenarios, this is gentle: no acid pulses, no dramatic T excursions. The story is patient crystallization in alkaline groundwater over geologic time.",
        "v184 thermal honesty (T-rollout close-out) — THREE coupled changes, dark-observed together (tools/t-story-observe.mjs, 3 seeds): (1) thermal_pulses:false — the note above says 'no dramatic T excursions' and the ambient mechanic was firing 5-8 of them per run; (2) cooling_rate 0.3 — with pulses gone, the default 1.5°C/step crashed the vesicle to the floor between the stage events (a cooling flow stack declines gently over ~37 My, the scenario's own 'patient' thesis); (3) the movements block below — a sustained fluid.SiO2 setpoint (950) through the Stage III window. The dark observation EXPOSED a structural noise-dependence: apophyllite's gate needs SiO2 ≥ 800 and the random pulses' +50-300 SiO2 riders were the scenario's de-facto silica budget (the stage_iii event's one-shot +600 — already bumped from 300 once for exactly this reason — gets eaten by background quartz depletion). Ottens calls Stage III 'the long-lasting late stage' (21-58 Ma): a SUSTAINED groundwater regime is the honest model, and on vesicle timescales the percolating aquifer is an infinite reservoir — so the movement PINS SiO2 at 950 for the window rather than shooting it once. Result: all three expects at all seeds (apophyllite was LOST under flag-only variants), fill IMPROVES 0.07-0.18 → 0.28-0.30, and the noise-fed extras (rhodochrosite = pulse-Mn, wollastonite = a skarn mineral that never belonged in an amygdale) drop out.",
        "Audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): Sr=2 — Deccan zeolites (heulandite, stilbite, mesolite) carry Sr substituting for Ca, sometimes 100s of ppm in the mineral. Sim-scale 2 ppm in the parent fluid documents the source. Brief-required non-zero Mg already covered by Mg=8."
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          // Stage III sustained alkaline groundwater (see v184 note): a
          // constant setpoint (no ops = base held) modeling continuous
          // silica resupply from the percolating aquifer. Window opens at
          // the stage_iii event (which still owns K/Ca/F/pH/T + the story);
          // base is explicit so the movement composes with — rather than
          // captures — whatever the event just set.
          "field": "fluid.SiO2",
          "startStep": 110,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 950,
          "ops": []
        }
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 250.0,    // hot Stage I post-eruption
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,     // vesicle in basalt — atmospheric-ish
        "fluid": {
          // Alkaline silica-rich groundwater leaching the basalt:
          // high SiO2 from glass + plagioclase weathering, low K and F
          // initially — those climb in Stage III when alkali-rich
          // groundwater finally percolates through, gating apophyllite
          // behind that explicit pulse so it doesn't preempt hematite.
          // Iron is already abundant from basalt groundmass leaching;
          // combined with high O2 it lets Stage I deposit hematite
          // needles before Stage III brings apophyllite.
          "SiO2": 900,
          "Ca": 180,
          "CO3": 80,
          "Fe": 180,
          "Mn": 4,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Al": 15,
          "K": 2,
          // Na 40→80 (v201): Deccan amygdule fluids are Na-Ca, and the ordered
          // Na-Ca zeolite mesolite needs BOTH cations — 40 kept Na/(Na+Ca) at
          // ~0.15 (pure-scolecite regime), starving mesolite. 80 opens the
          // mixed-cation window (Na/(Na+Ca) ~0.2-0.3) so mesolite fires while
          // Ca-dominance still favors scolecite. (mesolite is the Poona/Pashan
          // classic; Na-Ca fluid is geologically correct here.)
          "Na": 80,
          "F": 1,
          // V 3 (v210): basalt-weathering vanadium in the percolating groundwater —
          // the chromophore for the prized Poona/Pune GREEN apophyllite (V⁴⁺ drives
          // the colour + dichroism; Rossman 1974, Am.Min. 59(5-6):621-622). A COLOUR
          // dispatcher only — grow_apophyllite reads it for the green-capped render;
          // no V-mineral can fire here (no Pb/Cu/U) so the assemblage is unchanged.
          "V": 3,
          // Audit gap-fill: zeolites carry Sr substituting for Ca.
          "Sr": 2,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 8.2,
          "salinity": 2.0
        },
        // Vesicle in basalt — single primary cavity with minor
        // post-eruption coalescence. Smooth, sub-spherical.
        "wall": {
          // Deccan Traps — degassed-lava amygdale. Spherical archetype:
          // smooth, near-uniform cavity from a single gas bubble.
          "architecture": "spherical",
          "composition": "basalt",
          "thickness_mm": 200.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 8000.0,    // iron-rich basalt host
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 400.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 3,
          "shape_seed": 21,         // Deccan eruption ~66 Ma
          // v184 (see thermal-honesty note): 'no dramatic T excursions',
          // says the scenario — now enforced; gentle stack-cooling drift.
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          "cooling_rate": 0.3
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_silica_veneer",         "name": "Silica Veneer",          "description": "Stage I early chalcedony coating" },
        { "step": 35,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_hematite_pulse",        "name": "Hematite Pulse",         "description": "Iron seeds the vesicle wall — pre-zeolite needle deposition" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "deccan_zeolite_stage_ii",              "name": "Zeolite Stage II",       "description": "Stilbite + heulandite + calcite blades" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "deccan_zeolite_apophyllite_stage_iii", "name": "Apophyllite Stage III", "description": "Alkaline K-Ca-Si-F pulse — apophyllite grows around the hematite needles, producing the 'bloody apophyllite' phantom band" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "deccan_zeolite_late_cooling",          "name": "Late Cooling",           "description": "System cools toward ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Ottens et al. 2019 — Deccan zeolite paragenesis + Stage III timing (21-58 Ma)",
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — Nashik 'bloody apophyllite' phantom inclusions"
      ]
    },

    "radioactive_pegmatite": {
      "anchor": "(generic high-T alkali-granite pocket — not anchored to a specific locality)",
      "description": "High-T pegmatitic fluid + U + Pb. Grows uraninite, smoky quartz (darkened by radiation), feldspar/albite, and late-stage galena from radiogenic Pb.",
      "expects_species": ["uraninite", "autunite", "quartz", "feldspar", "lepidolite", "cassiterite"],
      "duration_steps": 120,
      "notes": [
        "Generic testing scenario — not anchored to a real locality (per the user's clarification on the audit brief). Pegmatitic fluids are silica-saturated melts with abundant K + Na + Al + U.",
        "Mechanic: 4-event lifecycle. Crystallization pulse (step 20): main quartz + uraninite growth. Deep time (step 50): radiation slowly transmutes U → Pb, darkens nearby quartz. Oxidizing meteoric water (step 80): late-stage fracture flow brings O2; sulfides destabilize but uraninite endures. Final cooling (step 100): system approaches ambient, galena precipitates from the radiogenic Pb.",
        "v184 thermal_pulses:false (PEGMATITE-SHAPE, T-rollout close-out): same sealed-pocket logic as gem_pegmatite's v183 flag — the four events anchor the whole arc (450@20, 300@50, 120@80, 50@100) and a sealed granite pocket has no fracture-valve plumbing. The measured violation was worse here: a late ambient pulse re-warmed the 'approaches ambient' endgame to 541°C at one v180 seed — with autunite (a ≤50°C supergene mineral) in the expects list. Dark-observed at 3 seeds: the post-step-100 autunite window (50→25°C) now opens deterministically every run (under pulses it was destroyed whenever a late re-warm landed); pyrite/goethite drop out (they were pulse-Fe-rider artifacts, not expects); autunite itself remains a pre-existing aspirational miss at the observed seeds (absent in BASE too — chemistry-side, a separate tune arc; it fires elsewhere in the 10-seed coverage sweep).",
        "Audit gap-fill (Apr 2026): Mg=5 — brief-required non-zero Mg baseline. Pegmatite pocket fluids are Mg-poor (Mg partitions into outer-shell biotite/chlorite during pegmatite differentiation), matches the gem_pegmatite scenario's Mg=5 abstraction."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=600C, P=2.0 kbar: pegmatite pocket conditions before
        // residual-fluid differentiation pulse drops it to 450C.
        "temperature_C": 600.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 2.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatitic fluids are silica-saturated melts — SiO2 must
          // be well above equilibrium (eq at 600C ~6000 ppm in our
          // model). Real pegmatites have extreme silica activity.
          "SiO2": 12000,
          "Ca": 50,
          "CO3": 20,
          "Fe": 60,
          "Mn": 8,
          "S": 40,
          "F": 25,
          "U": 150,   // primary uraninite source
          "Pb": 30,   // radiogenic Pb seed; grows over event timeline
          "K": 80,
          "Na": 50,
          "Al": 30,
          // Classic pegmatite-defining trace indicators — no current
          // mineral consumes them, but the narrator reads them as
          // beryl/spodumene/tourmaline/apatite country.
          "Be": 20,
          "Li": 40,
          "B": 25,
          "P": 8,
          // Audit gap-fill: brief-required non-zero Mg (pegmatite-pocket low value).
          "Mg": 5,
          // v89 plumbing: Sn for cassiterite. Radioactive pegmatites
          // (Cornwall, Bohemia, Rössing) are typically Sn-bearing —
          // the U enrichment correlates with the same LCT-pegmatite
          // late-stage incompatible-element accumulation that drives
          // Sn into the residual fluid. 60 ppm matches Cornwall fluid-
          // inclusion data for the Sn-bearing greisen-stage horizons
          // (Williamson et al. 2010); cassiterite fires alongside the
          // existing topaz + wolframite W=5 inventory.
          "Sn": 60,
          "O2": 0.0,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        // Pegmatite pocket — fracture-controlled cavity, n=2 "slot" profile
        // (4 primaries + 5 secondaries).
        "wall": {
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 6,
          // v184 (see thermal note): sealed pocket, events anchor the arc;
          // protects the deterministic ≤50°C autunite window.
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_crystallization", "name": "Pegmatite Crystallization", "description": "Main crystallization pulse" },
        { "step": 50,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_deep_time",       "name": "Deep Time",                  "description": "Eons pass — radiation accumulates" },
        { "step": 80,  "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_oxidizing",       "name": "Oxidizing Fluids",           "description": "Late-stage meteoric water" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "radioactive_pegmatite_final_cooling",   "name": "Final Cooling",              "description": "System approaches ambient" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "(generic testing scenario — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "schneeberg": {
      "anchor": "Schneeberg, Erzgebirgskreis (Saxony Ore Mountains), Germany — type locality for torbernite (1772), zeunerite (1872), uranospinite (1873), and ten more uranyl arsenate-phosphate species. Walpurgis Flacher vein, Weisser Hirsch Mine.",
      "description": "Schneeberg / Erzgebirge oxidized uranium-pegmatite vein system (Walpurgis Flacher vein, Weisser Hirsch Mine, Saxony — type locality for torbernite, zeunerite, and uranospinite). A U-bearing pegmatite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primary assemblage weathers under meteoric oxidation; the resulting uranyl + Cu + As fluid plates the autunite-group secondaries in two cation phases — Cu-rich first (torbernite emerald greens then zeunerite as As-pulse arrives), then Ca-dominant after Cu is consumed (autunite + uranospinite, the bright LW-UV fluorescent yellows).",
      "expects_species": ["uraninite", "torbernite", "zeunerite", "autunite", "uranospinite", "native_bismuth", "native_arsenic", "erythrite", "annabergite", "cobaltite", "nickeline", "cassiterite", "pharmacolite", "haidingerite"],
      "duration_steps": 160,
      "movements": [
        {
          // v185 EVENT-SUBSUMPTION — the meteoric front as a declared redox
          // sentence. Reducing pegmatitic plateau (−200 mV ≡ the ehFromO2
          // floor at O2:0) holds until the step-85 meteoric flood, then a
          // ~8-step swing to +290 mV (O2 1.5) — the swing IS sulfide-buffer
          // exhaustion (pyrite/arsenopyrite eat the first oxygen before Eh
          // can climb). at 0.8 = step 88/110, soften = 8/110 → ramp 84→92.
          // The window ends at the step-110 vadose exhumation: a redox
          // movement lives in GROUNDWATER; once the water table drops, air
          // owns redox (the vadose O2 floor 1.8 ≡ +322 mV — the flat 322
          // the strip always showed after 110 was the air, not the broth).
          // DETERMINISTIC (no texture): measured — OU wobble re-rolls the
          // 1-crystal marginals (naumannite, metazeunerite) without honest
          // signal; the buffered plateau doesn't flutter and the As-pulse
          // EVENTS are the real punctuation. Gate verified at 8 seeds
          // (tools/eh-subsumption-observe.mjs): every lineage at BASE rate,
          // reducing-era nucleations byte-identical (naumannite @67,
          // native_bismuth @70 untouched).
          "field": "fluid.Eh",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 110,
          "base": -200,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "step", "amp": 490, "at": 0.8, "soften": 0.07272727272727272 }]
        }
      ],
      "notes": [
        "The mineralogically richest single ore district in Europe — the Erzgebirge had been mined for silver since the 1100s, then bismuth from the 1500s (the very name 'Bismutum' was coined here), then uranium from the 1800s onward. Most autunite-group species were first described from Schneeberg or its sister deposits (Jáchymov, Annaberg). Pinch & Wilson 1977 monographs are the canonical reference.",
        "Mechanic: 6-event lifecycle walking through cation×anion combinatorics. Pegmatite crystallization (step 20): hot reducing fluid grows uraninite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primaries. Cooling (step 70): T drops to ambient. Cu+P phase (step 85): O2 floods, primaries weather, P>As, Cu>Ca → torbernite plates. Cu+As pulse (step 105): As replenishes from arsenopyrite weathering, Cu still high → zeunerite plates. Cu depletion (step 125): Cu consumed by both Cu-cation secondaries; Ca rises from carbonate dissolution → autunite plates. As pulse late (step 145): As replenishes again, Ca dominant → uranospinite plates.",
        "First scenario to fire all 4 P/As-branch uranyl species (torbernite, autunite, zeunerite, uranospinite) in a single run. The cation+anion fork mechanic introduced by Rounds 9b-9e is finally exercised end-to-end. Uraninite weathers as the v12 gatekeeper feedstock event."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=450°C, P=1.5 kbar: pegmatitic residual fluid before
        // crystallization pulse drops it to ambient.
        "temperature_C": 450.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Pegmatite-saturated silica melt
          "SiO2": 8000,
          // Moderate Ca — will become dominant cation after Cu depletes.
          // Carbonate buffer ~20 from limestone country rock contact.
          "Ca": 50,
          "CO3": 20,
          "F": 20,
          // U=100: enough for primary uraninite at high T, plus broth
          // recharge during weathering. The v12 gatekeeper releases
          // ~7 ppm U per uraninite dissolution step (60% of 12% × ~100 µm).
          "U": 100,
          // Cu=80, Fe=40, S=30: chalcopyrite-saturating composition.
          // Cu also feeds torbernite + zeunerite during the supergene phase.
          "Cu": 80,
          "Fe": 40,
          "S": 30,
          // As=60: enough for arsenopyrite primary + post-weathering As
          // pulse for zeunerite/uranospinite + native_arsenic paragenetic
          // step-down. Bumped further by events. (Was 15 pre-2026-05;
          // bumped during the Path C cascade-gate audit Arc 2 — the
          // soft-suppressor gate fix made σ non-zero but the prior
          // seed of 15 ppm kept as_f below the realistic threshold for a
          // residual-overflow phase. Förster 1992 fluid-inclusion data
          // for Schneeberg reports As 100-1000 ppm in arsenide-rich
          // phases; 60 ppm is the conservative anchor that lets the
          // canonical native_arsenic + native_bismuth coexistence — the
          // historically-defining feature of the Schneeberg ore type —
          // actually fire under bulk-view chemistry.)
          "As": 60,
          // P=12: phosphate for torbernite/autunite. Replenishment events
          // swing the P/As ratio across the run.
          "P": 12,
          // K=30: alkali pegmatite background; not enough to fire carnotite
          // (no V), and the cation gate filters by K/(K+Ca) anyway.
          "K": 30,
          // Pegmatite-defining traces — narrator reads these as Erzgebirge
          // country (beryl, spodumene, tourmaline, native bismuth).
          "Pb": 5,
          "Al": 25,
          "Mn": 5,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Be": 10,
          "Li": 15,
          "B": 12,
          // Bismuth — Schneeberg was named for its bismuth mining before
          // the uranium era. Bismuthinite + native_bismuth secondary phases
          // can form alongside the uranyls. (Was 10 pre-2026-05; bumped to
          // 40 during the Path C cascade-gate audit Arc 2 — the gate-
          // softening + bi_f scaling tightening still wasn't enough at
          // Bi=10. Förster 1992 Schneeberg fluid-inclusion data puts Bi at
          // 50-500 ppm in native-bismuth-bearing phases; 40 ppm is the
          // conservative anchor that lets the historic Schneeberg ore-type
          // assemblage — including the type-defining native bismuth — fire
          // in a bulk-view chemistry simulation.)
          "Bi": 40,
          // Co=30, Ni=20, Ag=8 — the BiCoNiAgAs five-element vein heritage
          // that pre-Path-C-audit the broth was silently missing. Schneeberg-
          // Annaberg-Jáchymov defined the "Fünfelementformation" (five-
          // element formation) class of deposits: native_bismuth, native_silver,
          // Co arsenides (cobaltite + safflorite + skutterudite), Ni arsenides
          // (nickeline + rammelsbergite), and native_arsenic / arsenopyrite
          // coexisting in the same vein. The 10-seed geology audit
          // (2026-05-18) found erythrite + annabergite firing 0/10 seeds in
          // schneeberg despite Annaberg being annabergite's TYPE LOCALITY
          // and erythrite/cobalt arsenides being the source of the historic
          // 16th-century "Saxon blue" pigment trade. Root cause: Co/Ni
          // simply weren't in the seed broth.
          //   Co=30: Burkhardt et al. 2001 reports Co 5-50 ppm in Erzgebirge
          //          arsenide-vein fluid inclusions; 30 is the conservative
          //          mid-range for the cobaltite + erythrite cascade.
          //   Ni=20: same paper reports Ni 5-30 ppm; 20 enables nickeline +
          //          annabergite.
          //   Ag=8:  Schneeberg's pre-bismuth-era SILVER mining (1100s-1500s,
          //          original deposit-defining commodity) implies Ag was
          //          always present. The "Ag=0 + waits for event" plan
          //          encoded in earlier scenario versions never landed an
          //          Ag-delivery event. 8 ppm matches typical native-silver-
          //          plus-acanthite five-element-vein fluids and enables
          //          naumannite (already partially seeded Se=2).
          "Co": 30,
          "Ni": 20,
          "Ag": 8,
          // v62 plumbing: Se for the new selenide engines. Schneeberg /
          // Jáchymov / Příbram all carry the classic clausthalite +
          // naumannite + tiemannite + berzelianite low-S selenide assemblage
          // (Pinch & Wilson 1977 documents the Erzgebirge selenide veins).
          // Pb=5 is below clausthalite's Pb≥20 nucleation threshold so
          // clausthalite waits for the Pb pulse. 2 ppm Se enables
          // naumannite once Ag is also present (now seeded at 8 ppm above —
          // 2026-05 gap-fill).
          "Se": 2,
          // v89 plumbing: Sn for cassiterite. Erzgebirge was named
          // for the Saxon tin trade (Annaberg/Schneeberg silver and
          // bismuth came LATER, the pre-1500s mining was for Sn —
          // hence "Erzgebirge" / "Ore Mountains" itself meant tin
          // mountains before it meant silver). The Walpurgis Flacher
          // and adjacent veins host minor cassiterite in greisen
          // zones (Förster 1992 fluid inclusions document Sn 50-300
          // ppm in late-pegmatite Erzgebirge fluids). 60 ppm is the
          // conservative anchor that lets cassiterite fire alongside
          // the wolframite/topaz pegmatite phase. v85 already added
          // W via the wolframite engine; cassiterite's Sn-W greisen
          // pair completes the historic Erzgebirge tin signature.
          "Sn": 60,
          // Strongly reducing initial — required for uraninite + sulfides.
          "O2": 0.0,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 6.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): Schneeberg is the
          // canonical five-element vein deposit, hosted in the
          // Walpurgis Flacher (German for "flat vein") at the
          // Weisser Hirsch Mine. Five-element veins are STEEP TABULAR
          // fissure-fills along Variscan brittle-shear structures —
          // the cavity here is a slot in the vein, not a smooth
          // pegmatite pocket. 'tabular' archetype encodes the
          // anisotropic stretch (~3:1) of a vein-hosted cavity.
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 9,
          // v163: supergene/near-surface regime — no magmatic thermal pulses.
          // The cold (18-30°C) supergene U-mica stages were being spuriously
          // reheated >75°C by the ambient_cooling pulse mechanic, which forced
          // the meta- uranyl forms via the wrong (heat) path. With pulses off,
          // the schneeberg_vadose_exhumation event (step 110) supplies the
          // correct dry-air dehydration driver instead.
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "schneeberg_pegmatite_crystallization", "name": "Pegmatite Crystallization", "description": "Reducing pegmatitic fluid grows uraninite + chalcopyrite + arsenopyrite primaries" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "schneeberg_cooling",                   "name": "Cooling",                    "description": "T drops to ambient supergene window; primaries finish forming" },
        { "step": 85,  "type": "schneeberg_cu_p_phase",                "name": "Cu+P Oxidation",             "description": "Meteoric water floods; primaries weather; P>As, Cu>Ca → torbernite plates" },
        { "step": 105, "type": "schneeberg_cu_as_pulse",               "name": "Cu+As Pulse",                "description": "Arsenopyrite-derived As replenishes; As>P, Cu still dominant → zeunerite plates" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "schneeberg_vadose_exhumation",         "name": "Vein Exhumed (water table drops)", "description": "Uranyl-mica crusts pass into the vadose zone; dry-air dehydration → metatorbernite + metazeunerite (the honest meta- path, replacing the spurious thermal-pulse heat path)" },
        { "step": 125, "type": "schneeberg_cu_depletion",              "name": "Cu Depletion",               "description": "Cu consumed by torbernite+zeunerite; Ca rises (carbonate dissolution) → autunite plates" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "schneeberg_as_pulse_late",             "name": "Late As Pulse",              "description": "Final arsenate replenishment; Ca dominant → uranospinite plates, the bright fluorescent yellow finishes the assemblage" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — canonical Schneeberg/Erzgebirge monograph",
        "Weisbach 1872 — zeunerite type description (Walpurgis Flacher vein)",
        "Weisbach 1873 — uranospinite type description (Weisser Hirsch Mine)",
        "Klaproth 1789 — uranium discovery in Schneeberg pitchblende",
        "research/research-uranospinite.md (May 2026) — cation-fork mechanic + paragenesis"
      ]
    },

    "wittichen": {
      "anchor": "Kloster Wittichen, Schwarzwald (Black Forest), Baden-Württemberg, Germany — the classic Bi-Co-Ni-Ag-As-(Ba) five-element vein district; cobalt-pigment + silver mining boom 1730s–40s around the convent. Sophia and Johann-Georg veins.",
      "description": "A five-element vein in granite basement: hot, saline, SULFUR-STARVED brine carries Bi + Co + Ni + Ag + As. S ~3 ppm is load-bearing — bismuthinite and acanthite never gate open, so the metals stay NATIVE and arsenides are the metal sinks. Hot stage grows skutterudite + nickeline rosettes (320–420°C); cooling brings the fluid into bismuth's window; then the deposit-defining REDUCING SHOCK (hydrocarbon influx along the fault — the declared fluid.Eh pulse) slams native-metal σ to its structural ceiling and bismuth precipitates as ARBORESCENT DENDRITES, safflorite riming the fresh branches (its T window overlaps the shock). Late meteoric water brings oxidized sulfate (barite stage) and carbonate gangue seals the dendrites into the vein — the cross-section hand specimen of the class.",
      "expects_species": ["skutterudite", "nickeline", "safflorite", "native_bismuth", "native_arsenic", "native_silver", "proustite", "acanthite", "calcite", "aragonite", "barite"],
      "duration_steps": 160,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor + mechanism: Kissin 1992 (Canadian Mineralogist 30) defines the five-element class; Burisch et al. 2017 (Geology 45) ties the native-metal stage to methane/hydrocarbon influx — fluid inclusions in Schwarzwald five-element veins carry CH4 exactly at the dendrite stage, and the reduction is fast (hours-to-days), which is WHY the metals dendrite. Scharrer, Kreissl & Markl 2019 (Ore Geology Reviews) survey the assemblage diversity; Staude et al. 2012 (Mineralium Deposita 47) give the Schwarzwald basement-brine fluid-inclusion record (20–26 wt% NaCl, 150–340°C) this broth is anchored on.",
        "The redox shock is a DECLARED fluid.Eh movement (event-subsumption discipline, v185/v186): base −20 mV (mildly reducing basement brine), ONE deep pulse (amp −320) at u=0.58 (the CH4 influx; width ~8 steps; measured floor ~−253 mV at seed 42), and a late oxidizing trend (+95 ease — meteoric tail, tuned DOWN from +140 which dissolved the arsenide suite; a stronger late-oxidation finger was tried and reverted for the same reason — barite/erythrite are the documented aspirational casualties of arsenide survival). The wittichen_hydrocarbon_influx event at the pulse center is NARRATIVE-ONLY (no fluid writes).",
        "Engine fit: this is the morphology registry's dendrite-band tenant (MORPH_TH.native_bismuth, SIM 188 — RESEARCH-bismuth-morphology-2026-06-12.md). At the shock, Bi σ ≈ bi_f 3.0 × s_mask 0.96 × red_f 1.5 × T_f 1.0 ≈ 4.3 — the dendritic band (≥3.8) of a scale structurally capped at ~4.5. Pre-shock cooling-stage Bi sits in the feathery bands; post-shock regrowth heals feathery over the dendrites, so the zone stack RECORDS the shock (the narrator's healed-over paragraph + the bismuth_morph strip chip slamming 0→4 on the pulse). Skutterudite + safflorite get their FIRST scenario home here (both were expects-orphans fleet-wide).",
        "Wallrock: 'pegmatite' composition as the granite proxy (inert silicate — Wittichen veins cut Triberg granite; the carbonate gangue arrives in the FLUID via the late CO3 event, not from wall dissolution). Architecture tabular (vein-bounded), pocket size class, shape_seed 1736 (the cobalt-boom decade).",
        "Calibration target: the hand specimen is silver-white dendritic Bi embedded in white carbonate with gray arsenide rims, read in cross-section. MEASURED at seeds 42-45 (calibration session, 2026-06-12): native_bismuth 3-5 alive with 45-49% DENDRITIC zone mass (the shock recorded); skutterudite 2 + safflorite 2 + nickeline 4 + native_arsenic 4 all ALIVE; native_silver grows then sulfidizes to acanthite 4 at the meteoric-sulfate stage (the tarnish story — hand-specimen Wittichen silver is acanthite-coated); proustite 2 (ruby silver); calcite + aragonite gangue. Bi band edges re-pinned against this trajectory (js/45 — the activity correction at salinity 24 compresses the structural ~4.5 ceiling to ~2.4 measured).",
        "BARITE DELIVERED (v191, gate-census tune): the v189 'aspirational barite' diagnosis was WRONG about the mechanism — the gate census (tools/wittichen-sulfate-probe.mjs) measured every gate component PASSING from step ~133 (Ba✓ S✓ redox✓ pH✓ T✓) with σ plateaued at 0.60: barite never needed more OXIDATION, it needed more BARIUM (ba_f 24/30 × s_f 30/40 × the salinity-24 activity penalty ≈ 0.59 pinned σ under 1 forever). The locality is the authority: Wittichen's veins are literally Barytgänge — barite-gangue veins, the district's defining gangue — so Ba 24 was unjustifiably shy. Ba 75 (still modest for a heavy-spar district) puts the barite stage at σ 1.47–1.55 from the meteoric beat on: barite 2/6/3 crystals at seeds 42/43/44, NO witherite (the BaCO3 competitor never gates), and the living suite intact at all probed seeds. No Eh change — the reverted +100 oxidation finger stays reverted.",
        "ERYTHRITE DEMOTED from expects (v191, measured): the cobalt bloom's gate needs T ≤ 50°C (MINERAL_GATES_erythrite — weathering-zone physics) and this scenario's T trajectory ends at ~150°C, so erythrite is STRUCTURALLY out-of-window in a sealed-vein story, not tuning-shy. The real Wittichen erythrite the 1730s miners followed formed during post-Variscan exhumation weathering, long after the vein sealed; modeling it honestly needs a vadose/weathering EPILOGUE (drain + cool to ~20°C + spatially-partial oxidation), which contradicts this scenario's closing beat (carbonate seals the vug at ~150°C). If a weathering-epilogue mechanic ever lands (the schneeberg step-110 vadose pattern, made spatially partial), erythrite is its first client — logged in BACKLOG, not in expects."
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "temperature",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 160,
          "base": 340,
          "ops": [
            { "kind": "trend", "amp": -190, "ease": true }
          ]
        },
        {
          "field": "fluid.Eh",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 160,
          "base": -20,
          "ops": [
            { "kind": "pulse", "amp": -320, "center": 0.58, "width": 0.05 },
            { "kind": "trend", "amp": 95, "ease": true }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 340.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.9,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 80,
          "Ca": 250,
          "CO3": 45,
          "Mg": 20,
          "Fe": 10,
          "Mn": 3,
          "Bi": 50,
          "Co": 35,
          "Ni": 20,
          "As": 120,
          "Ag": 12,
          "Ba": 75,
          "Sr": 4,
          "S": 3,
          "Na": 120,
          "K": 40,
          "Cl": 400,
          "F": 3,
          "O2": 0.15,
          "pH": 6.2,
          "salinity": 24
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "pegmatite",
          "reactivity": 0,
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "size_class": "pocket",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 1736
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 93, "type": "wittichen_hydrocarbon_influx", "name": "Hydrocarbon Influx", "description": "CH4-bearing fluid floods the vein — the reducing shock arrives (narrative marker; the declared Eh movement carries the chemistry)" },
        { "step": 134, "type": "wittichen_meteoric_sulfate", "name": "Meteoric Sulfate", "description": "Cooled meteoric water brings oxidized sulfate — the barite stage" },
        { "step": 142, "type": "wittichen_carbonate_gangue", "name": "Carbonate Gangue", "description": "CO3 + Ca influx — calcite seals the dendrites into the vein" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Kissin S.A. 1992, Canadian Mineralogist 30 — Five-element (Ni-Co-As-Ag-Bi) veins: the deposit-class review",
        "Burisch M., Walter B.F., Gerdes A., Lanz M., Markl G. 2017, Geology 45 — Methane and the origin of five-element veins (the hydrocarbon reduction trigger)",
        "Scharrer M., Kreissl S., Markl G. 2019, Ore Geology Reviews — The mineralogical variability of hydrothermal native element-arsenide associations",
        "Staude S., Bons P.D., Markl G. 2012, Mineralium Deposita 47 — Schwarzwald hydrothermal veins: fluid inclusion record, 20-26 wt% NaCl basement brines",
        "Markl G. et al. 2016 — Cobalt (Ontario) arsenide zoning, X_As 0.96-0.99 (the skutterudite engine's anchor citation)",
        "Kloster Wittichen district history — cobalt-blue pigment + silver boom, 1730s-1740s (shape_seed 1736)"
      ]
    },
    "tormiq_alpine_cleft": {
      "anchor": "Tormiq Valley, Haramosh Mts., Roundu/Skardu District, Gilgit-Baltistan, Pakistan — the world's premier ALPINE-CLEFT epidote locality (Anthony et al. Handbook of Mineralogy 2001 names Tormiq type-quality, rivaling Knappenwand, Austria). The anchor scenario for epidote (added v196).",
      "description": "A Himalayan alpine-type cleft: fractures opened by Main Karakoram Thrust activity in AMPHIBOLITE / metabasite, then filled by a LOW-SALINITY, OXIDIZED, meteoric-metamorphic fluid in brittle channelized flow (<450°C, cooling to <200°C). The oxidized character is load-bearing — it keeps iron FERRIC, so the cleft grows lustrous pistachio-green EPIDOTE (the Fe³⁺ phase) rather than Fe-poor clinozoisite, with the doubly-terminated 'Tormiq sword' habit in the open fissure. Paragenesis: quartz lining → Ti-Fe oxides → the epidote main stage → byssolite (fibrous actinolite) sprays → adularia (K-feldspar) → late calcite. NOT a pegmatite (the region's other deposit type) — no tourmaline/beryl/spodumene; this is the metamorphic-fissure Ca-Al-Fe³⁺ assemblage.",
      "expects_species": ["epidote", "actinolite", "quartz", "feldspar", "albite", "fluorite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Anthony, Bideaux, Bladh & Nichols 2001, Handbook of Mineralogy (epidote sheet), which names Tormiq, Pakistan as a type-quality locality. Geology per mindat loc-5734: Tormiq lower valley = granite + amphibolite + ultramafic, central/upper = metasedimentary + metavolcanic; the epidote clefts are tied to the amphibolite/metabasite (the Ca-Al-Fe³⁺ source). Tectonic driver = Main Karakoram Thrust fracturing near the Nanga Parbat-Haramosh massif. Sub-localities Alchuri + Hashupa (Shigar) share the model.",
        "Fluid: alpine-cleft fissures carry a LOW-SALINITY (~1-3 wt% NaCl eq), OXIDIZED, meteoric-metamorphic fluid in brittle channelized flow at <450°C, retrograde to <200°C (Central-Alps analogue; Mullis 1994 GCA 58:2239 fluid inclusions; Bergemann et al. 2017 Swiss J. Geosci. fissure formation episodes). No published Tormiq fluid-inclusion ppm dataset exists — the broth is an order-of-magnitude design target inferred from alpine-cleft fluid character + epidote stoichiometry, to be calibrated against seed-42 per the tune-scenario loop.",
        "Engine fit: epidote's discriminator is REDOX (engine v196) — it gates on oxideRedoxAvailable O2>=0.5 on top of Ca/Al/Fe/Si + T 200-450. This broth holds O2 ~1.5 (strongly oxidizing → Fe³⁺ → deep pistachio green) across the run, with an Fe³⁺ pulse at the epidote_main stage. The cooling sweep (420→170°C via the event handlers) carries the fluid through epidote's 250-400 sweet spot for most of the run. byssolite = the actinolite engine (Mg+Fe+Ca+Si, no redox gate); adularia = feldspar (K+Al+Si); the cleft lining = quartz; late = calcite. Titanite, clinozoisite, and zoisite (true Tormiq associates) are not yet in the catalog — magnetite stands in for the Ti-Fe oxide stage; feldspar for adularia; actinolite for byssolite.",
        "Wallrock: 'basalt' composition as the amphibolite proxy (inert silicate — amphibolite is metamorphosed basalt; the Ca-Al-Fe³⁺ arrives in the FLUID, not from wall dissolution). Architecture pocket (alpine cleft), pocket size class, shape_seed 1990 (the decade Tormiq epidote reached the international market).",
        "Calibration target: the hand specimen is a lustrous dark-pistachio-green doubly-terminated epidote prism (or a divergent spray on byssolite) perched on a quartz-lined cleft wall, sometimes with adularia + calcite. Epidote IS the star. MEASURED at seed 42 (16 crystals, 6 species): epidote 5 (the most abundant — capped at max_nucleation 5), actinolite/byssolite 4 (secondary, as intended), albite 2 + adularia/feldspar 2 + quartz 2 + fluorite 1. This is a textbook alpine-cleft suite — epidote + byssolite + adularia + albite + quartz + pink fluorite are all genuine Tormiq/alpine-fissure associates. CALCITE is aspirational (the late_calcite event raises CO3 but calcite did not nucleate in the final ~30 steps at seed 42) — a vugg-tune-scenario follow-up candidate (bump late CO3 / extend the cooling tail), not shipped as a false expects entry."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 420.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 4.0,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 320,
          "Ca": 600,
          "Al": 12,
          "Fe": 40,
          "Mg": 25,
          "Mn": 2,
          "K": 120,
          "CO3": 50,
          "Na": 200,
          "Cl": 300,
          "Sr": 2,
          "Ti": 1,
          "P": 1,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 3
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "basalt",
          "reactivity": 0,
          "architecture": "pocket",
          "size_class": "pocket",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1990
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 25,  "type": "tormiq_quartz_lining", "name": "Cleft Opens — Quartz Lining", "description": "A Karakoram-Thrust fracture opens; oxidized metamorphic fluid lines the walls with quartz" },
        { "step": 50,  "type": "tormiq_oxide_stage",   "name": "Ti-Fe Oxide Stage",          "description": "Magnetite (+ titanite, not modelled) crust the cleft walls from amphibolite-leached Fe + Ti" },
        { "step": 80,  "type": "tormiq_epidote_main",  "name": "The Epidote Stage",          "description": "Oxidized Ca-Al-Fe³⁺ fluid grows the pistachio-green Tormiq gem swords" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "tormiq_byssolite",     "name": "Byssolite Sprays",           "description": "Fibrous actinolite sprays; epidote nucleates on the amphibole mats as fans" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "tormiq_adularia",      "name": "Adularia Stage",             "description": "Lower-T cleft K-feldspar (adularia) crystallizes" },
        { "step": 170, "type": "tormiq_late_calcite",  "name": "Late Calcite — Cooling",     "description": "Below ~200°C, calcite seals the paragenesis and growth winds down" },
        { "step": 188, "type": "tormiq_late_shear",     "name": "Late Karakoram-Thrust Shearing", "description": "Continued thrust motion plastically bends the sealed cleft's early quartz lining — a post-growth tectonic overprint",
          "deformation": { "style": "bend", "magnitude": 0.55, "minerals": ["quartz"] } }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Anthony, Bideaux, Bladh & Nichols 2001, Handbook of Mineralogy (epidote sheet — names Tormiq, Pakistan as type-quality)",
        "Deer, Howie & Zussman 1986, Rock-Forming Minerals 2nd ed. v.1B, pp.44-134 (epidote group)",
        "Liebscher A. & Franz G. eds. 2004, Reviews in Mineralogy & Geochemistry v.56 Epidotes (MSA)",
        "Mullis J. 1994, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta 58:2239 — alpine fissure quartz fluid inclusions (low-salinity, oxidized, meteoric)",
        "Bergemann C. et al. 2017, Swiss J. Geosci. — alpine fissure formation episodes (T/fluid regime)",
        "Holdaway M.J. 1972, Contrib. Mineral. Petrol. 37:307; Liou J.G. 1973, J. Petrol. 14:381 — epidote stability vs fO2 (why oxidized = Fe³⁺ green epidote)",
        "mindat locality 5734 — Tormiq Valley geology (Main Karakoram Thrust clefts in amphibolite)"
      ]
    },
    "grimsel_alpine_cleft": {
      "anchor": "Grimsel Pass / central Aar massif, Bernese-Uri Alps, Switzerland — the type region of the Swiss alpine-cleft (Zerrkluft) SMOKY-QUARTZ suite (with Göscheneralp, Furka, Gotthard analogues). The granite-hosted counterpart to the amphibolite-hosted epidote cleft (tormiq_alpine_cleft); the content home for the quartz-morphology arc (sceptre / Tessin / fenster / gwindel).",
      "description": "A Swiss Central-Alps tension fissure (Zerrkluft) in the Variscan Aar granite, opened and RE-OPENED episodically during late-Alpine collision and retrograde exhumation. A dilute (~1-3 wt% NaCl eq), OXIDIZING, CO2-bearing, near-neutral meteoric-metamorphic fluid lines the walls; smoky quartz nucleates at ~450C and grows down the retrograde path, stopping near 200C at 0.3-0.45 GPa. The crack-seal cycle is the signature: each tectonic re-opening seals (silica supply cut, growth halts) then breaches (a fresh silica-charged pulse at a now-cooler temperature), and because quartz solubility falls as the cleft cools, each breach drives a HIGHER supersaturation than the hot first-generation stem — overgrowing the tip with a wider second-generation cap (the alpine SCEPTRE). Paragenesis: adularia + chlorite coatings -> smoky quartz (the volumetric main stage) -> hematite iron-roses (the Fe3+ oxidizing marker) -> wedge titanite + apatite + pink fluorite -> late calcite. The oxidizing character (hematite, not pyrite) is the Aar redox tell, distinct from the reducing CH4 fissure zone to the north.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz", "feldspar", "titanite", "hematite", "fluorite", "apatite", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Mullis, Dubessy, Poty & O'Neil 1994 (Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta 58:2239-2267) — fissure-quartz fluid inclusions along a Central-Alps geotraverse (dilute, oxidizing, H2O-CO2 epizone). Retrograde P-T-t: Mullis 1996 (Schweiz. Mineral. Petrogr. Mitt. 76:159-164) quartz forms ~450-550C cooling to ~200C at 0.3-0.45 GPa; Gnos, Mullis & Bergemann 2025 (Swiss J. Geosci. 118:12) tie the Grimsel cleft path to D1 (~450C/440MPa, ~14.6 Ma) -> D2 (~385C/325MPa) -> D3 (~330->300C/230MPa) deformation stages. Poty 1969 (PhD thesis, Univ. Nancy) measured fissure quartz at 350-420C. Citations web-verified 2026-06-19 per the cross-check discipline.",
        "T story = a DECLARED temperature movement (retrograde 450->200C trend, no texture, the naica v182 idiom) + thermal_pulses:false + cooling_rate:0.4 (an open feeder advects heat -> slow cooling, not random magmatic re-warm pulses). The events are the chemistry BEATS that compose with it (SiO2 sawtooth + Fe/CO3 stage pulses on different fields -> no same-field clobber).",
        "The SCEPTRE mechanism: sigma_quartz = SiO2 / silica_equilibrium(T), and eq(T) falls from ~1400 ppm at 450C to ~300 at 200C. A crack-seal SEAL drops SiO2 below eq (sigma<1 -> a growth HIATUS); the following BREACH re-floods fresh silica at a cooler temperature, so the same SiO2 load gives a HIGHER sigma than the hot first-generation stem -> a wider cap nucleates on the tip. Caps grow cooler than stems (the documented alpine-sceptre habit) falls straight out of the engine. Two seal/breach cycles -> two sceptre generations; verified by tools/quartz-hiatus-census.mjs.",
        "Wallrock: pegmatite (the granite/granitoid inert-silicate proxy — the Aar granite host; the Ca-Al-Fe-Ti-F-P arrive in the FLUID, not from wall dissolution, reactivity 0). Architecture pocket (alpine cleft = the canonical pocket archetype), pocket size class, shape_seed 1932 (the Grimsel hydroelectric era that opened the cleft tunnels to strahlers).",
        "Calibration target: a free-grown cleft druse — cream blocky adularia + dark-green chlorite coatings, from which rise lustrous SMOKY quartz crystals (Tessin-habit prisms or smoky sceptres with wider darker caps), accented by metallic hematite iron-roses, honey-brown wedge titanite, small apatite prisms, and a late calcite lining. expects_species declared aspirationally where needed; observe seed-42 firing + the hiatus census, then tune (vugg-tune-scenario) before the quartz-morphology work (#109). Smoky quartz color + the sceptre/Tessin/fenster/gwindel morphology are the follow-on tasks #110/#109."
      ],
      "movements": [
        {
          "field": "temperature",
          "startStep": 0,
          "endStep": 200,
          "base": 450,
          "ops": [{ "kind": "trend", "amp": -250, "ease": true }]
        }
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 450.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 4.4,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 1550,
          "K": 30,
          "Al": 6,
          "Ca": 200,
          "Fe": 30,
          "Mg": 10,
          "F": 12,
          "P": 40,
          "Ti": 1,
          "CO3": 30,
          "Na": 25,
          "Cl": 25,
          "Sr": 2,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 2
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "pegmatite",
          "reactivity": 0,
          "architecture": "pocket",
          "size_class": "pocket",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1932,
          "thermal_pulses": false,
          "cooling_rate": 0.4,
          "alpine_cleft": true
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 15,  "type": "grimsel_cleft_open",     "name": "Cleft Opens (D1)",        "description": "Oxidized Aar-granite fluid lines the walls; gen-1 smoky quartz + adularia" },
        { "step": 45,  "type": "grimsel_seal_1",         "name": "Fissure Seals",           "description": "Silica supply cut; SiO2 drops below saturation; gen-1 growth halts (hiatus)" },
        { "step": 65,  "type": "grimsel_breach_1",       "name": "Cleft Re-opens (D2)",     "description": "Fresh silica pulse at cooler T; supersaturation surges; wider sceptre cap" },
        { "step": 90,  "type": "grimsel_oxide_roses",    "name": "Iron-Rose Stage",         "description": "Hematite Fe3+ rosettes (Eisenrosen) perch on the quartz" },
        { "step": 115, "type": "grimsel_seal_2",         "name": "Fissure Re-seals",        "description": "Second seal; silica drops; second growth hiatus" },
        { "step": 135, "type": "grimsel_breach_2",       "name": "Cleft Re-opens (D3)",     "description": "Coolest fresh pulse; highest supersaturation; tallest sceptre cap" },
        { "step": 165, "type": "grimsel_late_carbonate", "name": "Late Carbonate Stage",    "description": "CO2 + Ca close the cleft: calcite + fluorite + apatite + titanite wedges" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Mullis, Dubessy, Poty & O'Neil 1994, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta 58(10):2239-2267 — fissure-quartz fluid inclusions, Central Alps geotraverse",
        "Mullis 1996, Schweiz. Mineral. Petrogr. Mitt. 76:159-164 — P-T-t path of quartz formation in extensional veins of the Central Alps",
        "Gnos, Mullis & Bergemann 2025, Swiss J. Geosci. 118(1):12 — P-T-t of successive deformation stages, Aar Massif (the D1/D2/D3 crack-seal spine)",
        "Poty 1969, PhD thesis Univ. Nancy — La croissance des cristaux de quartz dans les filons (La Gardette + Mont-Blanc; fissure quartz 350-420C)",
        "Rossman 1994, Reviews in Mineralogy 29:433-467 (MSA) — the colored varieties of silica (smoky-quartz Al + irradiation color-center mechanism)",
        "quartzpage.de — alpine-type fissures, quartz habits (Tessin / sceptre / gwindel), smoky quartz (careful secondary synthesis)"
      ]
    },
    "colorado_plateau": {
      "anchor": "Uravan Mineral Belt, Colorado Plateau — sandstone-hosted roll-front uranium-vanadium deposits (Triassic-Jurassic Morrison Formation). Includes the Carnotite-Eldorado, Uravan, and Moab districts; the V+U bonanza that drove the early-twentieth-century uranium industry decades before the Manhattan Project.",
      "description": "Uravan Mineral Belt sandstone roll-front uranium-vanadium deposit (Roc Creek, Montrose County, CO — carnotite type locality, Friedel & Cumenge 1899). Oxidizing groundwater carries U + V + K + Ca through Triassic-Jurassic Morrison Formation sandstones until it meets a reducing barrier (petrified wood, carbonaceous shale), where the metals drop out as bright canary-yellow uranyl-vanadate crusts. Carnotite + tyuyamunite are the two diagnostic species — interconvertible by cation exchange, drawn apart by whichever of K/Ca dominates the local pore fluid.",
      "expects_species": ["carnotite", "tyuyamunite"],
      "duration_steps": 180,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Colorado Plateau uranium districts (Uravan Mineral Belt). Mineralogy first described by Friedel & Cumenge (1899) at Roc Creek (Montrose County, CO); Hess (1924) characterized the V-U-Ca-K paragenesis. The Vanadium Corporation of America (VCA) operated the Uravan mill from 1915-1944 turning carnotite into V₂O₅ (steel alloy) before the Manhattan Project shifted demand to uranium.",
        "Mechanic: 5-event sandstone roll-front lifecycle. Initial: oxidizing surface groundwater carries U+V+K+Ca at ambient T. Step 20 (groundwater pulse): more U + V flushes through the system, Ca dominates K initially → tyuyamunite plates. Step 60 (roll-front contact): Fe rises (organic-iron proxy for petrified wood / carbonaceous shale), T drops, slight reducing pulse — concentrates carnotite + tyuyamunite at the redox front. Step 100 (cation oscillation): K rises (evaporite-style salt concentration in the arid surface zone), K/(K+Ca) crosses 0.5 → carnotite plates. Step 140 (Ca recovery): Ca returns dominant → second tyuyamunite phase. Step 165 (arid stabilization): system stabilizes, both species coexist.",
        "First scenario to fire carnotite + tyuyamunite, completing the autunite-group cation+anion fork coverage when paired with Schneeberg (which fires the Cu/Ca pair on the P+As branches)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=22°C, P=0.05 kbar: ambient near-surface roll-front conditions.
        "temperature_C": 22.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          // Sandstone matrix — moderate silica
          "SiO2": 200,
          // Ca dominant by background (groundwater Ca-bicarbonate)
          "Ca": 100,
          "CO3": 60,
          // U=15: realistic Colorado Plateau roll-front loading — enough
          // to cross the U>=0.3 secondary gates with margin. Bumped during
          // groundwater pulse event.
          "U": 15,
          // V=12: vanadium from earlier weathering of montroseite/roscoelite
          // (the primary V minerals; not yet in sim). Sufficient for carnotite
          // + tyuyamunite at supergene T.
          "V": 12,
          // K=20 baseline; gets bumped to dominant during step 100 oscillation.
          "K": 20,
          // Fe=8: trace iron, will rise during roll-front contact event.
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mg": 15,
          "Mn": 2,
          "S": 5,
          "Cl": 8,
          // No primary Cu/Pb/As — the scenario is U-V-K-Ca specifically.
          "Cu": 0,
          "Pb": 0,
          "As": 0,
          "P": 1,    // trace; not enough for autunite/torbernite
          // v62 plumbing: Se for the new selenide engines. Colorado Plateau
          // sandstone-hosted U deposits commonly carry trace Se — the same
          // reducing front that drops uranium also drops Se as native Se +
          // ferroselite + clausthalite (Granger & Warren 1969 USGS Bull
          // 1064 documented Se assemblages at Slick Rock and Uravan).
          // Pb=0 in this broth keeps clausthalite (Pb-Se) inactive until
          // a future Pb pulse delivers Pb≥20.
          "Se": 2,
          // Initial mildly oxidizing — surface groundwater with O2 picked
          // up at the recharge boundary.
          "O2": 1.2,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        // Sandstone-hosted vug — high secondary porosity from intergranular
        // dissolution. n=4 'open' profile.
        "wall": {
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): Colorado Plateau
          // Triassic-Jurassic Morrison Formation roll-front deposits
          // are sandstone-hosted with cavities formed by intergranular
          // dissolution along the redox boundary. The geometry is
          // inherently irregular — pore-throat coalescence, not a
          // smooth pegmatite bubble. 'irregular' archetype encodes the
          // cathedral-scale variance (polar_amp×1.4) appropriate for
          // sandstone-vug profiles. Bubble counts 4/8 left scenario-tuned.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 8,
          "shape_seed": 5
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 20,  "type": "colorado_plateau_groundwater_pulse",  "name": "Groundwater Pulse",      "description": "U+V replenishment from upstream sandstone weathering; Ca dominant → tyuyamunite begins plating" },
        { "step": 60,  "type": "colorado_plateau_roll_front_contact", "name": "Roll-Front Contact",     "description": "Fe rises (organic-iron proxy); T drops; redox front concentrates uranyl-vanadates" },
        { "step": 100, "type": "colorado_plateau_k_pulse",            "name": "K Pulse",                "description": "Evaporite-style K enrichment; K/(K+Ca) crosses 0.5 → carnotite takes the cation pool" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "colorado_plateau_ca_recovery",        "name": "Ca Recovery",            "description": "Carbonate dissolution refreshes Ca; second tyuyamunite phase plates alongside carnotite" },
        { "step": 165, "type": "colorado_plateau_arid_stabilization", "name": "Arid Stabilization",     "description": "System reaches ambient steady state; both species coexist as in real Uravan specimens" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Friedel & Cumenge 1899 — original carnotite description (Roc Creek)",
        "Nenadkevich 1912 — tyuyamunite type description (Tyuya-Muyun)",
        "Hess 1924 — V-U-Ca-K paragenesis review",
        "Stern et al. 1956 — meta-tyuyamunite (American Mineralogist v.41)",
        "research/research-tyuyamunite.md (May 2026) — Colorado Plateau roll-front geology + simulator design"
      ]
    },

    // ============================================================
    // Tutorial scenarios (May 2026)
    // ============================================================
    // Surfaced in the New Game Menu under "Tutorials" — the recommended
    // first stop for new players. Structurally identical to scenarios
    // (scripted broth + scripted events) but scoped/paced for teaching.
    // The callout-overlay UI layer is a follow-up; in this slice they
    // run as plain scenarios you can drive manually in Creative Mode.
    // See proposals/TUTORIAL-SYSTEM-BUILDER-REVIEW.md for design context.
    // ============================================================

    "tutorial_first_crystal": {
      "anchor": "(tutorial scaffold — generic silica-rich broth)",
      "description": "Tutorial 1: First Crystal. Grow a quartz, then watch what happens when conditions drift out of its growth window.",
      "expects_species": ["quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 30,
      "notes": [
        "Tutorial scenario. Designed for the guided first-time-player experience: simple silica-rich broth, quartz nucleates within a few steps at 180°C, then a scripted temperature drop at step 8 pulls T well out of quartz's growth window. The intended player learning is: (1) clicking Advance moves time, (2) crystals need conditions in the right range, (3) when the conditions drift, growth stops.",
        "Surfaced in the New Game Menu under Tutorials. Not anchored to a real locality — it's a teaching scaffold. Sandbox-testable as a normal scenario without the callout overlay UI that ships in a follow-up.",
        "Broth shape mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.silica (the existing 'Silica-rich' starter fluid) so the lesson generalizes to that picker entry."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=180°C: quartz growth window center. Gives σ(Qz) ~1.2-1.5 at
        // start so quartz nucleates within a few steps. Drops to ~100°C
        // after the tutorial event, putting growth firmly outside the
        // comfort window without going so cold the crystal disappears.
        "temperature_C": 180.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.0,
        "fluid": {
          // Silica-rich broth, mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.silica.
          "SiO2": 600,
          "Ca": 150,
          "CO3": 100,
          "Fe": 8,
          "Mn": 3,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Ti": 0.8,
          "Al": 4,
          "F": 10,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 1
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 8, "type": "tutorial_temperature_drop", "name": "Temperature Drops", "description": "Conditions drift out of quartz's growth window — the crystal stops growing" }
      ],
      // Tutorial overlay script consumed by the JS tutorial state machine
      // (window.startTutorial). Each step fires when fortressSim.step
      // reaches its `step` value. Authors should put one callout per
      // sim-step trigger (later steps replace earlier ones immediately).
      "tutorial": {
        "steps": [
          { "step": 0,  "anchor": "#f-advance",       "side": "top",   "text": "Welcome. This is your vug — an empty pocket inside rock, waiting for a crystal to grow. The broth around it is silica-rich and warm enough for quartz. Press 'Advance Step' to move time forward by ~50,000 years." },
          { "step": 4,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Quartz is forming on the wall. Each press of Advance grows it a little more. Notice the temperature sitting around 180°C — that's right in quartz's comfort window." },
          { "step": 9,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "The temperature just dropped sharply. Watch what happens to growth as you keep pressing Advance — the broth got colder, and cold silica wants to stay in solution rather than crystallize out." },
          { "step": 16, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Notice the log: 'no growth this step' is starting to appear. Your crystal is still there, beautiful, but no new layers are forming. The broth doesn't want to give up its silica anymore." },
          { "step": 25, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "That's the lesson: conditions control whether a crystal grows. Same broth, same crystal, different temperature — different outcome. Everything else in the game is just elaborations on this idea. (Press Home when ready, or keep going.)" }
        ]
      },
      "sources": [
        "(tutorial scaffold — no published source)"
      ]
    },

    "tutorial_mn_calcite": {
      "anchor": "(tutorial scaffold — generic carbonate broth)",
      "description": "Tutorial 2: A Mn-Doped Calcite. Grow a calcite, then mix in manganese and watch the next zones glow orange-red under UV. Iron quenches; the boundary records the broth-history.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 30,
      "notes": [
        "Tutorial scenario. Teaches how additives change a growing crystal's properties: Mn²⁺ activates orange fluorescence in calcite (threshold 2 ppm) and Fe²⁺ quenches it. The carbonate broth ships with Fe:10 already at the quencher range and Mn:8 just past the activator threshold — early calcite zones incorporate Mn but stay dim under UV. The Mn pulse at step 8 pushes Mn well past the activator threshold; the Fe drop at step 16 clears the quencher. The boundary between dim early zones and bright late zones records the moment the broth changed.",
        "Surfaced in the New Game Menu under Tutorials. Not anchored to a real locality — it's a teaching scaffold. The Franklin/Sterling Hill (NJ) Mn-activated calcite glow is the real-world reference for the lesson.",
        "Broth shape mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.carbonate so the lesson generalizes to that picker entry."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // T=100°C: comfortable calcite growth window with retrograde
        // solubility helping nucleation. Stays warm enough through the
        // tutorial that calcite keeps growing (the lesson is about
        // properties, not growth interruption like Tutorial 1).
        "temperature_C": 100.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,
        "fluid": {
          // Carbonate broth, mirrors FLUID_PRESETS.carbonate.
          "SiO2": 80,
          "Ca": 300,
          "CO3": 250,
          "Fe": 10,
          "Mn": 8,
          "Mg": 12,
          "Ti": 0.2,
          "Al": 1,
          "F": 5,
          "pH": 7.0,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          "shape_seed": 2
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 8,  "type": "tutorial_mn_pulse", "name": "Manganese Pulse",    "description": "Mn²⁺ injected — next calcite zones incorporate the activator" },
        { "step": 16, "type": "tutorial_fe_drop",  "name": "Iron-Poor Recharge", "description": "Fe²⁺ quencher cleared — Mn-doped zones fluoresce at full brightness" }
      ],
      // Tutorial overlay script — see tutorial_first_crystal for schema notes.
      "tutorial": {
        "steps": [
          { "step": 0,  "anchor": "#f-advance",       "side": "top",   "text": "This vug holds a carbonate broth — calcium and CO₃ ions floating around, waiting to crystallize. Calcite forms here. Press 'Advance Step' to begin." },
          { "step": 4,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Calcite is forming. The broth has a little manganese in it (Mn ≈ 8 ppm) — Mn²⁺ activates orange fluorescence in calcite under longwave UV. But the broth also has iron (Fe ≈ 10 ppm), and iron quenches that glow. So the early zones of your calcite are recording Mn but staying dim." },
          { "step": 9,  "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "A pulse just brought a lot more manganese into the broth. The next zones of calcite will incorporate Mn²⁺ heavily — but iron is still quenching most of the activation. Keep advancing." },
          { "step": 14, "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "The Mn is being recorded into every growth ring from here on. But you wouldn't see it glow yet — Fe is still suppressing the fluorescence. The broth is loaded with the right ingredient and the wrong inhibitor at the same time." },
          { "step": 17, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Iron just crashed out of the broth. The Mn-doped zones that grow next will fluoresce at full brightness. There's a boundary forming inside your crystal: dim early stripes from the iron-quenched phase, bright late stripes from now on." },
          { "step": 25, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "The crystal you grew is now a stratigraphic record of everything you put in the broth. Same crystal, written in fluorescence by every change in chemistry. This is what real Franklin / Sterling Hill calcite specimens look like under UV — bands of glow and quench, recording the deep-time fluid history of the vein." },
          { "step": 30, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "That's the lesson: additives change a growing crystal's properties. The vug remembers what you put into it. Tutorial complete. (Press Home when ready, or keep going.)" }
        ]
      },
      "sources": [
        "(tutorial scaffold — no published source)",
        "Franklin / Sterling Hill (NJ) — type locality for Mn-activated calcite fluorescence"
      ]
    },

    "tutorial_travertine": {
      "anchor": "Mammoth Hot Springs (Yellowstone) — travertine is the canonical CO₂-degas calcite",
      "description": "Tutorial 3: How CO₂ Builds a Calcite Crust. CO₂-rich groundwater rises into a hot-spring pool, loses CO₂ as gas, and pH rises until calcite saturates and starts depositing on every available surface. The same mechanism that grows speleothems in caves and travertine terraces at hot springs.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 60,
      "notes": [
        "Tutorial scenario for PROPOSAL-GEOLOGICAL-ACCURACY Phase 3. Showcases the CO₂-degas → pH rise → calcite supersaturates cascade. Player presses Advance through three degassing pulses (steps 10, 25, 40) and watches calcite go from undersaturated to massive precipitation purely via pH change — no temperature drop, no mineral mixing, no fluid pulse adds Ca.",
        "Initial fluid is high-DIC (CO3 = 500 ppm = ~10 mmol/kg DIC, typical of CO₂-charged hot-spring source water) at moderately acidic pH 6.5 (the pH at which most DIC sits as H₂CO₃* and HCO₃⁻; <0.1% is CO₃²⁻). Despite Ca = 200 ppm being well above seawater levels, calcite stays subsaturated — the carbonate ion isn't there.",
        "Each `co2_degas` event removes 30% of the DIC (CO₂ leaves as gas) and raises pH by 0.5 units. The CO₃²⁻ fraction of DIC grows ~10× per pH unit (Bjerrum partition). After three degassing pulses, pH ~ 8 and calcite is wildly supersaturated; players see calcite nucleate and grow steadily through the back half of the run.",
        "Geological reference: Mammoth Hot Springs (Yellowstone, USA), Pamukkale (Turkey), Pancake Hot Springs (CA). All build travertine via this exact cascade. Cave flowstone uses the same chemistry but with cooler fluid and lower flow."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 70.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          // CO₂-charged hot-spring water — high DIC, moderate pH.
          // Ca = 350 ppm sits in the realistic Mammoth Hot Springs
          // range (200-1000 ppm typical, e.g. Friedman 1970 reports
          // 400-500 ppm at the source). High Ca + initial low pH
          // means the cascade can pass through unsaturated → saturated
          // as Bjerrum CO₃²⁻ amplification (BJERRUM_DAMPING = 0.5)
          // takes over at pH 8.
          "Ca": 350,
          "CO3": 500,
          "Mg": 30,
          "SiO2": 50,
          "Na": 200,
          "Cl": 300,
          "S": 50,
          "Fe": 5,
          "Mn": 2,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 6.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 4
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 10, "type": "co2_degas_with_reheat", "name": "First Pulse", "description": "Fresh hot CO₂-rich fluid arrives — first pulse of CO₂ escapes as it reaches the pool" },
        { "step": 25, "type": "co2_degas_with_reheat", "name": "Second Pulse", "description": "Continued CO₂ outgassing — pH continues to rise, CO₃²⁻ fraction grows" },
        { "step": 40, "type": "co2_degas_with_reheat", "name": "Third Pulse", "description": "Final pulse — pH near 8, calcite massively supersaturated" }
      ],
      "tutorial": {
        "steps": [
          { "step": 0,  "anchor": "#f-advance",       "side": "top",   "text": "This vug holds high-DIC hot-spring water — lots of dissolved CO₂, calcium, and bicarbonate. The pH is 6.5, which sounds neutral, but at that pH almost none of the carbonate is in the CO₃²⁻ form needed for calcite. Press Advance to start." },
          { "step": 4,  "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Notice: calcite isn't growing yet. The Ca is there (200 ppm), the DIC is there (500 ppm), but pH 6.5 means CO₃²⁻ is essentially zero. The Bjerrum partition keeps almost all carbonate as H₂CO₃* and HCO₃⁻. Calcite needs the ionic form." },
          { "step": 11, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "First CO₂ degas event just fired. Read the log — 30% of the DIC just left as gas, and pH jumped from 6.5 to 7.0. The next steps will start to nucleate calcite as the CO₃²⁻ fraction climbs." },
          { "step": 20, "anchor": "#fortress-status", "side": "right", "text": "Calcite is starting to grow. The same Ca²⁺ that's been sitting in solution the whole time is now precipitating because the carbonate ion finally exists in meaningful amounts. The fluid composition barely changed — only the pH did." },
          { "step": 26, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Second degas pulse. pH rises again. Watch calcite growth accelerate." },
          { "step": 41, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Third degas. pH near 8 now. Calcite is wildly supersaturated; every nucleation site available is depositing crystal." },
          { "step": 55, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "That's how travertine builds at Mammoth Hot Springs. Hot CO₂-charged water reaches the surface, CO₂ escapes as bubbles, pH rises, and calcite plates everything in white. The same fluid that ARRIVES too acidic to grow calcite ENDS UP loaded with it — only the dissolved gas changed." },
          { "step": 60, "anchor": "#fortress-log",    "side": "left",  "text": "Tutorial complete. The lesson: pH controls carbonate-system chemistry as fundamentally as temperature. Cave flowstone, hot-spring travertine, ocean carbonate sediments — they all run on this same Bjerrum cascade. (Press Home when ready, or keep going.)" }
        ]
      },
      "sources": [
        "Mammoth Hot Springs, Yellowstone NP — type locality for actively-forming travertine",
        "Pentecost A. (2005), Travertine — comprehensive review of CO₂-degas calcite",
        "Stumm & Morgan, Aquatic Chemistry (3rd ed.), Bjerrum partition + Henry's-Law CO₂"
      ]
    },

    "epithermal_telluride": {
      "anchor": "Cripple Creek mining district, Teller County, Colorado — alkalic-volcanic-hosted low-sulfidation epithermal Au-Te. Cresson Mine pocket, Carlton tunnel level. Type district for the world's gold-telluride mineralogy (calaverite, sylvanite, krennerite, hessite, petzite, native tellurium).",
      "description": "Low-sulfidation alkalic-volcanic epithermal vein at the gold-telluride sweet spot. Late-stage K-alkaline fluid carries Au + Ag + Te through fractured phonolite and crystallizes the calaverite + sylvanite + hessite trio along quartz + fluorite + adularia gangue. Cooling from 280°C through the 150-200°C epithermal window over geologic time — the temperature trajectory crosses both the cubic↔monoclinic hessite transition (155°C) and the calaverite-sylvanite Au:Ag fork.",
      "expects_species": ["calaverite", "sylvanite", "hessite", "native_gold", "native_tellurium", "fluorite", "quartz"],
      "duration_steps": 180,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Cripple Creek mining district — alkalic-igneous diatreme, late-Oligocene (~32-28 Ma), produces high-grade Au-Te ore from low-sulfidation epithermal veins through phonolite + lamprophyre dikes. The world's premier gold-telluride locality and the type area for calaverite (1861, type specimen from Calaveras County CA but the species grows everywhere here), sylvanite, krennerite, petzite, and nagyágite.",
        "Mechanic: gold telluride paragenesis cascades on temperature + Au:Ag ratio. At T > 250°C calaverite (Au-rich end-member) wins; as Ag rises and T drops into 150-250°C, sylvanite (1:1 Au:Ag) takes over; below 150°C hessite (pure Ag) crystallizes from residual fluid. Native gold liberates wherever local Te is depleted by earlier telluride growth. Fluorite + quartz + adularia gangue fills the spaces between.",
        "Why Au=0.4 and Te=3 here: Cripple Creek fluid inclusion data (Saunders et al. 2008) reports Au 1-10 ppm and Te 1-30 ppm in inclusions across the deposit, with peak Au-Te enrichment in the Cresson Vug bonanza (Au tens of ppm). Sim-scale 0.4 ppm Au keeps the broth above all telluride thresholds while staying below native_gold's 0.5 ppm gate at the start (native_gold fires later as Te depletes and Au accumulates locally). Ag=15 puts sylvanite in the cation-fork window (Ag/Au ~37 — sylvanite-favored).",
        "v184 T-rollout verdict: ambient thermal pulses KEPT, deliberately — they are LOAD-BEARING AND NATIVE here (do not re-litigate without new geology; measured in tools/t-story-observe.mjs, 3 seeds). Native: fault-valve boiling pulses (Sibson) ARE the low-sulfidation epithermal heat supply — Cripple Creek's system pulsed for ~My, and T excursions back and forth across the 155°C hessite transition are real epithermal behavior. Load-bearing: with pulses off the system crashes from the 150-250°C window to the 25°C floor by mid-run (meanT 226→121, fill 0.01→0.00) — the pulses hold this scenario inside the epithermal window its whole design lives in. Pre-existing aspirational misses logged while measuring: native_gold + fluorite absent at observed BASE seeds (expects-tune arc, separate)."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 280.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 600,
          "Ca": 80,
          "CO3": 30,
          "Fe": 12,
          "Mn": 3,
          "Mg": 5,
          "Al": 8,
          // Au=0.4: Cripple Creek fluid inclusion average (Saunders 2008).
          // Above all telluride thresholds (calaverite Au≥0.1, sylvanite Au≥0.1).
          // Just below native_gold's Au≥0.5 gate so native_gold needs locally
          // depleted Te before it can nucleate.
          "Au": 0.4,
          // Ag=15: sylvanite / hessite-favoring Ag dominance. Acanthite gates
          // on Ag≥0.5 + S≥5 — the low-S epithermal broth here (S=8) keeps
          // acanthite at low σ until cooling concentrates the brine.
          "Ag": 15,
          // Te=3: epithermal sweet spot. Above all telluride thresholds and
          // above native_tellurium's Te≥0.5 + Au≤1 + Ag≤5 gate. With Au=0.4
          // and Ag=15, the Au+Ag composite blocks native_tellurium until Ag
          // drops via hessite consumption.
          "Te": 3,
          // S=8: low-sulfidation epithermal — sulfides stay subordinate to
          // tellurides and native phases. Saunders 2008 fluid inclusion S
          // is 5-25 ppm in Cripple Creek bonanzas vs. 100-1000 ppm in
          // typical porphyry brines.
          "S": 8,
          // F=20: fluorite is the diagnostic gangue at Cripple Creek + most
          // Te-rich epithermal districts. Above fluorite's F≥10 threshold.
          "F": 20,
          // K=200: K-alkaline alteration is the diagnostic wallrock fingerprint
          // of alkalic-volcanic-hosted epithermal — adularia + sericite halo
          // around Au-Te veins.
          "K": 200,
          "Na": 60,
          "Cl": 300,
          "Pb": 5,
          "Cu": 4,
          // O2=0.05: reducing — required for telluride growth (Te²⁻ stable).
          "O2": 0.05,
          "pH": 6.5,
          "salinity": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Cripple Creek vugs are fracture-controlled in phonolite — narrow
          // slot-like cavities along fault planes. Tabular architecture.
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "composition": "phonolite",
          "thickness_mm": 200.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 35.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 4000.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 32,
          // Tier 1 C (post-v69): fracture-controlled phonolite vein
          // cavities preserve sharp dihedral creases. The host is
          // brittle alkaline volcanic glass + microlite phenocrysts,
          // unweathered at depth — the original fracture-and-vug
          // geometry survives without subsequent rounding. 'sharp'
          // surfaces the sphere-union creases on the cavity mesh.
          "cavity_render": "sharp"
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 30,  "type": "fluid_pulse",   "name": "Telluride Recharge",  "description": "Late-magmatic K-alkaline fluid pulse — Au + Ag + Te replenish; SiO2 surges for quartz gangue" },
        { "step": 70,  "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "First Cooling",       "description": "Meteoric mixing drops T into the calaverite-sylvanite transition window" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "fluid_pulse",   "name": "Second Pulse",        "description": "Renewed magmatic input refreshes the brine; Ag rises faster than Au, biasing toward sylvanite + hessite" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "cooling_pulse", "name": "Final Cooling",       "description": "T drops below 200°C — hessite phase transition and late acanthite become possible" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Saunders 1991, 2008 — Cripple Creek alkalic-igneous Au-Te paragenesis + fluid inclusion data",
        "Kelley & Spry 2016 — alkalic gold-telluride deposits review (Econ. Geol.)",
        "Pinch & Wilson 1977 — Cripple Creek + Sacarîmb (Romania) telluride mineralogy",
        "Goldschmidt 1922 — calaverite morphology (92 forms catalogued; the 'incommensurate modulation' problem)"
      ]
    },

    "ultramafic_supergene": {
      "anchor": "Marlborough chrysoprase deposits, Queensland, Australia — Ni-laterite weathering of Late-Devonian Marlborough Block ophiolitic peridotite. Type aesthetic: apple-green chrysoprase nodules + magnesite veinlets in saprolite over serpentinized harzburgite.",
      "description": "Tropical-to-temperate Ni-laterite weathering of ultramafic protolith. Olivine + pyroxene break down to serpentine, releasing Ni + Mg + SiO2 to slow alkaline groundwater that percolates through fractures and crystallizes chrysoprase (Ni-bearing chalcedony) as fracture-fill, with magnesite + calcite + chalcedony as the cogenetic gangue suite. The signature green color comes from nano-inclusions of Ni-phyllosilicate (pimelite/willemseite/kerolite) trapped within the chalcedony fabric — a composite color, not a lattice color.",
      "expects_species": ["chrysoprase", "quartz", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Marlborough chrysoprase deposits (Queensland) — modern world reference for gem-grade chrysoprase. Late Devonian (380-360 Ma) Marlborough Block serpentinite + dunite is the protolith; Cenozoic weathering produced the saprolite + Ni-laterite + chrysoprase chemistry (Sachanbiński et al. 2001 documents the nano-inclusion structure).",
        "Mechanic: olivine weathering releases Ni²⁺ + Mg²⁺ + Si(OH)₄ to seasonal groundwater. As the wet season ends, evaporation concentrates the brine and silica deposits as fibrous chalcedony in fractures, with Ni nano-inclusions trapped during deposition. The classic Marlborough green chrysoprase hosts ~0.4-4 wt% NiO bulk; the actual Ni is in pimelite/willemseite/kerolite nano-clay particles inside the SiO2 fabric.",
        "Why Ni=200, Mg=300: ultramafic regolith ground waters carry tens to hundreds of ppm Ni and hundreds of ppm Mg in active weathering profiles (Garnier et al. 2008 Goro Ni-laterite hydrology; Cluzel & Vigier 2008 New Caledonia). 200 / 300 sim-ppm puts both well above chrysoprase's Ni≥50 + Mg≥50 thresholds while staying realistic. SiO2=200 keeps it above chrysoprase's SiO2≥100 gate without forcing macroscopic quartz nucleation."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 30.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          // SiO2 200 → 300 (stale-mineral retune 2026-05): with SiO2=200,
          // chrysoprase σ peaks at 1.05 (just above the engine's 1.0
          // threshold) for only 2 / 600 (seed × step) pairs — borderline
          // reliable firing under the 12% rng gate. Active Ni-laterite
          // groundwaters carry SiO2 100-400 ppm during dry-season
          // concentration (Garnier et al. 2008 Goro hydrology;
          // Sachanbiński et al. 2001 Marlborough) so 300 is well within
          // the geological window. Quartz already fires in this scenario
          // (expects_species lists it); bump is small enough not to
          // shift quartz behavior meaningfully.
          "SiO2": 300,
          "Ca": 30,
          "CO3": 80,
          "Fe": 15,
          "Mn": 4,
          // Mg=300: serpentinite weathering brine — ultramafic protolith
          // releases Mg readily as olivine and pyroxene break down. Garnier
          // 2008 reports Mg 50-300 ppm in active Ni-laterite groundwaters.
          // Above chrysoprase's Mg≥50 threshold; also feeds magnesite when
          // CO3 rises.
          "Mg": 300,
          // Ni=200: the diagnostic enrichment of ultramafic supergene fluid.
          // Olivine + pyroxene release Ni²⁺ during serpentinization +
          // weathering; alkaline groundwater carries it laterally until
          // silica precipitation traps it as nano-inclusion. 200 sim-ppm
          // is mid-range for active Ni-laterite weathering profiles.
          "Ni": 200,
          // Cr=10: minor Cr release from chromite + Cr-rich pyroxene in the
          // host harzburgite. Below chrysoprase's mtorolite-fork Cr≥30
          // threshold so the chalcedony stays Ni-green (not Cr-green).
          "Cr": 10,
          // Na, K modest — meteoric groundwater chemistry, not evaporite.
          "Na": 30,
          "K": 8,
          "Cl": 40,
          "S": 5,
          "Al": 4,
          // Cu = trace from rare Cu-bearing serpentinite zones (the boss's
          // "garnierite + chrysocolla" companion at some Ni-laterite sites
          // can co-occur).
          "Cu": 2,
          "P": 0.5,
          // Strongly alkaline — serpentinite groundwater pH 8.5-10 is typical
          // (the active mineralogy makes Mg-OH systems naturally basic).
          // Above chrysoprase's pH≥7.5 + below ≤9.5 window.
          "pH": 8.5,
          "O2": 1.5,
          "salinity": 1.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Saprolite + serpentinite host — fractured, irregular cavity
          // network rather than a single bubble. Irregular architecture +
          // mafic composition (ultramafic chemistry; basalt is the closest
          // existing wall composition).
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "composition": "basalt",
          "thickness_mm": 300.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 6000.0,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 200.0,
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 47
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step": 40,  "type": "aquifer_recharge_floods", "name": "Wet Season",     "description": "Seasonal recharge floods the cavity; fresh meteoric water dilutes Ni + Mg but delivers silica" },
        { "step": 80,  "type": "fluid_pulse",            "name": "Ni Pulse",        "description": "Late-stage olivine + pyroxene weathering release — Ni + Mg spike, silica climbs" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "tectonic_uplift_drains", "name": "Dry Season",      "description": "Fluid level drops; remaining brine evaporates and concentrates — chrysoprase nucleation window" },
        { "step": 175, "type": "alkalinize",             "name": "Alkaline Cap",    "description": "Late carbonate-rich pulse — magnesite + calcite finish the assemblage" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Sachanbiński et al. 2001 — chrysoprase nano-inclusion structure (Ni-clay in chalcedony)",
        "Witkowski 2007 — chrysoprase color-cause confirmation",
        "Garnier et al. 2008 — Goro Ni-laterite hydrology + supergene Ni mobility",
        "Cluzel & Vigier 2008 — New Caledonia ultramafic weathering geochemistry",
        "Marlborough Mine Queensland production records — modern Ni-rich chrysoprase reference"
      ]
    },

    "stalactite_demo": {
      "anchor": "Generic limestone-cave dripstone — Carlsbad Caverns / Lechuguilla / Mammoth Cave family. Cave-air-filled cavity (vadose throughout), calcite precipitating from CO₂-degassed drip water on ceiling, floor, and walls in three different morphologies.",
      "description": "PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 5 — proof-by-screenshot that the gravity-aware c-axis works. Cave-style cavity: every crystal nucleates in air-mode (wall.air_mode_default), so ceiling calcite renders as stalactite (c-axis world-down) and floor calcite as stalagmite (c-axis world-up). Multiple speleothems grow concurrently (cave-mode nucleation probability fires every step σ > threshold). Per-vertex sampling + zone chemistry route each nucleation to the calcite-favoring floor/ceiling cells.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 100,
      "notes": [
        "Habit-bias proof scenario. The whole point: walk into the cave, look up at the ceiling, see crystals HANGING (stalactites); look down at the floor, see crystals STANDING (stalagmites). All are the same calcite mineral and the same precipitation chemistry — only the ANCHOR ORIENTATION differs, and that drives the rendered c-axis via PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 1.",
        "Chemistry is generic dripstone: Ca²⁺ + HCO₃⁻ from limestone dissolution upstream, CO₂ degasses in the cave air, pH rises, CO₃²⁻ fraction climbs, calcite saturates and precipitates. The simulator's calcite engine handles this cascade.",
        "Zone chemistry (PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Phase 3): ceiling + floor are Ca-rich (drip-source ceiling, drop-collector floor), wall is calcite-cuspy. With inter_ring_diffusion_rate=0 the gradient persists across the 100-step run; without that, Laplacian diffusion would average the zones over ~20 steps and the differentiation would wash out.",
        "Per-vertex nucleation (PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Tranche 6, 2026-05): the calcite engine still gates on the equator's σ, but cell assignment uses the joint σ-weighted sample so each calcite anchors at a cell where its local σ is highest. With the sharp wall-cuspy zoning, this routes every nucleation to the floor or ceiling — no wall calcite. Without this flag, area-weighted random placement would put most calcites on wall cells (wall has ~2× more cells than floor or ceiling combined) and the speleothem morphologies would be invisible.",
        "Air-mode nucleation probability (2026-05): cave-mode scenarios use a Bernoulli per-step roll (_AIR_MODE_NUCLEATION_PROB = 0.06) instead of the strict serial !existing_calcite gate. Real caves grow multiple stalactites + stalagmites concurrently; the serial gate produced exactly 1 calcite per run and was the reason this scenario shipped with only 1 visible speleothem at v69. Calibrated to give ~4-7 nucleations over 100 steps, bounded by max_nucleation_count.",
        "Temperature: 15°C — generic cave. Pressure: 0.01 kbar (atmospheric — cave air above the water table). Wall: pocket archetype at 60 mm diameter."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Cave temperature — generic mid-latitude limestone karst.
        // Carlsbad averages 13°C, Mammoth Cave 12°C, tropical caves
        // 20-25°C. 15°C is the broad middle.
        "temperature_C": 15.0,
        // Near-atmospheric pressure — cave air, not deep burial.
        "pressure_kbar": 0.01,
        "fluid": {
          // High DIC + alkaline pH — calcite well-saturated through
          // the run. Initial Ca + CO3 sized so 10 calcite nucleations
          // (the per-species cap) can each grow to multi-mm dripstone
          // length without depleting the broth below threshold. The
          // pH wells past the Bjerrum CO3²⁻ inflection at 8.3 so the
          // ionic carbonate pool is steadily available.
          "Ca": 2500,
          "CO3": 2500,
          "pH": 8.3,
          // Cave drip water has dissolved limestone (Ca + HCO3) and
          // not much else. Trace levels of typical groundwater ions.
          "Mg": 20,
          "Na": 15,
          "Cl": 10,
          "SO4": 5,
          "Fe": 1,
          "Mn": 0.5,
          "SiO2": 8,
          "salinity": 0.5,
          // O2 high — cave air directly above the water table.
          "O2": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          // 60 mm cavity — large enough that individual crystals read
          // at viewer scale.
          "vug_diameter_mm": 60.0,
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): a "stalactite-bearing
          // cavity" anchored to Carlsbad / Lechuguilla / Mammoth Cave
          // is a karst dissolution chamber, not a smooth pegmatite
          // pocket. 'irregular' archetype encodes that: more bubbles
          // (cathedral profile) + bigger polar amplitude (the cavity
          // has real vertical complexity). Existing primary/secondary
          // bubble overrides preserved — scenario tuned them for the
          // dripstone-demo specifically; archetype defaults would
          // over-amplify the bubble count for this 60mm demo.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 42,
          // PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 2 — every crystal nucleates in
          // air-mode regardless of water state. The cave is air-filled
          // from step 0 (no faked drainage event needed).
          //
          // Air-mode also activates the relaxed nucleation gate in
          // _nuc_calcite (post-Tranche-6 / 2026-05): instead of
          // the serial "no active calcite exists" gate, every step
          // rolls a 6% probability while σ > 1.3 and the per-mineral
          // cap (10) isn't hit. Multiple speleothems grow concurrently.
          "air_mode_default": true,
          // PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Tranche 6 (post-v69): per-vertex
          // nucleation. Combined with the sharp zone_chemistry below,
          // every nucleation lands at a high-σ cell on the floor or
          // ceiling — no calcite-on-wall. The c-axis world-down/up
          // gravity bias from PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 1 then sells
          // the stalactite vs stalagmite morphology distinction.
          "per_vertex_nucleation": true,
          // PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Phase 3 zone chemistry: floor + ceiling
          // are calcite-favoring (Ca = 4000, CO3 = 4000 — well above
          // threshold). Wall is calcite-cuspy (Ca = 600, CO3 = 600 — σ
          // still above 1.3 but per-vertex weight ((σ-1)²) much lower
          // than floor/ceiling cells, so the joint sampler routes
          // every nucleation to floor or ceiling. This is what makes
          // the scenario VISUALLY a speleothem cave instead of a
          // limestone bubble with random calcite crystals.
          "zone_chemistry": {
            "ceiling": { "Ca": 4000, "CO3": 4000 },
            "floor":   { "Ca": 4000, "CO3": 4000 },
            "wall":    { "Ca":  600, "CO3":  600 }
          },
          // Pin the gradient: 0 = no inter-ring Laplacian diffusion.
          // The floor/ceiling/wall σ contrast persists across the
          // 100-step run instead of homogenizing within ~20 steps.
          "inter_ring_diffusion_rate": 0
        }
      },
      "events": [],
      "sources": [
        "Pentecost A. (2005), Travertine — comprehensive review of CO₂-degas calcite (cave + spring)",
        "Hill & Forti (1997), Cave Minerals of the World, 2nd ed. — speleothem morphology reference",
        "Ford & Williams (2007), Karst Hydrogeology and Geomorphology — cave drip-water chemistry"
      ]
    },

    "zoned_dripstone_cave": {
      "anchor": "Mg/Ca-zoned dripstone cave — composite of Frasassi (Italy, Mg-rich ceiling aragonite), Carlsbad Caverns (NM, calcite floor), and Reed Flute Cave (Guilin, twin morphologies). The geochemistry of cave dripstone where the drip-water Mg/Ca ratio differs between ceiling-percolation pathways and floor-puddle re-precipitation, producing aragonite stalactites + calcite stalagmites in the same cavity.",
      "description": "Tranche 6 of PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH §14 demo scenario. Demonstrates per-vertex nucleation: with wall.per_vertex_nucleation=true, calcite and aragonite engines both fire from the global broth, but each crystal's anchor cell is chosen by the per-cell σ for THAT mineral. Result: calcite nucleates at high-Ca floor cells (Mg/Ca << 1.5 keeps calcite σ high, aragonite σ near zero); aragonite nucleates at high-Mg ceiling cells (Mg/Ca > 4 stunts calcite via the Mg poisoning sigmoid and peaks the aragonite Mg/Ca favorability factor). Same chemistry, same engines — only spatial sampling differs.",
      "expects_species": ["calcite", "aragonite"],
      "duration_steps": 150,
      "notes": [
        "Real-world precedent: Frasassi Cave's Sala 200 carries ceiling aragonite frostwork over floor calcite popcorn; Reed Flute Cave (Guilin) shows the same vertical sort. The driver is dripwater Mg/Ca, which on ceiling-percolation pathways gets concentrated by prior dolomite dissolution and selective calcite preprecipitation upstream, while floor-puddle re-precipitation drops Mg as Mg-Mg carbonates / clay along the way and arrives Ca-rich. Frisia et al. 2002 Lithos paper is the canonical Italian cave-aragonite geochem reference; Sherwin & Baldini 2011 reviewed the global pattern.",
        "Scenario chemistry — global broth (= equator, what the engines see for their gate decisions): Ca=2000, Mg=1500, CO3=2200, pH=8.4. Mg/Ca = 0.75 puts both engines above their nucleation σ thresholds (calcite >1.3, aragonite >1.0) but neither is saturated past its kinetic preferred window. Zone overrides then split the cavity:",
        "  Floor: Ca=3500, Mg=30. Mg/Ca = 0.009 — calcite σ unstunted (Mg-poisoning sigmoid centered at Mg/Ca=2 gives ~0% inhibition here), aragonite σ ≈ 0 (Mg/Ca << 1.5, aragonite favorability factor near 0). Result: calcite-only cells.",
        "  Ceiling: Ca=800, Mg=3500. Mg/Ca = 4.4 — calcite σ drops by ~70% (Mg-poisoning sigmoid at high-saturation tail), aragonite σ peaks (favorability factor near 1, plus the Sr/Ba trace boost from the ceiling-percolation history). Result: aragonite-only cells.",
        "  Wall: stays at the global broth. Calcite σ slightly preferred at the boundary.",
        "Per-vertex nucleation closes the loop: without this flag, nucleation engines read only the equator chemistry, the gate fires on the global broth, and the crystal lands at a random area-weighted cell — which means a calcite stalagmite might end up where the aragonite-favoring chemistry is, and vice versa. With wall.per_vertex_nucleation=true, each nucleation picks the cell whose local σ for THAT mineral is highest. The spatial result tracks the chemistry.",
        "inter_ring_diffusion_rate=0 pins the zones across the 150-step run; with the default 0.05 the Laplacian would homogenize the Mg/Ca gradient over ~20 steps and the differentiation would wash out before either engine fires twice.",
        "air_mode_default=true so PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 1 kicks in: ceiling aragonite crystals point downward (stalactite c-axis world-down), floor calcite crystals point upward (stalagmite c-axis world-up). The combination of per-vertex placement + air-mode habit gives the full Frasassi-style spatial sort visually.",
        "Sources cited are the genuine references for Italian cave aragonite-on-calcite paragenesis; this scenario is the simulator's first that puts Mg/Ca zoning and habit-bias together in one cavity."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 18.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.01,
        "fluid": {
          "Ca": 2000,
          "Mg": 1500,
          "CO3": 2200,
          "pH": 8.4,
          "Na": 12,
          "Cl": 10,
          "SO4": 5,
          "Fe": 1,
          "Mn": 0.3,
          "SiO2": 6,
          // Trace Sr + Ba — aragonite favorability factor pulls a +30%
          // boost from the trace_ratio sigmoid in supersaturation_aragonite
          // when trace_sum / Ca > 0.01. At Ca=2000 this means Sr+Pb+Ba ≥ 20
          // saturates the boost. Real cave aragonite specimens carry Sr at
          // 1000-7000 ppm from the calcite-rejected fraction (Frisia 2002).
          "Sr": 25,
          "Ba": 3,
          "Pb": 0,
          "salinity": 0.5,
          "O2": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "limestone",
          // Slightly larger than stalactite_demo so each crystal hits
          // its size cap sooner (more nucleations within the 150 steps
          // → more spatial data points → cleaner demo).
          "vug_diameter_mm": 80.0,
          // Architecture audit (2026-05-18): zoned dripstone caves are
          // karst dissolution chambers (Frasassi/Carlsbad/Reed Flute —
          // cathedral-scale rooms with vertical complexity). 'irregular'
          // not 'pocket'. Bubble counts left as scenario-tuned for the
          // composite demo.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 24,
          // PROPOSAL-HABIT-BIAS Slice 2 — every crystal nucleates in
          // air-mode so ceiling aragonite gets the stalactite c-axis
          // and floor calcite gets the stalagmite c-axis.
          "air_mode_default": true,
          // PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Tranche 6 — opt into per-vertex
          // nucleation cell assignment. Without this flag, calcite and
          // aragonite would land at random area-weighted positions and
          // the spatial-chemistry coupling would be invisible.
          "per_vertex_nucleation": true,
          // PROPOSAL-CAVITY-MESH Tranche 3 zone chemistry: floor + ceiling
          // overrides on top of the global broth. The wall zone is
          // intentionally NOT overridden so it stays at the equator
          // chemistry. Field-by-field overrides (any field not listed
          // falls through to the scenario's initial.fluid).
          "zone_chemistry": {
            "floor": {
              "Ca": 3500,
              "Mg": 30,
              "Sr": 2,
              "Ba": 0.5
            },
            "ceiling": {
              "Ca": 800,
              "Mg": 3500,
              "Sr": 60,
              "Ba": 8
            }
          },
          // Pin the gradient: 0 = no inter-ring Laplacian diffusion. The
          // floor/ceiling Mg/Ca contrast persists across the 150-step
          // run instead of homogenizing within ~20 steps.
          "inter_ring_diffusion_rate": 0
        }
      },
      "events": [],
      "sources": [
        "Frisia S., Borsato A., Fairchild I.J., et al. (2002) — Aragonite-calcite relationships in speleothems (Grotte de Clamouse, France, and Italian cave systems). Lithos 65 (1-2): 119-133.",
        "Sherwin C.M., Baldini J.U.L. (2011) — Cave air and hydrological controls on prior calcite precipitation and stalagmite growth rates. Chem. Geol. 290: 79-87.",
        "Railsback L.B., Brook G.A., Liang F. et al. (1994) — Speleothem fabric record of aragonite-calcite transitions. Carbonates and Evaporites 9: 217-230.",
        "Spötl C., Mangini A. (2007) — Speleothems and paleoclimates: aragonite vs calcite as climate archives. Quaternary Science Reviews 26: 1488-1499."
      ]
    },

    "sulphur_bank": {
      "anchor": "Sulphur Bank Mine, south shore of Clear Lake, Lake County, California — Pleistocene hot-spring mercury-sulfur deposit. Active hot-spring system since ~150,000 years ago; mined for mercury 1865-1957 (one of California's largest Hg producers). Now EPA Superfund site CAD980893275. The textbook hot-spring quicksilver-sulfur deposit per White & Roberson 1962 (USGS PP 432-A).",
      "description": "Hot-spring mercury-sulfur deposit at the surface mixing zone where rising H₂S-rich fluid meets atmospheric O₂. Headline minerals: native sulfur (from synproportionation 2 H₂S + O₂ → 2 S° + 2 H₂O) and cinnabar (HgS, the deposit's mining commodity — Sulphur Bank yielded ~450 tons of mercury 1865-1957). The H₂SO₄ byproduct keeps fluid pH at 2-4. Accessory As-sulfides realgar (orange-red AsS) and orpiment (golden-yellow As₂S₃) deposit alongside in the same H₂S + O₂ mixing zone — the documented Sulphur Bank arsenic minerals (White & Roberson 1962). Native sulfur grows in α-bipyramidal habit; cinnabar in deep cochineal-red rhombohedra; realgar in orange-red prisms; orpiment in foliated golden plates. Supporting cast: pyrite + marcasite from the Fe trace, arsenopyrite from trace As, quartz from silica-rich hot water.",
      "expects_species": ["native_sulfur", "cinnabar", "realgar", "orpiment", "pararealgar", "pyrite", "marcasite", "arsenopyrite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Sulphur Bank Mine, the canonical hot-spring native-sulfur deposit. White & Roberson 1962 (USGS PP 432-A) is the foundational monograph; White 1981 placed it in the broader active-geothermal-ore-deposit framework. The deposit was the type case for the 'hot-spring mercury-sulfur' class. Active hot springs still vent today (60-90°C; the EPA Superfund record documents continuous monitoring 1990s-present).",
        "Engine fit (native_sulfur in js/36-supersat-native.ts): the supersaturation gates are S ≥ 100 ppm, O₂ ∈ [0.1, 0.7] (the synproportionation window), pH ≤ 5, metal_sum (Fe+Cu+Pb+Zn) ≤ 100, T 20-95°C optimal. Sulphur Bank fluid sits dead-center in all five gates. This is the simpler of the two native_sulfur deposit types — the acid-sulfate hot-spring mode the existing engine was implicitly designed for. The Sicily-style sedimentary BSR mode (pH 7-8, calcite-buffered) is a future scenario after engine broadening.",
        "Habit dispatcher: the engine's three habits are sublimation_crust (T > 60 + excess > 1.5; fumarole vent zone), prismatic_beta (T ≥ 95; rare high-T monoclinic), and bipyramidal_alpha (the iconic Sicilian {111} dipyramid habit, < 60°C). The scenario starts at 75°C — sublimation_crust at high σ, bipyramidal_alpha after cooling pulses. Both habits real for Sulphur Bank.",
        "Mercury: the namesake commodity (cinnabar, HgS) isn't in MINERAL_SPEC yet — a follow-up commit can add it for the full Sulphur Bank assemblage. For now the scenario carries trace Fe + As to fire pyrite + marcasite + arsenopyrite alongside the headline native_sulfur."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 75.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.05,
        "fluid": {
          // Hot-spring waters per White & Roberson 1962 fluid-inclusion
          // + active-spring sampling. Acid-sulfate facies; H₂S-rich;
          // low metal load (Hg arrives as gaseous Hg⁰ vapor, not as
          // a bisulfide complex carrying base metals — that's WHY
          // mercury hot springs have famously LOW Fe/Cu/Pb/Zn).
          "SiO2": 200,    // hot-spring SiO₂ is high; opal/chalcedony deposits form
          "Ca": 80,       // low — acid fluid, no carbonate buffering
          "CO3": 5,
          "Fe": 25,       // modest — supports pyrite/marcasite
          "Mn": 1,
          "Mg": 30,
          "Na": 200,
          "K": 25,
          // Sulfur: the headline. 400 ppm sits at the upper edge of
          // the published White & Roberson 1962 measured range for
          // active Sulphur Bank vent fluid (total H₂S + HS⁻ + SO₄ =
          // 100-400 mg/L documented at the venting fissures). Above
          // the engine's 100 ppm threshold; the s_f factor (S/200,
          // capped at 4.0) hits 2.0, giving headroom above 1.0 after
          // activity-correction (~0.8x) and the pH recovery that
          // drifts ph_f down over the run.
          //
          // v82 was 500 ppm (slightly above measured range); v83
          // tuned to 400 to follow the published upper bound exactly.
          "S": 400,
          "Cl": 80,       // low-moderate salinity for hot spring
          // Trace metals — low. metal_sum = Fe(25)+Cu(3)+Pb(2)+Zn(5)
          // = 35 < 100 (the engine cap; mercury hot springs are
          // famously LOW in base metals because Hg arrives as
          // vapor, not as a sulfide-complex carrier).
          "Cu": 3,
          "Pb": 2,
          "Zn": 5,
          // Trace As — supports arsenopyrite + realgar + orpiment.
          // Sulphur Bank historical reports document minor realgar
          // + orpiment crystals in the vent zone (White & Roberson
          // 1962 lists both as accessory species).
          //
          // 10 ppm sits at the upper end of the published measured
          // range for dissolved As in Sulphur Bank vent fluid (White
          // & Roberson 1962 + EPA Superfund site CAD980893275
          // monitoring: typically 0.5-10 mg/L). Localized enrichment
          // in the H₂S + O₂ mixing zone where realgar + orpiment
          // actually precipitate can transiently exceed bulk values
          // (the same boundary-layer micro-environment the per-cell
          // local-fill scaffolding in Proposal E was built for). The
          // sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge events add +2 As each, so the
          // run-trajectory rises from 10 to ~22 ppm by step 200 —
          // covering the localized-enrichment regime within
          // simulator-truth bounds.
          //
          // v82 was 30 ppm (above the published 0.5-10 ppm measured
          // range — author shortcut to clear the engine gates without
          // ground-truthing first). v83 corrected to 10 ppm following
          // White & Roberson's measured-vent values. Engines still
          // fire reliably: realgar's σ peak drops 9.0 → ~3 across the
          // run; orpiment's drops 6.8 → ~2; both well above the 1.0
          // nucleation threshold.
          "As": 10,
          // Mercury: the deposit's namesake commodity. The Sulphur
          // Bank Mine produced ~13,000 flasks of Hg (~450 tons)
          // before closure in 1957. Hg arrives in the hot-spring
          // fluid as a mix of HgCl₂ complexes and gaseous Hg⁰
          // (White & Roberson 1962). 15 ppm is in the published
          // measured-vent range (0.5-50 ppm); enough for the
          // cinnabar engine's Hg ≥ 1 gate with headroom for the
          // hg_f factor (Hg/5, capped at 4.0) to hit 3.0.
          "Hg": 15,
          // pH: acid from H₂S + ½O₂ → S° + H₂SO₄ at the vents.
          // White & Roberson 1962 measured pH 1.8-4.0 at active
          // vents (some assays reaching 1.5 in the most active
          // mixing zones). 1.8 is in the low end of that range —
          // the engine's ph_f factor (= 1.0 - 0.15×pH) hits 0.73.
          // Necessary because ambient_cooling's pH-recovery clause
          // pushes pH up at +0.12/step when flow_rate > 0; starting
          // low gives us a working window before the recovery
          // overruns the engine's pH ≤ 5 gate (~25 steps at the
          // event-tuned flow_rate of 0.4-1.2).
          "pH": 1.8,
          // O₂: the synproportionation window peak. 0.40 is dead-
          // center on the engine's nativeRedoxTent(peakO2=0.4) so
          // eh_f hits 1.0 (maximum). The vent zone is exactly where
          // rising H₂S meets atmospheric O₂; this is what the
          // synproportionation reaction needs.
          "O2": 0.40,
          "salinity": 4.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Sulphur Bank's host is Pliocene lake sediments + altered
          // Mesozoic Franciscan complex. The host is NOT carbonate;
          // it's clastic + silicate, which is the geological reason
          // the acid hot-spring fluid stays acidic. If we used
          // limestone here, the wall would dissolve and buffer pH
          // up out of the native_sulfur engine's window — the
          // canonical hot-spring sulfur deposit needs an inert
          // silicate host. 'basalt' is the closest proxy in this
          // codebase (silicate, dissolve() returns no-op so the
          // fluid stays acid, just like Sulphur Bank IRL).
          "composition": "basalt",
          "reactivity": 0.0,
          // Modest hot-spring vent cavity. Real Sulphur Bank vents
          // open into cm-to-meter-scale cavities; 40 mm is in the
          // mid-range and matches the simulator's vug class for
          // specimen-scale paragenesis.
          "vug_diameter_mm": 40.0,
          // Irregular archetype: acid-dissolution cavity in altered
          // sediments. The cavity geometry is anything but smooth —
          // pore-throat coalescence + secondary dissolution carves
          // an irregular profile.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 3,
          "secondary_bubbles": 7,
          // 1865 — the year mining started at Sulphur Bank
          "shape_seed": 1865
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // Active hot-spring hydrology — Sulphur Bank vents are not
        // pulsed events but continuous flow with seasonal modulation
        // (White & Roberson 1962 documented vent activity year-round
        // with summer/winter T swings). The scenario encodes "continuous"
        // as frequent recharge events every 10-15 steps: each H₂S
        // recharge pushes pH down 1.0 and refills S; the ambient_cooling
        // pH-recovery clause pushes pH up between events (at low
        // flow_rate the recovery is 0.01-0.03/step). The net is a
        // sawtooth-acidic regime that stays inside the synproportionation
        // window for the full duration. Two cooling events bracket
        // the run for the α-sulfur bipyramidal habit transition.
        { "step":  10, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #1",      "description": "Hot fluid rises with fresh H₂S" },
        { "step":  20, "type": "sulphur_bank_surface_oxidation", "name": "Surface O₂ Mixing #1", "description": "Atmospheric O₂ drives synproportionation" },
        { "step":  35, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #2",      "description": "Renewed thermal pulse — H₂S replenished" },
        { "step":  45, "type": "sulphur_bank_surface_oxidation", "name": "Surface O₂ Mixing #2", "description": "Continued S° precipitation at vent" },
        { "step":  60, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #3",      "description": "Thermal pulse" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "sulphur_bank_surface_oxidation", "name": "Surface O₂ Mixing #3", "description": "Synproportionation event" },
        { "step":  90, "type": "sulphur_bank_cooling",           "name": "Seasonal Cooling",     "description": "Vent flow slows; α-sulfur bipyramidal habit favored" },
        { "step": 105, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #4",      "description": "Hot pulse rebounds T after cooling" },
        { "step": 115, "type": "sulphur_bank_surface_oxidation", "name": "Surface O₂ Mixing #4", "description": "Late synproportionation event" },
        { "step": 130, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #5",      "description": "Sustained vent activity" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "sulphur_bank_surface_oxidation", "name": "Surface O₂ Mixing #5", "description": "Continued synproportionation" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "sulphur_bank_cooling",           "name": "Final Cooling",        "description": "Late vent cools; last bipyramidal habit window" },
        { "step": 175, "type": "sulphur_bank_h2s_recharge",      "name": "H₂S Recharge #6",      "description": "Final H₂S pulse before run-end" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "White D.E. and Roberson C.E. (1962) — Sulphur Bank, California, a major hot-spring quicksilver deposit. USGS Professional Paper 432-A.",
        "White D.E. (1981) — Active geothermal systems and hydrothermal ore deposits. Economic Geology 75th Anniversary Volume.",
        "Donnelly-Nolan J.M., Burns M.G., Goff F.E., Peters E.K., Thompson J.M. (1993) — The Geysers - Clear Lake area, California: thermal waters, mineralization, volcanism, and geothermal potential. Economic Geology 88: 301-316.",
        "EPA Superfund site CAD980893275 — Sulphur Bank Mercury Mine. Site monitoring records 1990-present document continuous hot-spring activity at the vent zone."
      ]
    },

    "sicily_solfifera": {
      "anchor": "Cianciana / Caltanissetta district, Agrigento province, Sicily — Solfifera Series (Messinian, 6-5.3 Ma). The canonical sedimentary BSR native-sulfur deposit. World's primary sulfur production center 1860s-1950s, when the Sicilian fields supplied ~80% of global elemental sulfur. Type for 'bacterial-mediated sedimentary sulfur' per Ziegenbalg et al. 2010.",
      "description": "Sedimentary native sulfur from bacterial sulfate reduction of Messinian gypsum + Pleistocene meteoric O₂ infiltration. The OTHER half of the native_sulfur story (Sulphur Bank = acid-sulfate hot-spring; Sicily = alkaline-buffered BSR-near-surface). Mineable S° crystallizes in the upper few meters of the Solfifera Series, the gypsum-marl-sulfur sequence deposited during the Mediterranean salinity crisis. Co-products: calcite cement from the BSR-generated H₂CO₃, residual selenite (Messinian gypsum), celestine from gypsum-derived Sr trace, sometimes aragonite.",
      "expects_species": ["native_sulfur", "calcite", "selenite", "celestine"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Sicilian Solfifera Series, Cianciana / Caltanissetta. The Messinian salinity crisis (6-5.3 Ma) precipitated a thick gypsum + halite + marl sequence in the central Sicilian basin (Decima & Wezel 1971; Manzi et al. 2009). Bacterial sulfate reduction at depth, fueled by organic-C burial, converted gypsum sulfate to H₂S + CaCO₃ over millions of years (Ziegenbalg et al. 2010 — sedimentary geology evidence; Aharon 2000 — isotope record). Pleistocene meteoric water infiltrated the upper meters, bringing dissolved O₂. The H₂S met O₂ in the upper oxidation zone and precipitated as native S° via synproportionation. Cianciana alone produced ~2 Mt of sulfur 1840-1950.",
        "Engine mode: this scenario fires the BSR-near-surface peak of the v80 bimodal pH factor (peaks at 2.5 Sulphur-Bank-style and 6.0 Sicily-style). The pH = 6.0 initial condition is dead-center on the BSR peak. The engine's metal_sum ≤ 100 gate fits Sicilian fluid — Messinian marls are clean (metal_sum ≈ 25, dominated by trace Fe).",
        "Co-products: the simulator's calcite + selenite + celestine + aragonite engines fire under the same broth: calcite from the 600 ppm Ca + 80 ppm CO₃ supersat; selenite (gypsum) from the same Ca + 400 ppm S (sulfate fraction); celestine from the trace Sr; aragonite as the calcite polymorph at low T + appropriate Mg/Ca. This is the geologically-real Sicilian assemblage — the same minerals you'd identify in a hand specimen from Cianciana.",
        "Wall composition: 'limestone' — Sicily IS literally hosted in calcite/gypsum matrix. The Solfifera Series sits on the Trubi Formation (Pliocene pelagic chalk) and is interbedded with limestone marls. The wall's dissolve() releases Ca + CO₃ which models the actual gypsum/calcite matrix dissolution. reactivity = 0.5 keeps the buffer gentle so pH stays in the BSR window."
      ],
      "initial": {
        // Sedimentary basin T — ambient. The Messinian-Pleistocene
        // section never reached hydrothermal T; BSR happens cool.
        "temperature_C": 30.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,            // ~5m depth (top of Solfifera oxidation zone)
        "fluid": {
          // Calcite-buffered Messinian porewater, mid-oxidation zone.
          // Composition reconstructed from Garcia-Veigas et al. 1995
          // (Mineralogy and isotope geochemistry of the Solfifera Series)
          // + Manzi et al. 2009 (fluid-inclusion data on Messinian gypsum).
          "SiO2": 30,
          // Ca high — gypsum + calcite dissolution at every interface.
          "Ca": 600,
          // CO3 moderate — BSR generates H₂CO₃ that buffers the porewater.
          "CO3": 80,
          // Sulfur: the BSR-produced sulfide pool. 400 ppm is in the
          // measured Solfifera porewater range. Above the engine's
          // 100 ppm threshold; s_f saturates at 2.0.
          "S": 400,
          // Trace metals — LOW. Messinian marls are clean evaporite-
          // derived sediments. metal_sum = Fe(5)+Cu(0)+Pb(0)+Zn(0) = 5
          // well below the engine's 100 cap.
          "Fe": 5,
          "Cu": 0,
          "Pb": 0,
          "Zn": 0,
          // Sr trace — the famous Sicilian celestine signature. Gypsum
          // carries 0.5-3% Sr (substituting for Ca); when meteoric
          // water dissolves the gypsum the Sr ends up partitioned
          // into late celestine.
          "Sr": 30,
          // Mg low — Messinian fluids were Mg-depleted after halite
          // precipitation but before sylvite/carnallite.
          "Mg": 50,
          // Na + Cl: residual brine salinity from the evaporite source.
          "Na": 400,
          "Cl": 600,
          // pH: calcite-buffered, peak of the BSR-mode ph_f factor.
          // Real Solfifera porewater measurements (Aharon 2000) cluster
          // at 5.8-6.3. 6.0 is dead-center.
          "pH": 6.0,
          // O₂: mixed-oxic Pleistocene meteoric infiltration. 0.40 is
          // the peak of the engine's nativeRedoxTent — the
          // synproportionation sweet spot.
          "O2": 0.40,
          "salinity": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          // Solfifera Series is HOSTED IN CALCITE/GYPSUM MATRIX.
          // Unlike Sulphur Bank (silicate-hosted to keep pH acid),
          // Sicily WANTS the carbonate buffer — that's exactly what
          // keeps pH at 6.0 in the BSR-mode window. The limestone
          // composition's dissolve() releases Ca + CO₃, modeling the
          // actual gypsum/calcite matrix dissolution.
          "composition": "limestone",
          // reactivity 0.5 = gentle dissolution. Higher and the wall
          // would over-buffer pH up to ~7.5 (out of the BSR window's
          // ph_f peak); lower and there'd be no carbonate cement
          // formation. 0.5 holds pH around 6.0 across the run.
          "reactivity": 0.5,
          // Modest sedimentary pocket — gypsum-marl porosity is
          // small-scale, mm to cm.
          "vug_diameter_mm": 30.0,
          // Architecture: irregular sedimentary pore-space, gypsum-
          // marl pore-throat coalescence. Same archetype as the
          // Tsumeb-style gossan (supergene_oxidation) — geologically
          // similar in that both are weathering-driven irregular
          // cavities.
          "architecture": "irregular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 5,
          // 1860 — the year industrial Sicilian sulfur mining took off
          "shape_seed": 1860,
          // Wall trace chemistry — Messinian marls carry minor Fe + Mn
          // (mostly from organic-matter-bound clay phases). Released
          // into fluid via the limestone wall's dissolution mechanic.
          "wall_Fe_ppm": 80,
          "wall_Mn_ppm": 30
        }
      },
      "events": [
        // 10 events over 200 steps modeling the Pleistocene infiltration
        // and BSR-cycle hydrology. The geological story: each event is
        // a recharge pulse where meteoric water dissolves more
        // upgradient gypsum (replenishing S substrate) and brings O₂
        // (driving synproportionation in the oxidation zone). Slow
        // cycle — sedimentary BSR operates on 10,000-year timescales
        // IRL but compressed to 200 steps here.
        { "step":  15, "type": "sicily_gypsum_dissolution",        "name": "Gypsum Pulse #1",          "description": "Meteoric water dissolves Messinian gypsum" },
        { "step":  25, "type": "sicily_meteoric_o2_pulse",         "name": "Meteoric O₂ Pulse #1",     "description": "O₂-rich water reaches the oxidation zone" },
        { "step":  50, "type": "sicily_gypsum_dissolution",        "name": "Gypsum Pulse #2",          "description": "Renewed gypsum dissolution upgradient" },
        { "step":  60, "type": "sicily_meteoric_o2_pulse",         "name": "Meteoric O₂ Pulse #2",     "description": "Synproportionation continues" },
        { "step":  85, "type": "sicily_carbonate_buffer",          "name": "Carbonate Buffer Lock",    "description": "BSR-generated H₂CO₃ pins pH at 6.0" },
        { "step": 105, "type": "sicily_gypsum_dissolution",        "name": "Gypsum Pulse #3",          "description": "Continued upgradient gypsum dissolution" },
        { "step": 115, "type": "sicily_late_synproportionation",   "name": "Late Synproportionation",  "description": "Fresh O₂ + replenished S pool" },
        { "step": 140, "type": "sicily_carbonate_buffer",          "name": "Mid-Run Buffer Refresh",   "description": "Carbonate buffer maintains pH 6.0" },
        { "step": 160, "type": "sicily_late_synproportionation",   "name": "Late Synproportionation",  "description": "Continued S° growth in oxidation zone" },
        { "step": 180, "type": "sicily_late_synproportionation",   "name": "Final Synproportionation", "description": "Last meteoric pulse before run-end" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Ziegenbalg S.B., Brunner B., Birgel D., Voigt M., Strauss H., Peckmann J. (2010) — Formation of secondary carbonates and native sulphur in sulphate-rich Messinian strata, Sicily. Sedimentary Geology 227: 37-50.",
        "Manzi V., Lugli S., Roveri M., Schreiber B.C. (2009) — A new facies model for the Upper Gypsum of Sicily (Italy): chronological and palaeoenvironmental constraints. Sedimentology 56: 1937-1960.",
        "Garcia-Veigas J., Ortí F., Rosell L., Ayora C., Rouchy J.M., Lugli S. (1995) — The Messinian salt of the Mediterranean: geochemical study of the salt from the central Sicily basin. Bulletin Société Géologique de France 166: 699-710.",
        "Decima A., Wezel F.C. (1971) — Osservazioni sulle evaporiti messiniane della Sicilia centro-meridionale. Rivista Mineraria Siciliana 22 (130-132): 172-187.",
        "Aharon P. (2000) — Microbial processes and products fueled by hydrocarbons at submarine seeps. Microbial Sediments (Springer): 270-281. (Sulfur-isotope evidence for BSR in Sicilian Solfifera Series.)",
        "Wikipedia — Sicilian sulfur mining (history + production figures 1860-1950)."
      ]
    },

    "sunnyside_american_tunnel": {
      "anchor": "Sunnyside Mine / American Tunnel, Silverton caldera, San Juan County, Colorado. Intermediate-sulfidation polymetallic epithermal vein deposit hosted in the Crystal Lake Tuff (27.5 Ma San Juan ignimbrite). The American Tunnel (driven 1959, plugged 2003) was the principal modern source of Silverton-district display rhodochrosite + octahedral REE-fluorite + manganocalcite specimens. Per Casadevall & Ohmoto 1977 Econ. Geol. 72:1285 six-stage paragenesis (compressed to four stages here).",
      "description": "Late-stage carbonate-fluoride paragenesis at the Sunnyside-American Tunnel vein system. The scenario runs primary sulfide-Au-quartz (Casadevall Stages I-IV at 280-260°C) → Stage V Mn-carbonate (pale-pink small rhodochrosite at 215-245°C, Fe-poor signature) → Stage VI early fluoride pulse (octahedral REE-fluorite at 195-230°C with grass-green visible color + brilliant blue SW UV from Eu²⁺ activator per Bosze & Rakovan 2002 GCA 66:997) → Stage VI late manganocalcite cap (cauliflower botryoidal Mn²⁺-bright-fluorescing calcite at 175-200°C). The REE source is leaching of devitrified ignimbrite glass from the Carpenter Ridge Tuff host per Bachmann et al. 2014 — Eu²⁺ from feldspar at residence T, Y³⁺ general. Headline specimens: pale-pink rhodochrosite + manganocalcite cabinet pieces; octahedral REE-fluorite (~1-2 cm, sometimes with rhodochrosite + manganocalcite associates); native gold in milky quartz from the primary Stage IV ore. Many of these specimens carry dealer labels reading 'Standard Mine, Silverton' — but the only documented Standard Mine in Colorado is in Gunnison County (Ruby District, EPA Superfund, ~80 mi NE, different deposit). The 'Standard Mine, Silverton' label is dealer-conflation; the actual source is American Tunnel material from the 1959-1991 production window.",
      "expects_species": ["pyrite", "galena", "sphalerite", "chalcopyrite", "quartz", "rhodochrosite", "fluorite", "calcite", "native_gold"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Sunnyside Mine / American Tunnel, Silverton caldera, San Juan County, Colorado. The Silverton caldera nests inside the older San Juan caldera, both in the Oligocene San Juan Volcanic Field. Crystal Lake Tuff erupted at 27.5 Ma collapsing the Silverton caldera; resurgent doming reopened the ring-fracture system; mineralization peaked ~22.5 Ma (Lake City caldera granite porphyry intrusion). Two K-Ar sericite events bracket the hydrothermal history at 22.5 Ma (district-wide propylitic) and 21 Ma (focused sericite). References: Burbank & Luedke 1968 USGS PP 535 (canonical district geology); Casadevall & Ohmoto 1977 Econ. Geol. 72:1285 (the six-stage Sunnyside paragenesis + fluid inclusion data).",
        "Labeling note (CORRECTED v106 2026-05-20): specimens labeled 'Standard Mine, Silverton' refer to Sunnyside mine material from the Standard Metals Corporation lease period (1959-1978). Standard Metals leased Sunnyside in 1959, drove the American Tunnel from the Gold King portal at Gladstone, and operated until the June 4 1978 Lake Emma disaster (surface lake drained into upper workings; mine flooded; lease ended). The label is accurate to a 19-year production window and identifies the operator — the '[Operator] Mine' convention is well-attested (Hecla Mine for Sunshine material, Anaconda Mine for various Butte properties, etc.). The v105 commit originally described this as 'dealer-conflation' with the unrelated Standard Mine in Gunnison County (Ruby District near Crested Butte) — that interpretation was wrong; corrected here. The Silverton-Standard label is its own legitimate provenance anchor referencing Standard Metals' tenure. Casadevall & Ohmoto 1977 Econ. Geol. 72:1285, the canonical Sunnyside paragenesis paper, studied Standard-Metals-era ore (the paper precedes the 1978 disaster by one year), so the simulator's science anchor and the boss's specimens come from the same operating window.",
        "Six-stage compressed to four: Casadevall & Ohmoto 1977 documented six paragenetic stages (I pyrite-quartz, II banded quartz-sulfide, III massive galena-sphalerite-chalcopyrite-bornite-hematite, IV Au-Te-quartz, V Mn ores rhodochrosite-rich, VI quartz-fluorite-carbonate-sulfate). Stages I-IV are compressed into a single primary-ore phase in this scenario (steps 1-30) because the simulator's nucleation cap doesn't reward fine-grained sequencing of the primary sulfides. Stages V and VI map directly to the late-stage carbonate + fluoride pulses (steps 30-185).",
        "Engine fit (v103 + v104 infra commits): the Y fluid field (added v103) drives the REE-octahedral fluorite habit per Bosze & Rakovan 2002. The manganocalcite branch (v103) fires when Mn>5 + Fe<2 + low supersaturation; bright Mn²⁺ SW UV fluorescence note (graduated v103). The v104 fluorite color correction makes Y-rich fluorite display grass-green (yttrofluorite character per Naumov & Naumova 1980 + Pierce 1990 Pikes Peak HREE-fluorite mechanism), not blue (blue is the LOW-Y F-center mechanism). The boss's Silverton specimens (pale-blue-with-green-tint in white light, brilliant blue under SW UV) are photobleached display material — original was richer green, fluorescence preserved.",
        "Wallrock: 'basalt' proxy for the Crystal Lake Tuff silicate ignimbrite host. Reactivity 0.0 keeps the wall inert (the San Juan tuffs are crystalline silicate, not carbonate-buffered) — late-stage neutralization comes from CO₂ degassing of the cooling fluid, not from wallrock dissolution. Vug diameter 50 mm matches typical American Tunnel cabinet-pocket scale (boss's specimens range thumbnail to small miniature). Architecture 'pocket' for the vein-bounded cavity. Shape_seed 1959 (the year the American Tunnel was driven from the Gold King portal at Gladstone).",
        "Boss specimen calibration: 15 rhodochrosites from Silverton (most pale-pink, small ~3-10 mm rhombs); two with fluorite; one with calcite manganocalcite cap; the fluorites pale-blue-with-green-tint visible (probably photobleached from original richer green); SW UV brilliant blue fluorescence on fluorite (Eu²⁺/Y³⁺ activator); brilliant salmon fluorescence on manganocalcite (Mn²⁺ activator, 'much brighter than most' per boss observation). Plus a native gold in quartz from the primary ore phase. The scenario aims to reproduce this assemblage at seed 42."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 280.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 400,
          "Ca": 200,
          "CO3": 50,
          "Fe": 10,
          "Mn": 30,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Na": 100,
          "K": 30,
          "F": 8,
          "Y": 0.0,
          "Cu": 25,
          "Pb": 80,
          "Zn": 120,
          "S": 200,
          "Cl": 60,
          "Au": 0.5,
          "Te": 1.0,
          "Sb": 5,
          "As": 10,
          "Ag": 8,
          "pH": 4.5,
          "O2": 0.05,
          "salinity": 5.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "basalt",
          "reactivity": 0.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 50.0,
          "architecture": "pocket",
          "primary_bubbles": 4,
          "secondary_bubbles": 6,
          "shape_seed": 1959
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step":  30, "type": "sunnyside_cooling_transition",          "name": "Primary Cooling",                     "description": "Stage I-IV closes — sulfides + Au-quartz lock in; T drops; pH neutralizes" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "sunnyside_stage_v_mn_carbonate",        "name": "Stage V Mn-Carbonate Pulse",           "description": "Pale-pink rhodochrosite — Casadevall Stage V (245-200°C, Fe-poor lattice)" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "sunnyside_stage_vi_fluoride_pulse",     "name": "Stage VI Fluoride + REE Pulse",        "description": "Magmatic F + Y leached from Carpenter Ridge Tuff glass — octahedral REE-fluorite (grass-green visible, blue SW UV)" },
        { "step": 150, "type": "sunnyside_stage_vi_manganocalcite_cap", "name": "Stage VI Manganocalcite Cap",          "description": "Cauliflower botryoidal Mn²⁺-fluorescent calcite — terminal Sunnyside texture" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Burbank W.S. & Luedke R.G. (1968) — Geology and Ore Deposits of the Eureka and Adjoining Districts, San Juan Mountains, Colorado. USGS Professional Paper 535.",
        "Casadevall T. & Ohmoto H. (1977) — Sunnyside Mine, Eureka mining district, San Juan County, Colorado; geochemistry of gold and base metal ore deposition in a volcanic environment. Economic Geology 72: 1285-1320. DOI 10.2113/gsecongeo.72.7.1285.",
        "Burbank W.S. (1933) — Geology and Ore Deposits of the South Silverton Mining Area, San Juan County, Colorado. USGS Professional Paper 378-A.",
        "Bachmann O. et al. (2014) — Building zoned ignimbrites by recycling silicic cumulates: insight from the Carpenter Ridge Tuff, CO. Contrib. Min. Pet. 167: 1025. DOI 10.1007/s00410-014-1025-3. (REE/Eu source rock for the Y³⁺/Eu²⁺ leached during the Stage VI fluoride pulse.)",
        "Bosze S. & Rakovan J. (2002) — Surface-structure-controlled sectoral zoning of REE in fluorite from Long Lake NY and Bingham NM. Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta 66: 997-1009. DOI 10.1016/S0016-7037(01)00822-5. (Octahedral fluorite habit mechanism; Y³⁺ partition coefficient 1.4-3.5x into {111} vs {100}.)",
        "Naumov V.A. & Naumova S.S. (1980) — Optical spectra of rare-earth-bearing fluorites. (Russian literature; original yttrofluorite green color-mechanism description.)",
        "Pierce M.L. (1990) — Color centers and rare-earth substitution in Pikes Peak fluorite. (HREE-cluster green color mechanism distinct from F-center blue.)",
        "Bill H. & Calas G. (1978) — Color centers, associated rare-earth ions and the origin of coloration in natural fluorites. Phys. Chem. Min. 3: 117-131. (F-center photobleaching kinetics; SW UV REE fluorescence bleach-stability.)",
        "Pohl W.L. (2011) — Economic Geology of Mineral Deposits. Schweizerbart. (Manganocalcite paragenesis + Mn²⁺ activator fluorescence brightness.)",
        "Research dossier 2026-05-19 — internal research-agent compilation anchoring the scenario broth on Casadevall fluid-inclusion data + Bachmann REE-source-rock budget + boss specimen calibration targets."
      ]
    },

    "roughten_gill": {
      "anchor": "Roughten Gill Mine, Caldbeck Fells, Lake District, Cumbria, England. Polymetallic Pb-Cu fissure-vein deposit in Eycott Volcanic Group + Carrock Fell Intrusive Complex (granophyre footwall + gabbro hangingwall). Worked 1700s-1894 for lead + minor copper, dumps reworked for barite post-1894; classic specimen-collector locality. TYPE LOCALITY for plumbogummite (Hartley 1882; Förtsch 1967 corrected type material to plumbogummite-hinsdalite-hidalgoite mix-crystal). Per Cooper & Stanley (1990) 'Minerals of the English Lake District: Caldbeck Fells' + the Russell Society multi-part review (Bridges et al. 2011 Part 3).",
      "description": "Pb-Cu fissure-vein in Eycott Volcanic Group volcanics + Carrock Fell Intrusive Complex granophyre/gabbro walls, weathered through an exhaustively-documented supergene oxidation sequence: primary galena+chalcopyrite+sphalerite+pyrite+tetrahedrite/tennantite (T 110-130°C, high-salinity Na-Ca-Cl basinal brine, H2S-buffered) → cooling lockup → pyrite-oxidation AMD acid pulse → linarite stage (Pb+Cu+SO4 with CO3:SO4 << 0.3 producing the iconic Roughten Gill azure-blue cabinet specimens) → caledonite + brochantite transition as CO3 rises → leadhillite cap when CO3:SO4 > 1.5 and Cu depletes. The v100 Pb-Cu sulfate trio (linarite + caledonite + leadhillite) fires in their type-district here — Cooper & Stanley + the Russell Society three-part review document each mineral per-mine in Caldbeck Fells. TYPE LOCALITY for plumbogummite PbAl3(PO4)2(OH)5·H2O (Hartley 1882 from Roughten Gill); plumbogummite is NOT yet wired in the simulator and is flagged as the imminent v108 add-mineral commit to complete the type-locality story. The headline cabinet aesthetic is plumbogummite-after-pyromorphite pseudomorphs — cobalt-blue botryoidal crusts draping green pyromorphite hexagonal prisms — which will only complete once plumbogummite engine ships.",
      // v180: bayldonite REMOVED from expects (Shape D — declaration
      // tightening, v91 sweep pattern). Its engine encodes the formula's
      // Cu-dominance (PbCu3: gate Cu≥100 AND Cu/Pb≥2 → Cu≥140 at Pb 70),
      // which this Pb-dominant broth can never honestly reach (Cu max
      // ~75 at the plateau); forcing it would mean tripling Cu and
      // transforming the whole scenario. At the real Roughten Gill
      // bayldonite is a minor accessory; the catalog keeps the species,
      // this locality just doesn't promise it. mottramite WAS the one
      // aspirational entry; v193 DELIVERED it (5 crystals at seed 42) via
      // the supergene V-leach + engine V-economics fixes — see the
      // V-axis note in initial.fluid.
      "expects_species": ["galena", "sphalerite", "chalcopyrite", "pyrite", "tetrahedrite", "tennantite", "quartz", "calcite", "cerussite", "anglesite", "linarite", "caledonite", "leadhillite", "brochantite", "pyromorphite", "mimetite", "mottramite", "native_silver"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Roughten Gill Mine, Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria. The Caldbeck Fells district occupies the northern Skiddaw inlier; Roughten Gill itself sits on the southern flank of Balliway Rigg (NY 304 344). Host is the Ordovician Eycott Volcanic Group (basaltic-andesitic to rhyolitic lavas + tuffs — NOT Borrowdale Volcanic Group, a common error in derivative literature). The South Vein cuts a NE-SW normal fault juxtaposing the Carrock Fell Intrusive Complex's Iron Crag Microgranite (Carrock Granophyre, U-Pb zircon 452.4 ± 3.1 Ma) against gabbro of the same complex. Caldbeck Fells district hosts ~175 valid mineral species — the greatest mineralogical diversity per unit area in the British Isles per Bridges et al. 2011 + Cooper & Stanley 1990.",
        "Type locality for plumbogummite PbAl3(PO4)2(OH)5·H2O (Hartley J. 1882 'On plumbogummite from Roughten Gill, Cumberland' MinMag 5:21). Förtsch E.B. (1967) MinMag 36:530 re-examined Hartley's type material by X-ray + IR + optical methods and showed it to be a plumbogummite-hinsdalite-hidalgoite mix-crystal — the bluish-grey crust contains all three alunite-supergroup endmembers. Plumbogummite is currently NOT in the simulator's mineral catalog (128 live minerals as of v104). Imminent add-mineral commit (v108) will wire plumbogummite as a Pb-Al-PO4 supergene-late phase; the scenario will pick it up automatically once the engine wires, completing the headline cabinet aesthetic (plumbogummite-after-pyromorphite pseudomorphs).",
        "Engine fit: this scenario fires the v100 Pb-Cu sulfate trio (linarite + caledonite + leadhillite) in their type-district. v100 listed Leadhills (Scotland) + Tsumeb (Namibia) as canonical references; Caldbeck Fells is the third type-locality district and is now represented. The trio's CO3:SO4 ratio fork is the load-bearing discriminator: linarite needs CO3:SO4 < 0.3 (early supergene, before atmospheric CO2 has had time to accumulate); caledonite needs 0.1-2.0 (sweet spot 0.3-1.0); leadhillite needs > 1.5 (terminal stage, Cu mostly consumed). The five-stage event sequence walks the broth through this CO3:SO4 evolution naturally.",
        "Eycott Volcanic Group + Carrock Fell granophyre/gabbro host = SILICATE not carbonate. Wall composition 'basalt' as closest silicate proxy in the sim (no granophyre/gabbro composition supported). reactivity=0.0 keeps the wall inert — Caldbeck supergene chemistry is NOT carbonate-buffered (unlike Tsumeb where limestone wallrock buffers CO3 high). At Caldbeck, CO3 comes from atmospheric CO2 dissolution in meteoric water + minor vein-calcite during the supergene window. This is the geological reason linarite is so common at Roughten Gill (early-stage low-CO3 conditions persist; the deposit is 'deficient in carbonates' per Rumsey et al. 2008 Red Gill paper, applies to Roughten Gill similarly) and leadhillite is rarer (only fires once meteoric CO3 builds up). Same trio engine as Tsumeb, but different broth trajectory.",
        "Fluid chemistry per BGS Earthwise Lake District + Russell Society Caldbeck papers: T 110-130°C primary (cooler than Pennine-Yorkshire 150-250°C bracket; calibrated to the Lake District lower bound); salinity 15-30 wt% NaCl-eq basinal brine (scenario broth at 8 wt% as scaled simulator value); Ag-in-galena ~838 ppm (the 'lattice silver' reservoir liberated during supergene oxidation produces the native_silver flakes documented at Roughten Gill); native antimony + Sb-sulphosalt inclusions in galena are diagnostic. Sulfur partly sourced from Carboniferous evaporites per BGS sulfur-isotope work.",
        "Specimen aesthetic per Cooper & Stanley + Russell Society multi-part review (Bridges 2011, Green 2008, Rumsey 2008): thumbnail-to-small-cabinet scale (Caldbeck specimens are characteristically small — vug size_class). Linarite forms deep azure-blue elongate-tabular crystals (the headline Roughten Gill aesthetic, prized by UK collectors as some of the world's best linarites). Caledonite blue-green prismatic to acicular crystals up to 5 mm. Leadhillite pearly-white mica-like tablets. Brochantite emerald-green tufts. Pyromorphite world-class — vivid green hexagonal prisms in multiple colour variants (khaki, brown, lime green, pink, yellow per Cooper & Stanley palette). Mimetite as 'campylite' red barrel-shaped overgrowths on pyromorphite (the upper Roughten Gill / Mexico mine occurrence) + lemon-yellow overgrowths at Barstow's Trench. Mottramite as dark-brown to buff rice-grain microcrystals (Brae Fell Mine satellite within the Roughten Gill complex; minute < 0.1 mm). Native silver as < 0.3 mm plates in quartz-calcite microcavities; tarnishes to acanthite as post-collection growth.",
        "MINERALS NOT YET IN CATALOG (future add-mineral candidates beyond plumbogummite): hinsdalite + hidalgoite (alunite-supergroup endmembers in the type-mix), beudantite + corkite (Fe analogs), redgillite Cu6(OH)10(SO4)·H2O (Caldbeck type-mineral from Red Gill, Pluth et al. 2005 MinMag 69:973), mattheddleite Pb20(SiO4)6(SO4)6Cl4(OH)8 (Caldbeck-not-uncommon in caledonite-linarite cavities), scotlandite PbSO3 (the sulfite — Caldbeck-significant), tsumebite + arsentsumebite Pb2Cu(PO4)(SO4)(OH) family. A future 'alunite-supergroup family' add-mineral commit would benefit Roughten Gill, Tsumeb, and many global supergene localities simultaneously.",
        "v107 candidate calibration notes per vugg-tune-scenario: pyromorphite needs P > 2 + Cl > 5 (broth carries P=4 + Cl=25, should fire). Mimetite needs As(V) > 3 + Cl > 2 (broth As=12 with pyrite_oxidation pulse pushing higher). Mottramite needs Cu > 50 + V > 10 + Pb > 40 (broth carries V=12 + event-pulse Cu to 60 — geologically Brae Fell satellite, may fire marginally at seed 42). Native silver requires Ag mobilization (broth Ag=12 representing the 838-ppm-Ag-in-galena reservoir; relies on Ag liberation during pyrite_oxidation pulse). If any miss at seed 42, vugg-tune-scenario follow-up commit is the right pattern."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 130.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 0.5,
        "fluid": {
          // v109 tune (2026-05-20): SiO2 200 -> 50 to suppress
          // dioptase (Cu-silicate wrong for Caldbeck); V 12 -> 6 to
          // route to mottramite over vanadinite (vanadinite wrong
          // for Caldbeck); Al 8 -> 15 + P 4 -> 8 for plumbogummite
          // headroom; CO3 5 -> 25 for cerussite + caledonite +
          // leadhillite gates; Cu 30 -> 40 for brochantite +
          // mottramite. Per Bridges 2011 + Cooper & Stanley 1990
          // chemistry (Caldbeck Pb-Cu vein is carbonate-deficient
          // but not carbonate-zero; broth 25 ppm CO3 still well below
          // Tsumeb's 110 ppm).
          "SiO2": 50,
          "Ca": 60,
          "CO3": 25,
          "Fe": 25,
          "Mn": 2,
          "Mg": 8,
          "Na": 80,
          "K": 25,
          "Cu": 40,
          "Pb": 70,
          "Zn": 60,
          "S": 200,
          "Cl": 30,
          "Ag": 12,
          "As": 12,
          "Sb": 5,
          // V stays 6 in the INITIAL broth — and that is now understood to
          // be CORRECT. History: v109 6→0 rippled 3 minerals; v180 6→12
          // rippled sphalerite 7x→2x. Both reverted, both blamed "the V
          // axis." v193's gate census proved the axis was never the
          // problem — its PLACEMENT IN TIME was. An initial-broth V bump
          // fires from step 0 and re-rolls the primary-suite RNG; the V
          // actually belongs in the SUPERGENE window (the header's
          // "wallrock V 10-20 ppm leaches in the supergene window"), so
          // v193 added the leach to the step-70 pyrite-oxidation event
          // (V 6→14, AFTER the step-25 primary lockup → primaries intact,
          // sphalerite 2→3). Combined with the v193 engine fixes
          // (vanadinite redox gate + descloizite-group V-economics gate
          // 10→4) mottramite NOW fires 5 at seed 42. Leave initial V at 6;
          // the mechanism lives in the event, not the broth.
          "V": 6,
          "Al": 15,
          "P": 8,
          "pH": 5.0,
          "O2": 0.05,
          "salinity": 8.0
        },
        "wall": {
          "composition": "basalt",
          "reactivity": 0.0,
          "vug_diameter_mm": 25.0,
          "size_class": "vug",
          "architecture": "tabular",
          "primary_bubbles": 2,
          "secondary_bubbles": 4,
          "shape_seed": 1882,
          // v162: supergene-dominated regime (T 130→22°C; the run is mostly
          // the near-surface Pb-Cu oxidation sequence). No magmatic thermal
          // pulses — they were spuriously reheating the cold linarite/
          // caledonite/leadhillite oxidation stages toward ~120°C.
          "thermal_pulses": false
        }
      },
      "events": [
        { "step":  25, "type": "roughten_gill_primary_lockup",          "name": "Primary Stage Closes",         "description": "Galena + chalcopyrite + pyrite + sphalerite + tetrahedrite lock in; T crashes" },
        { "step":  70, "type": "roughten_gill_pyrite_oxidation",        "name": "Pyrite Oxidation AMD Pulse",    "description": "Acid pulse from FeS2 oxidation; Cu + Pb mobilized; cerussite + anglesite + mimetite begin" },
        { "step": 110, "type": "roughten_gill_linarite_stage",          "name": "Linarite Window",               "description": "Azure-blue linarite — CO3:SO4 << 0.3, the headline Roughten Gill specimen aesthetic" },
        { "step": 145, "type": "roughten_gill_caledonite_transition",   "name": "Caledonite + Brochantite",      "description": "CO3 rises; caledonite epitactic on linarite + brochantite as Cu sulfate end-member" },
        { "step": 175, "type": "roughten_gill_leadhillite_cap",         "name": "Leadhillite Cap",               "description": "Cu depleted; CO3:SO4 > 1.5; leadhillite + pyromorphite + cerussite cap the paragenesis" }
      ],
      "sources": [
        "Cooper M.P. & Stanley C.J. (1990) — Minerals of the English Lake District: Caldbeck Fells. Natural History Museum, London. ISBN 0-565-01102-2. THE canonical multi-volume monograph with per-mine paragenetic detail for every Caldbeck locality.",
        "Bridges T.F., Green D.I., Rumsey M.S. & Leppington C.M. (2011) — A review of the mineralisation at the Roughton Gill Mines, Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria: Part 3 - Roughton Gill Mine. Journal of the Russell Society 14: 3-23. The modern definitive paper on Roughten Gill specifically.",
        "Green D.I., Bridges T.F., Rumsey M.S., Leppington C.M. & Tindle A.G. (2008) — A review of the mineralogy of the Roughton Gill Mines, Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria: Part 2 - The Roughton Gill South Vein on Balliway Rigg. Journal of the Russell Society 11: 3-28.",
        "Rumsey M.S. et al. (2008) — A review of the mineralization at Red Gill Mine, Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria, England. Journal of the Russell Society 11: 29-47. Companion paper covering the adjacent Red Gill (carbonate-deficient supergene chemistry is identified there and applies to Roughten Gill similarly).",
        "Symes R.F. & Young B.R. (2008) — Minerals of Northern England. British Geological Survey / National Museums Scotland. ISBN 978-1-905267-01-9. Regional context for Caldbeck within the broader Northern English mining heritage.",
        "Förtsch E.B. (1967) — Plumbogummite from Roughten Gill, Cumberland. Mineralogical Magazine 36 (280): 530-538. DOI 10.1180/minmag.1967.036.280.07. Critical re-examination of Hartley's 1882 type material — demonstrated it is a plumbogummite-hinsdalite-hidalgoite mix-crystal by X-ray + IR + optical methods.",
        "Hartley J. (1882) — On plumbogummite from Roughten Gill, Cumberland. Mineralogical Magazine 5: 21-23. Original type description of plumbogummite from the type locality.",
        "Russell A. (1925) — On the occurrence of plumbogummite at Roughten Gill, Cumberland. Mineralogical Magazine 20: 257-264. Russell's Caldbeck mineralogy work.",
        "Russell A. (1986) — A review of the mineralization of the English Lake District. Mineralogical Magazine 50: 587-600.",
        "Pluth J.J., Steele I.M., Kampf A.R. & Green D.I. (2005) — Redgillite, Cu6(OH)10(SO4).H2O, a new mineral from Caldbeck Fells, Cumbria, England: description and crystal structure. Mineralogical Magazine 69: 973-980. Redgillite is a Caldbeck type-locality species (Red Gill, adjacent); flagged for future add-mineral.",
        "Stanley C.J., Symes R.F. & Jones G.C. (1991) — Nickeloan mottramite and a chemical and structural study of the descloizite group of minerals. Mineralogical Magazine 55: 121-126. Caldbeck mottramite chemistry.",
        "Goldring D. (1991) — Cumbria's Underground Heritage. Historical mining context for the Caldbeck Fells district + Roughten Gill working history.",
        "British Geological Survey Earthwise — Mineralization in the Lake District. Fluid-inclusion T 110-130°C, K-Ar wallrock alteration ages 360-330 Ma, sulfur partly from Carboniferous evaporites, Ag-in-galena ~838 ppm.",
        "Research dossier 2026-05-20 — internal research-agent compilation anchoring the scenario broth on Cooper & Stanley 1990 + Russell Society three-part review + BGS Earthwise."
      ]
    },

    "jeffrey_mine": {
      "anchor": "Jeffrey Mine, Val-des-Sources (formerly Asbestos), Quebec, Canada. Open-pit chrysotile-asbestos mine 1881-2011; produced ~40% of world chrysotile for most of the 20th century. Town renamed itself in 2020 from Asbestos to Val-des-Sources to step out from under the asbestos-health-crisis baggage. Among mineral collectors NOT famous for asbestos but for the rodingite metasomatic assemblage exposed by the open-pit excavation — Ca-Al-Mg silicate cabinet specimens 1880s through 2011. The world's premier locality for cabinet-grade CYPRINE vesuvianite (Cu-bearing sky-to-deep-blue Cu²⁺-O charge-transfer variety per Bernardini 1981 MR 12(5):277 figs 12-15). Geological context: Thetford Mines ophiolite complex, Quebec Appalachians, obducted ophiolite from the Taconian Orogeny ~470 Ma; host is serpentinized peridotite with cross-cutting mafic dikes that have been metasomatically altered to rodingite.",
      "description": "Rodingite metasomatic assemblage in the Jeffrey Mine pit. The fluid evolution walks the broth through five stages: (1) Serpentinization onset — olivine + pyroxene hydration releases Mg + Si + Ni + Fe to a hyperalkaline (pH 10.5-11.2), strongly reducing (O2 < 0.1) fluid at T 380→340°C. Chrysotile + brucite + magnetite + awaruite fire as the serpentinization byproducts. (2) Mafic dike alteration begins — the alkaline serpentinizing fluid invades cross-cutting mafic dikes (basalt-to-gabbro composition), releasing Ca + Al + Si from dike plagioclase + clinopyroxene. Trace Cr from chromite enables chrome varieties. Grossular + diopside fire as the high-T garnet + clinopyroxene endmember pair. (3) Mid-rodingite — vesuvianite stage. Trace Cu (1-4 ppm) from background chalcopyrite enables CYPRINE — the world-reference Jeffrey aesthetic per Bernardini 1981. Sky-blue cyprine vesuvianite at 1-5 ppm Cu, deep-azure cyprine > 5 ppm. (4) Late Ca-silicates — Na rises (from late-stage albitization of dike feldspar); pectolite spray-radiating habit on grossular substrate fires. Wollastonite acicular sprays. Prehnite pale-green botryoidal (Fe³⁺ trace). (5) Terminal datolite — trace B (from late hydrothermal fluid concentration) drives datolite gemmy_vitreous_terminated on prehnite/wollastonite substrate. Final-stage cabinet aesthetic; colorless to pale-yellow gemmy datolite crystals. The KEY DISCRIMINATOR vs. all other scenarios is the hyperalkaline pH (10-12) — rodingite is the alkaline outlier in the simulator's catalog (most other scenarios run pH 4-8).",
      "expects_species": ["chrysotile", "brucite", "magnetite", "awaruite", "grossular", "diopside", "vesuvianite", "pectolite", "wollastonite", "prehnite", "datolite", "calcite"],
      "duration_steps": 200,
      "notes": [
        "Anchor: Jeffrey Mine, Val-des-Sources (45.7686°N 71.9347°W), Quebec, Canada. Open-pit chrysotile-asbestos mine 1881-2011. The pit-side ROAD CUT exposures are the canonical Jeffrey cabinet-specimen source — chrysotile-asbestos veins crisscrossed by mafic dikes, with rodingite-altered contact zones in the dike margins. The town renamed itself Val-des-Sources ('Valley of Springs') in 2020 from its original 'Asbestos' name. The 1949 Quebec Asbestos Strike is a labor-history flashpoint — a 4-month strike at Asbestos QC that was a watershed moment in modern Quebec political history. These cultural-historical facts are real but the scenario encodes the GEOLOGY — the rodingite assemblage is the cabinet-collector story.",
        "Type-quality CABINET CYPRINE: Jeffrey is the world's premier locality for cyprine vesuvianite (Cu-bearing sky-blue to deep-azure variety; Cu²⁺-O charge transfer at trace Cu levels 0.5-5 ppm). Bernardini 1981 MR 12(5):277 figs 12-15 document the cyprine aesthetic; the world-reference best material. Cyprine is technically type-Norway 1820 (Sjøåsen, Telemark) but Jeffrey is the cabinet standard. The scenario adds Cu to 4 ppm in the mid-rodingite stage event (stage 3) to drive cyprine dispatch in the vesuvianite grow engine.",
        "Engine fit: this scenario fires the COMPLETE rodingite assemblage shipped v110-v114 — chrysotile (v114 host matrix), brucite (v114), awaruite (v114, microscopic Ni-Fe alloy grains in serpentine matrix), grossular (v112) with chromian green via Cr trace, diopside (v112) with chrome-diopside via Cr trace, vesuvianite (v111) with CYPRINE via Cu trace, pectolite (v113, spray-radiating on grossular), wollastonite (v113), prehnite (v113, pale-green via Fe trace), datolite (v110, gemmy on prehnite/wollastonite substrate). Five-stage event sequence walks the chemistry through the prograde paragenesis. The forward-prepared substrate slots from v110-v112 (datolite-on-prehnite, vesuvianite-on-grossular, etc.) now activate as the minerals co-occur.",
        "New 'ultramafic' wall composition (v115): broader than 'serpentinite' specifically; covers serpentinite + peridotite + dunite + harzburgite hosts. Future scenarios at Cassiar BC + New Idria CA + Italian Alps Val Malenco can reuse. Wall is silicate-inert (no acid dissolution), tabular architecture (rodingite alteration contacts are tabular zones between dike and host), size_class pocket (cabinet-scale specimens). reactivity=0.0 keeps the wall inert. shape_seed 1881 (Jeffrey opening year).",
        "Initial broth at step 0: T 380°C (high-T rodingite metasomatism), pH 10.0 (hyperalkaline serpentinization), O2 0.1 (strongly reducing), salinity 1.5 (low-salinity metamorphic fluid per Manning & Bird 1990), pressure 1.5 kbar (mid-crustal ophiolite). Mg 220 (serpentinization-derived Mg-rich), SiO2 200 (silica framework), Ca 350 (rodingite Ca-rich), Al 30 (dike Al), Ni 120 (peridotite-derived), Fe 50 (peridotite + chromite), Cr 1.0 (trace chromite-derived), Cu 1.0 (trace dike-chalcopyrite-derived), B 0.5 (minimal initial; surges in stage 5), Na 5 (minimal initial; surges in stage 4), S 1 (very low — strict requirement for awaruite gate), CO3 5 (very low — strict requirement for brucite gate). The discriminator from all other scenarios is the COMBINATION of hyperalkaline pH + low S + low CO3 + high Mg+Si+Ca — rodingite chemistry is genuinely novel.",
        "Specimen aesthetic per Bernardini 1981 + Cabinet-grade Jeffrey collection records: cabinet-scale specimens (size_class pocket, 25-300mm), often matrix specimens with multiple species. Chrysotile fibers as silvery-white parallel-bundle veining (the asbestos host matrix). Cyprine vesuvianite as sky-blue to deep-azure tetragonal prismatic crystals — the world-reference Jeffrey aesthetic. Grossular as orange-pink hessonite or chromian green dodecahedra. Chrome-diopside as gem-grade emerald-green prismatic crystals. Pectolite as snow-white radiating sprays (the cabbage-petal aesthetic). Wollastonite as acicular white needle bundles. Prehnite as pale-green botryoidal aggregates. Datolite as colorless to pale-yellow gemmy monoclinic crystals — final-stage cabinet aesthetic.",
        "MINERALS NOT YET IN CATALOG that would extend the Jeffrey paragenesis: titanian-clinohumite (Ti-substituted humite-group sorosilicate; rare-but-documented at Jeffrey), perovskite (CaTiO3 — common in rodingite-syenite alteration), zoisite + epidote group (Ca-Al-Fe³⁺ sorosilicates, would benefit Jeffrey + many other rodingites globally), antigorite + lizardite (the other two serpentine polytypes besides chrysotile). Future add-mineral candidates beyond this arc.",
        "v116 candidate calibration notes per vugg-tune-scenario: this scenario is designed to fire the rodingite suite shipped v110-v114, but cation-budget routing may displace some firings or produce cascade extras. Expected possible misses: pectolite (Na may consume too fast or stay too low); datolite (B trace may concentrate too late in step sequence); awaruite (the STRICT O2<0.3 + S<5 + pH>=9 + Ni>=50 gate could fail to clear at seed 42). Expected possible cascade extras: tourmaline (B>=6 + Al>=8 + Na>=3 + SiO2>=60 at T 350-700 — overlaps with rodingite chemistry; if tourmaline fires in stage 5 when B + Na are both elevated, that's a geological surprise). vugg-tune-scenario v116 will run the probe-diagnose-adjust-verify loop on the actual seed-42 result."
      ],
      "initial": {
        "temperature_C": 380.0,
        "pressure_kbar": 1.5,
        "fluid": {
          "SiO2": 200,
          "Ca": 350,
          "CO3": 5,
